<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> County leaders travel to Washington, D.C. to express concerns overland claims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Sharing a concern over Indian land claims,
a delegation of officials from several upstate New York counties
planned to travel to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''The goal is to apprise our federal representatives of the
situation we're in ... We really think it's wrong that the federal
government is on the Indians' side,'' said Ralph W. Standbrook,
Cayuga County Legislature chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Other counties participating in the trip to Washington, D.C.,
are Madison, Oneida, Seneca, Greene and Sullivan, said Stephen J.
Acquario, general counsel to the New York State Association of
Counties. The group organized the trip after meeting Friday in
Utica.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an opportunity for us to work together as communities
from land-claim areas and forge together a unified response,'' said
C. Lee Hinkleman Sr., an Oneida County spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   County leaders have concerns about many of the same land
claim-related issues. Their concerns include the sovereign
government status given to Native American reservations, collection
of property and sales taxes on those reservations, gaming compacts
and the impact reservations could have on property values and
environmental and zoning laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's important we know which laws they have to abide
and which ones they don't,'' said Cayuga County Legislator Herbert
D. Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   County officials may need a better understanding of federal
laws, particularly those granting sovereignty to Native American
tribes, said Clint Halftown, a spokesman for the Cayuga Indian
Nation. Their sovereign status, for example, exempts Native
Americans, who live on territorial land from paying property taxes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also must side with tribes filing land
claims because the Bureau of Indian Affairs has a trust
relationship with this country's Native Americans and must act in
their best interests, Halftown said.
</P>
<P>
   County officials are making the trip two months after a federal
court jury in Syracuse recommended a $36.9 million award to the
Cayugas to compensate the tribe for 64,015 acres of lost ancestral
lands in Cayuga and Seneca counties. A final judgment on the award
will be made by a judge this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Madison and Oneida counties, the Oneida Indian Nation is
suing to regain title to 250,000 acres in those two counties that
the tribe claims was illegally purchased by the state. The U.S.
Supreme Court found in 1985 that the land was taken illegally and
ruled the Oneidas were entitled to compensation. Last week,
out-of-court negotiations collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Acquario said the local delegation hopes to meet with
Congressional representatives from the land claim areas, including
Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
