<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some deals emerge, but big-ticket items still outstanding  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Legislators trying to finish negotiating a
new state budget removed one troublesome item from their list of
outstanding issues -- an expanded prescription drug program for
older New Yorkers -- but a host of others were still unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some complicated areas out there,'' state Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver conceded Tuesday after he and Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno extended the legislative conference
committees by 24 hours until today. That was in hopes of compelling
the seven committees yet to complete their negotiations to finalize
deals.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very difficult process at this stage, but we're
making progress,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators on Tuesday announced a deal to expand the state's
prescription drug program for senior citizens. The deal will
increase participation in the Elderly Pharmaceutical Insurance
Coverage (EPIC) program from the current 115,000 to an estimated
215,000 within three years and cost the state an extra $180 million
when fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements on other major outstanding issues in the budget were
harder to come by, however, despite days of closed-door negotiating
by legislative staffers and aides to Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative sources said a proposed $3.8 billion bond act to
fund roads, bridges and mass transit -- and a five-year, $17.1
billion capital plan for mass transit which the bond act is a
crucial component of -- was causing agreements to stall on other
unresolved big-ticket items in the 2000-01 state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are trying to make a deal on a state budget worth
about $78 billion for the fiscal year which began April 1. Their
leaders want to have the spending plan adopted by the start of
Passover, on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding and simplifying the EPIC program had for days been
talked about by staffers for the conference committee discussing
health spending in the 2000-01 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement announced Tuesday, annual income limits for
eligibility under EPIC will be expanded from $18,500 to $35,000 for
senior citizens living alone and from $24,400 to $50,000 for
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Copays and fees charged seniors to enroll in EPIC will be
reduced, and the complicated rules of the program will be
simplified, the Senate-Assembly agreement stipulated.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers must be 65 or older to qualify for EPIC.
</P>
<P>
   Both the state Assembly and Senate had proposed improvements to
the program. The plan agreed to Tuesday is closer to the Senate's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Word of other deals came in dribs and drabs Tuesday from the
nine legislative conference committees discussing spending in
various sections of the budget like health, education and social
services.
</P>
<P>
   The committee responsible for mental health spending, for
instance, said it had agreed to restore $7.6 million not included
in Pataki's proposed budget to pay the salaries for 215 mental
health officials working in hospitals, clinics and other treatment
centers. The cost of those officials are ''shared'' between the
state and the counties, and advocates for the mentally ill lobbied
hard for their salaries to be restored.
</P>
<P>
   That committee said it also agreed to a 1.5 percent
cost-of-living adjustment for nonresidential providers of mental
health and alcohol and substance abuse services. That will cost an
additional $10.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The committee responsible for agriculture said it had again
restored state funding for research at Cornell University into
various farm hazards, including golden nematodes and the cow
disease known as ''blue tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   In other conference committees, legislators would say little
about the details of behind-the-scenes negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to get into numbers,'' Assemblyman Vito Lopez,
D-Brooklyn, said about talks over housing programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0012 </TRAILER>
