<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State releases zip-code tracking of breast cancer cases  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State officials say the latest step in a
$4-million-dollar cancer study could bring them closer to finding
out what causes cancer. But at least one lawmaker says it's just
another sidestep from the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Department on Tuesday unveiled a zip code
breakdown of breast cancer occurrences across New York that's the
first of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department officials cautioned the breakdowns provide
little insight into what causes the cancer that each year claims
the lives of 3,500 New York women. The statistics are only a tool
by which health experts hope to ultimately answer that question,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the questions that need to be asked are those we must
now ask,'' said state Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia Novello.
''Now we really need to start the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer groups were generally supportive and said the research
will provide them with better information to serve the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm actually very pleased,'' said Geri Barish, president of
One in Nine, the Long Island Breast Cancer Action Coalition. ''I
think that the Department of Health has done a tremendous job in
giving us some of the information that we have asked for.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can see your community and what's really going on there,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Brodsky, a Westchester County Democrat and chairman
of the state Assembly's Environmental Conservation Committee, said
that information could be much better.
</P>
<P>
   The maps are ''completely, completely bogus,'' he said. ''This
was always about identifying cancer clusters in neighborhoods ...
By doing it by zip code, they're hiding the truth from
neighborhoods all across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department attracted some criticism when it released
its first set of maps in December that showed a county-by-county
breakdown of breast, lung and colorectal cancer. Critics said the
county breakdown was too expansive an area to detect the clusters
of the disease that some believe can be produced by fouled drinking
water, pesticides, industrial chemicals or other factors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that they've released, we've dragged out of them,''
Brodsky said of the Health Department. ''It's taken them two and a
half years to come out with this?''
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is, the Republicans have done in 2 1/2 years what the
Democrats couldn't do in 20 years,'' countered John Signor, a
Health Department spokesman. ''These are the most accurate,
up-to-date maps in the nation and it's exactly what the cancer
advocates have been calling for. The fact is, Brodsky is guilty of
cancer map envy.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists like Blair Horner of the New York Public Interest
Research Group said the new maps are no better than any prior ones
if they're not followed up with immediate research into what causes
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''From our perspective, it's like this was a public health flare
shot up today that should attract researchers' attention,'' Horner
said. ''The sooner they start working on the next maps, the sooner
we can see if there are any consistencies in environmental
hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   The maps are based on the number of women who developed breast
cancer in each of New York's approximately 1,400 zip codes from
1993 through 1997. Regions were assigned colors that show that
number compared to the number of incidences the Health Department
expected to find.
</P>
<P>
   The maps show a higher-than-normal breast cancer rate in:
</P>
<P>
   --Northwestern Erie and southwestern Niagara counties
</P>
<P>
   --Eastern Monroe and western Wayne counties
</P>
<P>
   --Mid/Southern Rockland and western Westchester counties
</P>
<P>
   --Southern Westchester County
</P>
<P>
   --Manhattan, on the eastern side of Central Park
</P>
<P>
   --Southern Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   --Northern Nassau County
</P>
<P>
   --Southwestern Nassau County
</P>
<P>
   --Southeastern Nassau County and southwestern Suffolk County
</P>
<P>
   --The east end of Suffolk County, including Mount Sinai, Port
Jefferson and Coram.
</P>
<P>
   Novello emphasized that women should not worry about their
health just because they live in a high incidence area and that
subsequent research as part of the state's Cancer Surveillance
Improvement Initiative will help answer the questions raised by the
zip code maps.
</P>
<P>
   Novello and other officials were hesitant to discuss any
theories on what led to the increased cancer rates in some areas
and not others.
</P>
<P>
   They emphasized in the meantime that if women are worried about
their health, they should talk with a health care provider about
personal risk factors, find out if their relatives have developed
cancer and look at screening programs in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   www.health.state.ny.us
</P>
<P>
   www.cancer.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
