<HEADLINE> New York's top court upholds state's Internet predator law  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Prosecutors say a state Court of Appeals'
decision to uphold a state law designed to keep adults from using
the Internet to target minors for sex is a precedent for future
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is most definitely a precedent,'' Oneida County District
Attorney Michael Arcuri said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arcuri prosecuted the case against Thomas Foley, a 54-year-old
radio engineer from Grand Island who was the first person convicted
under the 1996 Internet predator law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased with the decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court's ruling represents a critical step forward in
protecting our children from pedophiles in the Internet age,''
state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's lawyer said the decision was disappointing for his
client, but important from a First Amendment standpoint, since the
court emphasized people must be aware they are communicating with a
minor in order to be charged under the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's important because it limits the scope of protected
speech that can be criminalized,'' Roger Wilcox Jr. said. ''That
does have significant ramifications for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox said he was talking with Foley about a possible appeal to
the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox had argued the law, which makes it a felony for a person
to knowingly use the Internet to invite or induce a minor into
having sexual relations, was overbroad, vague and unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals disagreed, saying the law does exactly what
it is intended to do.
</P>
<P>
   It took effect Nov. 1, 1996, and the state police Computer Crime
Unit conducted a sting operation beginning Oct. 28 and continuing
through November during which an officer posed as a 15-year-old
girl purportedly from Utica named ''Aimee.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley, using the screen name ''JustMee,'' began a sexual
conversation with the ''teen'' in a chat room called ''Kids of
Family Sex.'' Foley then sent the officer several pictures of
preteen girls engaged in sexual acts with men. He also told
''Aimee'' that he wanted to have sex with her and the two made
preliminary plans to meet in Buffalo, where the ''teen'' supposedly
had cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was arrested during his fifth and final chat with
''Aimee'' on Nov. 22, when police executed a search warrant and
found him typing on his computer. They got his name by serving a
subpoena on his Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   He was convicted of two counts each of attempting to disseminate
indecent materials to minors and promoting a sexual performance by
a child and sentenced to two to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed the decision to the Appellate Division of the state
Supreme Court, arguing people who unintentionally proposition a
minor could be charged, and that the law unduly burdens interstate
trade and imposes New York's community standards nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division disagreed with all three arguments and
the Court of Appeals concurred, pointing out the law only seeks to
punish those who ''intentionally'' target minors.
</P>
<P>
   The court also derided Foley's commerce argument.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hard pressed to ascertain any legitimate commerce that
is derived from the intentional transmission of sexually graphic
images to minors for the purpose of luring them into sexual
activity,'' wrote Judge Richard Wesley in the court's 7-0 decision.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the moral standards argument, Wesley wrote, ''It
is difficult to envision a situation where this conduct would not
be considered harmful to minors outside New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley is being held at the Gowanda correctional facility in Erie
County. He could be released from prison as early as May 18, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0013 </TRAILER>
