<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton blasts mayor; vows best campaign ever  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton was headed for
Buffalo today to visit a school and a senior citizens center, and
to highlight the fact that while she is campaigning upstate, her
Senate rival is elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said he was scrapping a
campaign trip today to Rochester and Buffalo in favor of attending
the New York Yankees home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the New York City mayor was a poor leader fit more
for the gridiron than the Senate. And, the first lady, who stumbled
early on in her first-ever campaign, bragged to more than 1,000
cheering public employee union leaders that she was ''going to run
the single best campaign that this state or any state has ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If you stick with me, and I know you will for this campaign,
then we will go into the Senate come January 2001,'' she told the
New York leaders of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, it marked her third day in the past five
campaigning in upstate New York, a generally conservative area of
the state that is expected to be a key battleground in her race
with Giuliani. Upstate represents about 45 percent of the vote in
statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani made a brief stop in Binghamton on Friday for a
news conference and a speech, Clinton has been crisscrossing
upstate New York. Aides said the mayor, an avid baseball fan who
particularly loves the Yankees, has never missed a Yankees or Mets
home opener.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had a tough couple of weeks. It might be good for him to
go to a game,'' Clinton told a news conference Tuesday in Albany
following her appearance a few blocks away before the union
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's poll numbers have been declining in recent weeks and
his earlier lead has vanished. One recent poll showed the first
lady with a slight lead while others have shown the contest to be a
statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm trying to reach as many voters as I possibly can in every
part of the state,'' she said when asked whether she was spending
more time around the state than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's cut the guy some slack,'' said Monroe County GOP
Chairman Stephen Minarik, whose wife had helped arrange the
Rochester women's event for Giuliani that got postponed. ''He's
already rescheduled the event'' for June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans weren't as forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ''If upstate is being asked to tolerate his liberalism, you
would think he'd at least tolerate missing opening day,'' said GOP
strategist Nelson Warfield, who is not involved in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wasn't cutting the mayor any slack, launching what may
have been her harshest attack of the campaign on his mayoral
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have leadership in that city that cares about people
who need an extra hand to get up and get going,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a mayor who perverts welfare reform,'' she told the
union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At her later news conference, Clinton said the Giuliani
administration has not done enough to train welfare recipients and
has shown a desire to ''cut people off'' from benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign issued a statement saying Clinton
''prefers to increase dependency'' when it comes to welfare. ''Her
position on welfare is consistent with her left-wing ideology over
the past 25 years,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   During her often fiery speech to union leaders, Clinton even
managed to bring up the Yankees, and the Mets, as she defended
herself against carpetbagger charges and questioned Giuliani's
temperament. ''If we were trying to recruit somebody for the
Yankees or the Mets we wouldn't care where she was born,'' the
first lady said. ''To carry that sports analogy probably a step too
far, some might think that the Senate was the big leagues and if
you're going to go there, you've got to be prepared to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't go out on the diamond and think that you're playing
football,'' she added. ''You've got to be able to work with your
fellow senators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
