<HEADLINE> Gay Republican group wants Plattsburgh mayor to be a healer withBush  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's only openly gay mayor is
trying to help smooth relations between Texas Governor George W.
Bush and a gay Republican group.
</P>
<P>
   Plattsburgh Mayor Daniel Stewart, a Republican and a supporter
of Bush for the presidential race, planned to meet with Bush twice
today and once more Thursday in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was criticized after he said last November he probably
would not meet with the Log Cabin Republicans, but last month
reversed that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has also changed course on Bush's snub. Last month he
defended Bush's decision not to meet with the group, saying the Log
Cabin Republicans had endorsed Arizona Sen. John McCain. Later
Stewart said Bush should have met with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tafel, executive director of the Log Cabin Republicans,
said that if anyone can bring his group and Bush together, it is
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having Dan there is very reassuring because he has shown that
he is very concerned about policies and making things better,''
Tafel told the Plattsburgh Press-Republican. ''There has been some
bruised feelings on both sides, and I think he (Stewart) can lay
the groundwork for future discussions, and he has the potential to
be a healer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who said he is one of about a dozen gay people meeting
with Bush, said that he will tell the governor that ''it is time to
make sure that all Americans are included in the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabins need to hold tight and let this meeting go
forward and let us try to accomplish getting open some doors so we
can all move forward as a unified party,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as well as his chief opponent, Vice President Al Gore,
does not support gay marriages. Stewart favors some civil-union
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Tafel said he hopes today's meeting can clear up Bush's position
on administrative appointments for gays.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he will appoint people to his administration who have
the same feelings he does on national issues, and I think he is a
fair man,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Bush) has to realize that it's not just gays. It's our
friends and families too that are affected by issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor denied that he was looking for a job himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every one of us that is going down there is being chastised as
looking for appointments, but that's not why I am going at all,''
Stewart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
