<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki, chief judge back court reform process  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- People navigating through the state's
complex and confusing court system would have a much easier time if
the multi-level courts are consolidated, Gov. George Pataki says.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's only so much you can do administratively. There comes
a time when you have to take the next step by legislation or in
this case constitutional amendment,'' said Pataki, who joined Chief
Judge Judith Kaye Tuesday at a news conference to promote court
reform at Albany County Family Court.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators of the state court system, which Kaye heads, have
long sought to consolidate the nine trial level courts into two
trial courts -- Supreme Court and District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye used a domestic violence case as an example to illustrate
the ills of the state's complex court system. She said a victim can
go to Family Court to get an order of protection. But to get a
divorce, she would have to go to the Supreme Court. After that's
done, it's back to Family Court for custody issues.
</P>
<P>
   And if the victim chooses the wrong court, she may have to start
all over again, Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time to change that sorry picture,'' Kaye said. ''As a
system, it's confusing, it's inefficient and it raises the price of
justice for citizens who just want to get their cases decided so
they get on with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki first said he supported court restructuring in his 1998
State of the State address, but he had not actively campaigned for
Kaye's reform plan prior to Tuesday's joint appearance with the
chief judge.
</P>
<P>
   Under the amendment proposal, the New York City Civil Court, New
York City Criminal Court, Civil Court and District Court would be
merged into a statewide District Court. The Supreme Court level
would include duties currently handled by the Supreme Court, the
Court of Claims, Family Court, Surrogate's Court and County Court.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also called for creating a fifth judicial department to
help relieve the heavy caseload of the Second Department, which
covers Brooklyn, Queens and Staten Island and Nassau, Suffolk,
Westchester, Dutchess, Rockland, Putnam and Orange counties.
</P>
<P>
   In order for a constitutional amendment to win approval, both
houses of the state Legislature must pass it in successive terms,
followed by voters in statewide referendum ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said there is still time this year for the Assembly and the
Senate to pass a restructuring plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''This should be the year, this must be the year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't do it this year, the earliest we'll be able to do
this will be in 2003, and that would be a tragedy for the people of
New York,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly in 1998 passed legislation to reform the
state's court system and is now ''waiting for the Senate majority
to act,'' said Assemblywoman Helene Weinstein, a Brooklyn Democrat
who chairs her chamber's judiciary committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's version of the constitutional amendment also
called for transfer of $40 million from the state's abandoned
property fund to provide legal representation to poor New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said increasing 18-B fees, or ''assigned counsel
fees'' should be included as part of a court reform package.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only do we change the flow chart, but we should also
provide the resources,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned counsel fees now total $40 an hour for in-court work
and $25 an hour for out-of-court representation. Critics say that
fee schedule is outdated and that court-appointed lawyers only make
a fraction of what private defense lawyers command.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0015 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telestra Aims for Asia Alliance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Telstra Corp. announced Wednesday it is
in an advanced stage of preparing a memorandum of understanding
with Hong Kong's Pacific Century CyberWorks to form an Asia-Pacific
telecom alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would be Telstra's most significant expansion into Asia
and would give it new growth options outside the highly competitive
Australian telecom market.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century CyberWorks, which aims to use its satellite
technology to become the main broadband Internet service provider
in Asia, is a unit of Pacific Century Regional Development of
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Australian newspaper The Financial Review reported Wednesday
Telstra was preparing an Asian alliance worth $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that they are in talks with Cyberworks in Asia shows
that Telstra is now in a position where they realize there are
advantages in trying to build their business beyond the boundaries
of Australia,'' Jamie Spiteri, broker with Shaw Stockbroking Ltd.
in Sydney said.
</P>
<P>
   Trading of both companies' shares was halted. The Hong Kong
exchange cited a pending announcement ''in relation to a potential
partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century Cyberworks last month posted a net profit of
$44.5 million in the year ended Dec. 31, boosted mostly by its
Internet-related investments.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century CyberWorks, run by billionaire Li Ka-shing's son
Richard Li, announced in February it would buy Hong Kong's leading
telecom company, Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, in a deal that was initially
valued at $38.1 billion in stock or $35.9 billion in a combination
of cash and stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
