<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Change Said Needed in Labor Policy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore must change and become more flexible
toward labor policy, the city-state's deputy prime minister said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not just government policies which must change, but also
private sector companies and industries which must keep up as their
business moves, again and again,'' Lee Hsien Loong told delegates
at a trade union conference.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said preserving jobs was not always possible, and retrenched
workers needed to be retrained and employed in new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford to keep uncompetitive industries alive,
whether through government subsidies or by protecting our market,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee stressed the government's position on foreign talent, and
said that in order for the economy to thrive, Singapore needed to
continue bringing in overseas workers, despite opposition at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the reality. Our total work force is just over 2
million. Of these, Singaporeans account for 1.4 million, and
foreigners about 600,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had sent home the 600,000 foreign workers during the
(Asian financial) crisis, far from the economy recovering and
creating new jobs, it would have nosedived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
