<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crusading Nader: Third party candidate speaks at SyracuseUniversity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Consumer crusader and Green Party
presidential candidate Ralph Nader preached his message of
returning power to the people at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   The political mantra should be ''it's the citizens that matter.
It's the citizens who matter most,'' said the man behind Consumer
Reports and four decades of activism.
</P>
<P>
   Nader charged that his better-known opponents, Al Gore and
George W. Bush, are desperately trying to exclude third party
candidates, and issues that are important to voters, from the race.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime consumer activist told a Syracuse University
audience on Tuesday that the Democratic and Republican
front-runners do not have ''grassroots support'' and are in the
race exclusively because of the money behind their candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Nader also reacted to a Zogby poll showing a majority of voters
want a third party to participate in debates. He said the new poll
shows that Americans crave the discussion of more issues than Bush
and Gore have selected to dominate the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Politics should be about power -- who has it and who doesn't,''
Nader said, not the issues that Gore and Bush ''self-selected.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Nader feels the leading candidates are ignoring
is the taxing of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   If corporations were taxed properly, he said, another $200
billion would be in the public's hands.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Bill Gates, of Microsoft, has wealth equal
to 120 million people at the bottom of the economic scale.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to end corporate greed, and corporate fraud,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued reports of prosperity in America, Nader said,
libraries throughout the nation are closing.
</P>
<P>
   As debate season nears, the new poll by Zogby International
indicates that Nader could play an important role.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows that a majority of respondents wants to allow
potential third party candidates to participate in televised
presidential debates with Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, 54.9 percent said Pat Buchanan should be allowed
to take part if he is the Reform Party candidate, and even if he
doesn't meet the 15 percent poll support level. In contrast, 41.5
percent disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   The responses were similar for Nader, with 51.3 percent
supporting his being a part of the debates if he is the Green Party
candidate while 44.2 percent disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, Bush led Gore 45.8 percent to 42.2 percent
overall in the national head-to-head matchup, with 12 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   With Buchanan as the Reform Party candidate, Bush led Gore 43.6
percent to 41.1 percent, followed by Buchanan at 5.2 percent with
10.1 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   With Buchanan as the Reform Party candidate and Nader as the
Green Party candidate, Bush continued to lead Gore 42.9 percent to
38.5 percent, followed by Nader at 5.7 percent and Buchanan 3.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, of 842 likely voters, was conducted April 1-4 and
has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Nader has been involved in consumer issues for nearly four
decades. His book ''Unsafe at Any Speed'' in 1965, which focused on
the safety shortcomings of the rear-engine Chevrolet Corvair,
exposed practices of the automobile industry and led to the passage
of new motor vehicle safety laws in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   He is the force behind the groups Public Citizen and the
Consumer's Union, which publishes Consumers Report magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Nader also ran for president on the Green Party line in 1992 and
1996. In announcing his third candidacy, Nader said the United
States faces serious societal problems in health care, education,
labor, energy, and the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
