<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Semitic violence down nationally, up in New York, California  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Although figures showed that anti-Semitic
violence in the United States hit its lowest level last year since
1989, three major incidents that left 11 people shot indicate the
problem isn't dissipating, according to the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   ''The horrific acts of violence and extremism we have witnessed
in the last year overwhelm the statistics,'' ADL National Director
Abraham Foxman said Tuesday, when his group released its annual
report on anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that while such violence had decreased
nationally, there were increases in both California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Foxman said the national decline was mitigated by several
horrific incidents, including a pair in California: the firebombing
of three Sacramento synagogues, a shooting spree at a Jewish
community center in suburban Los Angeles, and the Chicago shooting
of six Orthodox Jews walking home from Sabbath services.
</P>
<P>
   Five people were wounded in the Los Angeles community center
attack.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, there were 1,547 acts of anti-Semitic
violence, harassment and hatred in 1999 -- down from 1,611 acts a
year earlier, a 4 percent decline. Overall, anti-Semitic acts were
down 25 percent over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited 868 acts of harassment, including verbal
intimidation, threats and physical assaults, and 679 acts of
vandalism, including property damage, arson and cemetery
desecrations.
</P>
<P>
   California saw an increase of 52 incidents last year, caused in
part by the June 17-18 synagogue arsons and the Aug. 10 community
center shooting. Both attacks prompted ''copycat'' incidents, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, there were 275 acts of anti-Semitism in California, up
from 1998's 223 -- a jump of 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the number of anti-Semitic acts was up 9 percent
last year, from 324 in 1998 to 352 in 1999. The increase took place
outside New York City, where the reported incidents were down six
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts reported a slight uptick in incidents, from 107 to
111. New Jersey and Florida, while both in the top five states in
number of incidents, experienced declines from 1998, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics for 1999 were compiled from the ADL's 30 offices
and from law enforcement. The ADL, founded in 1913, issued its
first report in 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0109 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Delays Slowing Farm Program  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SEEWER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- A delay in federal funding is keeping
farmers from participating in a program designed to block
pesticides from seeping into waterways and prevent soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
   The state is waiting for the U.S. Agriculture Department's share
of money so it can begin reimbursing farmers who plant trees or
strips of grass near streams. The ''buffer strips'' would help keep
chemicals from reaching northern Ohio's lakes and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all ready to get this going,'' Larry Vance, chief of the
state's division of soil and water conservation, said Tuesday.
''It's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservation Reserve Enhancement Program is slated to commit
$201 million over the next 15 years in Ohio. The federal
government's share would be about $11.1 million each year. The
state's share would be $33.5 million over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say it's crucial that this year's money be
available within the next few weeks so that farmers can plant the
trees and grass before summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to get those in before it gets too warm and too dry,''
Vance said. ''I don't think they understand that a lost week
converts into a lost year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's program is part of a national plan to have 2 million
miles of buffers by 2002. While other states have received federal
money this year, Agriculture Department officials say they are
still working on details for the Ohio payments.
</P>
<P>
   Vance said he has been told that the money has been approved,
but that federal officials are waiting to make an official
announcement, which could come within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, farmers are getting frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were told the funds were going to be there and they're
not,'' said Jared McClarren, a Fulton County farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are approaching the end of when we should be planting
trees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has 20,000 trees ready for planting that are sitting
in coolers, Vance said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio lawmakers have committed the $33.5 million to their 10-year
program that will pay farmers in 27 northern Ohio counties to use
strips of their land for the buffer zones instead of farming. The
state hopes to establish 100,000 acres of conservation buffers in
the Lake Erie region.
</P>
<P>
   Besides reducing pesticide and fertilizer runoff,
environmentalists say the program will improve Lake Erie's water
quality and restore wildlife habitats.
</P>
<P>
   It's a voluntary program, and farmers must use cropland or
pastureland to qualify. It will cover counties in the Maumee,
Portage, Sandusky, Huron, Vermilion and Black River watersheds.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LAPORTE, Ind. (AP) -- Last week's cold snap killed off most of
this year's apple crop in northern Indiana, where unseasonably mild
readings had lured flower-laden buds into early development.
</P>
<P>
   Apple growers and agriculture specialists said readings that
dropped into the lower 20s last Wednesday froze much of the
sensitive apple buds -- from those in large orchards to the backyard
apple trees.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the worst I've ever seen,'' said Mike Garwood of Garwood
Orchards, west of LaPorte.
</P>
<P>
   Garwood's family has been selling apples from their 200-acre
farm in rural LaPorte County since the 1930s. The orchard has
40,000 apple trees.
</P>
<P>
   But from cuttings he has made of his trees, Garwood estimates
that three-fourths of the buds will not bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Each fall, some 30,000 school children take field trips to
County Line Orchards in Lake County, either on pumpkin-gathering or
apple-picking adventures. This year, it looks like they'll be
plenty of pumpkins and few apples.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'll have to put it out in our newsletter that there
were no blossoms,'' said David McAfee, who operates the orchard
with his wife, Bonnie. ''We may have to put in more pumpkins.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimates his loss between 70 and 100 percent, but hopes
there will be at least a partial bearing of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   McAfee blames the apple loss on the Pacific Ocean's La Nina
phenomenon, which has brought an unseasonably mild winter to most
of the Eastern United States. The recent cold weather has been
short-lived, but it left its mark.
</P>
<P>
   ''The orchards are wiped out,'' said Porter County Purdue
agriculture educator David Yeager.
</P>
<P>
   He said the long warm spell caused the tree's bud bearing stems
to grow out instead of closer to the woody portion, where they are
usually protected from the cold at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Another spell of cold weather this weekend zapped the trees
again, along with sensitive trees and plants across a large portion
of Indiana. But northern Indiana's apple crop appears to have been
hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is part of the business,'' said Bonnie McAfee. ''The worst
part is people will get mad when you tell them they can't have any
apples.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeager said homeowners with apple trees can easily test to see
if they will have apples. They can take a sharp knife or razor
blade and slice in half the ''king'' bud -- the big bud in the
cluster of four other little buds.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is a brown spot in the middle, it's dead,'' Yeager
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
