<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Albanians Slowly Rebuilding  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Bejtush Popaj and his family fled
the country on foot when Serb forces began killing ethnic Albanians
in his village last year. Serbs then burned and plundered his home.
Now, after a winter of hardship, it's time to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Popaj was one of the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees who returned home last year after the 78-day NATO air
bombardment of Yugoslavia ended in June, driving out forces loyal
to President Slobodan Milosevic from the province.
</P>
<P>
   But home was nothing like he left it.
</P>
<P>
   The six-room, two-storied house where he, his wife, and his five
daughters had lived in this village, not far from the snowcapped
mountains of neighboring Albania, was a charred shell.
</P>
<P>
   ''They destroyed 40 years of my life in half an hour,'' said
Popaj, a 47-year-old English teacher who lost 28 relatives from his
village 50 miles southwest of Pristina in wartime atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 67 Bela Crkva residents shot or hacked to death
by Serb military forces. Most of them were killed March 25, 1999,
just hours before the first NATO bombings, the youngest only 2
years old. They are buried in the ''Martyrs' Cemetery'' on a nearby
hill.
</P>
<P>
   Popaj does not gladly talk about those horrors. Instead, he
concentrates on rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   The Popaj family is confined to living in two rooms whose only
furniture is a couple of thin mattresses. A new roof and a new rear
wall have been built, but most of the house is strewn with rubble
and blackened from fire. Huge sacks of U.S flour rations are stored
in the house and new window frames lie in the tent he and his
family lived in until January.
</P>
<P>
   Still Popaj's home is in better shape than many others. Kosovo
10 months after the withdrawal of Milosevic's forces still shows
the scars of nearly a year of fighting that provoked NATO
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Village after village displays rows of burned out and destroyed
houses. The hulks of charred cars destroyed in the fighting remain
on neglected streets, and skeletons of animals killed by the
fighting -- or through neglect --litter fields and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Most homes were incinerated by Serbs seeking to drive ethnic
Albanians from the province and destroy their property. After
NATO's air campaign ended in June, revenge-seeking Albanians also
carried out reprisal attacks on Serb property.
</P>
<P>
   International efforts in the wake of the violence were less
focused on rebuilding and more on survival -- the idea was to ensure
that the tens of thousands of returning residents had a least one
warm room to spend the winter in.
</P>
<P>
   But with the onset of spring, the focus has turned to wholesale
reconstruction. In Bela Crkva and elsewhere, piles of ruddy-orange
bricks, roof tiles wrapped in plastic, and mountains of timber are
lined up in the streets next to the rubble of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel safe here now,'' said Popaj, surrounded by his family
on a small plot of land next to the house. The village was shelled
by Serb forces in the summer of 1998 during a battle with the
Kosovo Liberation Army in the nearby town of Orahovac. Popaj
supported the KLA by giving fighters supplies and observing Serb
positions in the area.
</P>
<P>
   After the family returned, they dared not plant vegetables,
fearing the soil may have been mined.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as life slowly gets better, the family plans to sow water
melons.
</P>
<P>
   On the top floor of the house, there are loose electric wires
and rubble in one room. But there is also the smell of fresh timber
from doors and the roof rafters donated by humanitarian
organizations, and a new washing machine from his brother who lives
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Popaj's daughters still wake up crying at night. But in Kosovo,
he says, the basics are what count.
</P>
<P>
   ''The good thing is that we are alive. It is hard to crush the
spirit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
