<HEADLINE> ABC Wins Ratings Race, Again  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''ER'' isn't vulnerable yet.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ABC has stretched its winning streak in television's
prime-time ratings to 15 weeks, the network's ''Wonderland'' and
CBS's ''Falcone'' both faltered last week against NBC's popular
medical show.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC and CBS dramas had a combined viewership of barely more
than half of the ''ER'' audience on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 27 million people who had been watching ABC's ''Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire'' on Thursday, an eye-popping 20 million
changed the channel rather than watch ''Wonderland,'' Nielsen Media
Research reported. ABC announced Tuesday that it was pulling future
episodes of ''Wonderland'' from the air.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is taking the unusual step of airing nine ''Falcone''
episodes over eight nights. The opening night's average audience of
10.4 million people was respectable, but succeeding nights couldn't
match that.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the NCAA basketball championship game between Michigan
State and Florida had the lowest ratings since CBS began
broadcasting the college basketball championship in 1982. It was 18
percent under the previous low set last year.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's airing of the live drama, ''Fail Safe,'' with George
Clooney on Sunday night drew slightly lower ratings than the
average CBS Sunday movie. CBS was pleased, however, that the Cold
War drama drew far more male viewers to the network than usually
watch its sentimental Sunday fare.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, ABC had a prime-time average of 13 million viewers
(8.9 rating, 15 share), followed by CBS's 11.7 million (8.2, 14).
NBC had 10.4 million viewers (7.5, 13) and Fox had 7.6 million
(5.1, 9).
</P>
<P>
   UPN had 3.3 million viewers and the WB had 3.1 million, although
both had identical 2.3 ratings and 4 shares. Pax TV had 1.2 million
viewers (0.9 rating, 2 share).
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' won the evening news race with 9.7
million viewers (7.2 rating, 16 share). ABC's ''World News
Tonight'' had 9.2 million viewers (7.1, 15) and the ''CBS Evening
News'' had 7.6 million viewers (5.9, 13).
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of April 3-9, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were ''ER,'' NBC, 18.3; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
(Tuesday), ABC, 17.9; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday),
ABC, 17.2; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Thursday), ABC, 17.2;
''NCAA Basketball Championship: Florida vs. Michigan St.'' CBS,
14.1; ''The Practice,'' ABC, 13.7; ''Law and Order,'' NBC, 12.6;
''60 Minutes,'' CBS, 12.5; ''Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 12.1;
''Friends,'' NBC, 11.8.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0114 </TRAILER>
