<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Runoff Vote Sought in Peru Election  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori was hanging on the
edge of a questionable re-election victory while challenger
Alejandro Toledo demanded a second-round runoff to avoid social
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting ''Down with the dictatorship,'' about 30,000 Peruvians
rallied Tuesday outside the downtown hotel where Toledo issued his
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ''Alejandro Toledo will not lead disturbances or violence,''
said the 54-year-old economist-turned-candidate. ''But I should say
forcefully that we won't hesitate for one second to defend
democracy and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration weighed in with a
strongly worded appeal for fairness, telling Fujimori that the
United States expects a runoff and would question the legitimacy of
a first-round win.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian election authorities said final results from Sunday's
ballot would be released today.
</P>
<P>
   With 90.8 percent of the ballots counted, officials said Tuesday
that Fujimori had 49.96 percent of the vote and Toledo had 40.39
percent. Various other candidates split the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls and unofficial vote tallies by independent monitors
after the election had indicated Fujimori received significantly
less support and projected that he would not reach the 50 percent
plus one vote needed to avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   If neither candidate wins a majority of valid votes, a runoff
would be held in late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not accept the results if it does not go to a second
round, and if in this second round there aren't substantial changes
to the rules of the game,'' Toledo said while thousands of
supporters rallied outside.
</P>
<P>
   A gigantic red and white Peruvian flag was unfurled, blanketing
a mass of protesters, who passed it over their heads from one end
of the plaza to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ''The dictator will fall,'' they chanted, referring to
Fujimori's autocratic style of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred demonstrators, most of them students, broke from
the rally and marched nine blocks with the flag to the Presidential
Palace, chanting anti-Fujimori slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller demonstrations occurred throughout the day Tuesday in
cities across this Andean nation of 25 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori and his supporters had criticized Toledo for leading a
march to the palace that turned violent after the vote. But Toledo
said Tuesday that he had ''put the breaks on'' potentially
explosive protests in eight Peruvian cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to publicly ask Fujimori for a meeting with the
interests of the Peruvian people in mind, to find a solution to
avoid popular upheaval,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori made no public response.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old president denied any fraud at a news conference
Monday, his only appearance since the election. ''The process has
been clean, free and fair,'' he said. ''There were small incidents
that did not affect the process.''
</P>
<P>
   But details of voting irregularities continued to surface
Tuesday. Toledo's camp said that names of other candidates were
waxed over on ballots, allowing only Fujimori's name to be marked.
</P>
<P>
   Under Peruvian law, ballots are destroyed once the results are
recorded, making it nearly impossible to prove such allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's National Ombudsman Office, which had 1,316 poll monitors
at 875 voting centers, said there have been ''innumerable
accusations'' of irregularities, with the most general being the
distribution of copies of pre-marked ballots favoring Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   The Ombudsman Office also said that tests before the election of
the computer system used to tally votes detected ''demonstrable
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Stein, head of a team of monitors from the Organization
of American States, complained that his mission was denied access
to inspect the computer system on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Stein demanded an explanation for a 12-hour delay in the
delivery of the first official results, and questioned how election
officials tallied more than half the vote Monday after their
computer centers had been closed all night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
