<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activist to push bill forcing Wallingford to observe King holiday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The only Connecticut town that fails
to close its offices on Martin Luther King Day will get a visit
from the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will stop here April 26 to support a bill before the
Legislature that would force the town to honor the state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Appropriations Committee voted 39-6 in favor of
that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a national civil rights leader and King contemporary,
has also been invited to speak at the Capitol and to attend a
service honoring King at St. Paul's Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Mayor William Dickinson has said the controversy is
not about race, but a dispute with the town's labor unions.
Dickinson wants town workers to swap another holiday for King Day,
but union leaders want workers to get the day off as an extra paid
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson and union leaders are currently negotiating. Dickinson
could not be reached for comment Tuesday. A message was left at his
office by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Jan. 17 holiday this year, three people wearing Ku
Klux Klan hoods and robes walked along Main Street. On the holiday,
one of those people stood near the church hosting a celebration
honoring King.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson wants to do his part to push for statewide observance,
said Roger Vann, president of the state chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   ''From early on, he expressed interest in coming. It was only a
question of when,'' said Vann.
</P>
<P>
   Vann said he and others had hoped Jackson would come on April 4,
the 32nd anniversary of King's assassination in Memphis, Tenn., and
the day of the Appropriations Committee vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''His schedule did not provide for that, but we definitely
wanted him to come here before the end of the session,'' said Vann.
</P>
<P>
   The bill must clear the General Law Committee before reaching
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Alfred Adinolfi, R-Cheshire, has said the bill is unfair
because it singles out Wallingford. Before its vote, the
Appropriations Committee killed Adinolfi's proposal to require all
towns to close their offices on the holiday. Sen. Brian McDermott,
D-Wallingford has said he will push for that provision when the
bill is debated in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Jackson's second visit to Wallingford. Dickinson
marched briefly with Jackson in August 1991 when Jackson came to
town to bring attention to social and economic problems in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''He walked the town from the south end to the north end, and he
met a lot of people here, so I think he has a good impression of
Wallingford,'' said Rep. Mary Mushinsky, D-Wallingford, who
proposed the legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0122 </TRAILER>
