<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut officials investigating death of inmate in Virginiaprison  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) -- The state's corrections commissioner
says it was ''minutes'' before guards who witnessed a Connecticut
prisoner hanging himself entered his cell inside a Virginia prison.
</P>
<P>
   And that has some lawmakers questioning the safety of
Connecticut inmates who were transferred to Wallens Ridge State
Prison in Big Stone Gap, Va.
</P>
<P>
   David Tracy, 20, of Bridgeport, was found dead in his cell at
Wallens Ridge on April 5 with a bedsheet tied around his neck. A
guard reportedly saw him jump, fall or drop from the top bunk bed
in his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ''It did take some minutes to open the (cell) door. An officer
in a maximum security prison can't just open doors at whim,''
Department of Correction Commissioner John Armstrong said Tuesday.
''There are protocols and procedures that must be followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Lawlor, co-chairman of the Legislature's Judiciary
Committee, said those procedures may have cost Tracy his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''It takes a long time to suffocate if you hang yourself,'' said
Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East Haven, co-chairman of the Legislature's
Judiciary Committee. ''We need to know what happened between the
time of the fall and the time the guard entered the cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, Public Safety Commissioner Henry Lee and other state
officials returned from Wallens Ridge Monday after opening an
investigation into Tracy's death. Lee, a world-renown forensics
expert, observed the autopsy. He said Tracy died from a lack of
blood to the brain -- an injury consistent with a hanging suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Tracy wrote what appeared to be a suicide note on his
hand. He would not disclose details of the message, or other notes
left in Tracy's cell. Tracy, was a gang member serving a 2 1/2-year
sentence for selling drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''What was written in several locations clearly supports the
initial indication of this man taking his own life,'' Armstrong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy's body was expected to arrive at the Office of the State's
Chief Medical Examiner by Wednesday, where another autopsy may be
performed, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we first learned of the incident it was followed by
concerns and allegations of foul play,'' Armstrong said. ''All
indications are David Tracy took his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials say they will continue investigating the
incident, and will review the procedures at Wallens Ridge by
watching videotapes that recorded Tracy's death. Armstrong said the
state probe could take months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure that we are accurate and concise on the
findings,'' Armstrong said. ''If we have an issue that we want to
have further addressed, that will prolong the time frame.
</P>
<P>
   And Lawlor said that could include a federal probe.
</P>
<P>
   ''If their answers show some misconduct, or we're not satisfied
with some answers, we'll ask for a federal investigation,'' said
Lawlor, D-East Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is already investigating allegations of abuse made by
New Mexico inmates who were shipped to Wallens Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, about 480 Connecticut inmates have been moved to
Wallens Ridge. Gov. John G. Rowland and Armstrong say the transfers
ease overcrowding in Connecticut prisons and break up gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy's death, along with last month's shooting of three
Connecticut inmates with rubber bullets have prompted lawmakers to
call for the inmates' return.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounds as though there are enough problems occurring that
most people are agreeing hat Wallens Ridge is not the best place
after all,'' Lawlor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0123 </TRAILER>
