<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Haven tries to rebuild sports offerings  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- The Elm City, which has lost several
sports franchises and major events in recent years, is hoping for
an athletic renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the United Hockey League is expected to announce it will
bring a new team, the New Haven Blades, to the Coliseum this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   The news comes a year after the demise of the Beast of New
Haven, which ended play in the American Hockey League after when it
could not line up a major-league affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   New management at the Coliseum also is trying to lure the
Connecticut Pride, a Continental Basketball League basketball team,
from Hartford, and possibly an arena football team.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilot Pen Tennis Tournament has announced several marquee
names including Venus Williams and Monica Seles will play in New
Haven this year, two years after the city lost the men's event.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Double-A baseball team, the New Haven Ravens, is
giving the city another chance after threatening to leave because
of problems with their ballpark, 73-year-old Yale Field in
neighboring West Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the team drew a franchise-low 197,153 fans to 68
home games -- the second-worst attendance in the Eastern League.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens have long sought a downtown New Haven stadium. The
team talked last year with Springfield, Mass., about moving to a
new stadium there, but the plan was dropped amid court battles and
opposition from the Ravens' fellow Eastern League team, the New
Britain Rock Cats.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're committed to play at Yale Field and do the best we can
here. We've done a lot of things to improve the fan experience,''
said Bill Berger, assistant general manager of the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions include a ''Best Seat in the House'' promotion that
allows fans to sit in leather chairs, and the ability to rent a hot
tub to be placed later this spring in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry fans who do not want to wait in line for hot dogs and
other snacks can order concessions online before the game, and can
even specify what time they'd like the food.
</P>
<P>
   The concessions are picked up at a special window. Waiters
deliver online-ordered concessions to season ticketholders.
</P>
<P>
   Fans seem to be taking a wait-and-see approach to the new
efforts to attract them.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Haven can't seem to sustain a team here. I don't know what
the problem is. I guess attendance is a problem,'' said Jim Lucas,
a city resident who was enjoying a lunchtime beer at Playoffs, a
sports bar.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said he hoped the new sports teams could make a go of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of times, when you fail, you learn from those
failures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's geography can sometimes work against it. New Haven
residents are mostly fans of New York City sports teams, and the
city is close enough for area residents to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Many tennis fans attend the Pilot Pen as a warm-up to the U.S.
Open, which starts a week later in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A Connecticut-New York rivalry is the planned for the New Haven
Blades. The UHL already has four teams in New York, including a
team in Elmira that will also begin play this year.
</P>
<P>
   Quality of play is one step below the level of the Beast, and is
equivalent in the sports hierarchy to the Ravens' Double-A level to
Major League Baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0123 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0040 </DOCNO>
