<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State trains officials in mosquito battle plan  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTON, Conn. (AP) -- Municipal officials spent a day at boot
camp, where they were given tips on how to fight the enemy:
mosquitoes that carry strains of encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 local health directors, emergency management
coordinators, conservation directors and public works personnel on
Tuesday were asked to eliminate mosquito breeding grounds and
aggressively report animal deaths so the bodies can be tested for
infection.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, representing more than 60 cities and towns, were
told at a state-sponsored workshop that there is no way to predict
whether the West Nile-like strain of the virus will reemerge this
summer. Last year, seven people in New York died, dozens more were
sickened and more than 3,000 birds turned up dead in New York, New
Jersey and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   No human cases of the mosquito-borne viral infection were
reported in either Connecticut or New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is doubling the number of mosquito trapping sites
and spending $500,000 on larvicide. But municipalities also have a
role.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Andreadis, chief medical entomologist for the
Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station, said the state will
begin trapping and testing mosquitoes for the virus in June, adding
36 new locations to the 37 existing trap sites.
</P>
<P>
   The new sites will be located in Fairfield and New Haven
counties, where mosquitoes and dead crows infected with the virus
were found last year.
</P>
<P>
   The state will also hand out $500,000 for larviciding in 45
communities where the West Nile or eastern equine (EEE) strains of
encephalitis are likely to reemerge. While the West Nile virus was
found mainly in southwestern Connecticut last year, the discovery
of EEE created a scare in southeastern Connecticut in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're still not going to be able to get every one, but let's
kill the mosquitoes that could become adults,'' said Paul
Capotosto, mosquito management supervisor for the Department of
Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials were also asked to educate the public about the
need to clean out gutters, catchbasins, swimming pool covers and
anything else that holds standing water where mosquitoes breed.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Harrison, legislative liaison for Bridgeport, said the city
is in the process of cleaning out its 9,600 catchbasins. Last fall,
a caged crane at the Beardsley Zoo died from the West Nile strain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year, we had people calling on a daily basis saying, 'I
have a dead bird in my yard,''' she said. ''I don't think the
public is scared at this point ... but it's important to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   In Greenwich, where mosquitoes trapped at the Innis Arden Golf
Club tested positive for West Nile last September, officials are
sending every home and business in town copies of a brochure
outlining the town's mosquito management program and protective
steps people can take.
</P>
<P>
   ''Education is one of the most important pieces of combating
this virus, whether it's the state government, the municipality or
the residents,'' said Caroline Baisley, the town's health director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0123 </TRAILER>
