<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders in Havana Seek More Aid  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Complaining they have been left behind by the
global technology revolution, the world's poor nations are pushing
plans calling for more aid, fewer debts and a greater role in
international decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 heads of state or government and delegations from 80
other nations were to attend today's first summit in the 34-year
history of the Group of 77, which has swelled to a gathering of 133
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Draft resolutions prepared by foreign ministers urged ''the
establishment of a more just and fair international economic
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ''To those already enjoying them, the benefits of globalization
are clear: faster economic growth, higher living standards, the
rapid spread of new technology and modern management skills,'' U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Tuesday in a speech at the
University of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ''Many millions of people are excluded, left
behind in squalor not because they have been exposed to too much
globalization but because they have had too little or none at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders joining Annan are South African President
Thabo Mbeki, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, Indonesian
President Abdurrahman Wahid, Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez, and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The wide-ranging draft proposals call for a sort of new world
order that would share technological advances, increase aid and
investment, forgive debts and put poor countries on a more equal
footing with rich ones in determining how aid is used.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, whose country chairs the
G-77, told a news conference Tuesday that poor countries need more
resources to promote democracy and stability.
</P>
<P>
   In Nigeria, where his elected government replaced a military
dictatorship last year, ''we have just established a new
dispensation, a democratic situation where we want to do everything
right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo said that if he goes to villagers and tells them, ''I
wanted to give you water but I have to pay debts ... even though
the origin of these debts are dubious, and therefore I will not be
able to give you water ... they will say 'get away with your new
dispensation''' of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But he ruled out a ''Havana Club of debtors'' that would unite
to suspend debt payments, saying it would interfere with aid
transfers that some nations depend upon for part of their domestic
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The draft documents call for giving poor countries a greater
voice in development decisions by encouraging the United Nations to
take a bigger role in economic aid, rather than channeling it
through organizations controlled by rich nations.
</P>
<P>
   They also suggest easing patent restrictions that keep poor
nations from benefiting from new technologies and setting up
mechanisms to share inventions.
</P>
<P>
   The drafts urged preferential trade concessions for poorer
nations and freer movement of labor to match recent liberalization
of capital flows.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our peoples have run out of patience,'' Cuban Foreign Minister
Felipe Perez Roque told a meeting of foreign ministers Tuesday.
''For decades they have suffered broken promises and are today
living in an economic and social situation that is increasingly
serious and unsustainable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil rights panel preparing report on Giuliani, NYPD  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's New York Police
Department is expected to face sharp criticism from a
Democratic-tilting federal civil rights panel.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Civil Rights Commission is prepared to recommend that
an independent federal monitor oversee the police force, several
sources familiar with the commission's findings said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect it to be very critical,'' one source said Tuesday of
the pending report.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission has no enforcement powers but makes
recommendations. A draft copy of its report will be discussed at a
regularly scheduled meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is basing its findings primarily on a May hearing
it held in New York City in the wake of the police shooting of
Amadou Diallo and torture of Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and police Commissioner Howard Safir defended the
police at that hearing. But the Rev. Al Sharpton and other police
department critics described the force as out of control and called
for a federal monitor to be assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Civil Rights spokesman David Aronson declined to discuss the
draft report's conclusions and what, if any, recommendations it
contains.
</P>
<P>
   Established by the Civil Rights Act of 1957, the commission
produces reports for the president, Congress and other federal
agencies on how federal, state and local government agencies treat
individual and group civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has six Democratic and two Republican appointees.
Among them is Christopher Edley, a Harvard Law professor and a top
adviser to President Clinton on race. That has prompted speculation
in GOP circles that the commission report was being used as a
political tool to help first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in her
U.S. Senate bid against Giuliani. Aronson denied that Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's poll numbers have sunk in recent weeks largely
because of his handling of the most recent police shooting in New
York. After Patrick Dorismond, 26, was shot by police in March,
Giuliani released the victim's sealed juvenile record, which showed
he had been arrested at age 13.
</P>
<P>
   Recent commission investigations include police practices in Los
Angeles following the 1991 Rodney King beating. In the report that
followed that probe, the commission made the unprecedented
recommendation that the county district attorney be removed from
police abuse cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0145 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9-year-old girl raped by other students in school, police said  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hours after she was allegedly coerced into
having sex with an 11-year-old boy near a Manhattan school
staircase, a 9-year-old girl was raped by two 12-year-old boys in
the same area, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was not the first sexual assault to occur this year
at Community School 200 in Harlem, police said Tuesday. On March
30, a 7-year-old boy allegedly sodomized a 7-year-old girl,
according to police reports. The girl was hospitalized and both
students are undergoing counseling, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident occurred shortly after 1 p.m. Monday, in a
foyer area leading to a staircase inside the school, police said.
The attacks occurred after teachers combined the boys' sixth-grade
class with the girl's fourth-grade class, bringing the students
into contact, police said. The classes were merged when the sixth
grade teacher was absent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Margie Feinberg, a Board of Education spokeswoman, said the
classes were combined because the school did not have enough time
to get a substitute teacher for the sixth grade class.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-year-old boy somehow got the girl to leave the classroom
and go into the foyer area, where she was attacked, police said.
Upon returning to the classroom, the 12-year-old boys told the girl
they would tell on her if she didn't come with them into the foyer,
police said. The students left the classroom and the girl was
attacked again, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-olds ran away when they saw a school aide
approaching -- the aide summoned a school safety officer. The girl
then told the officer what happened and she was taken to Harlem
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old boys were charged with rape and sodomy, and the
11-year-old was charged with sodomy. Thelma Baxter, the school's
superintendent, was slated to suspend the boys for a maximum of
five days after their Family Court appearance, which had not
occurred as of late Tuesday afternoon, Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter spoke Tuesday with parents about the incident and safety
at the school. The city sent a crisis team -- made up of
professional counselors -- to counsel students and teachers at the
school, said Karen Crowe, another spokeswoman for the Board of
Education.
</P>
</TEXT>
