<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crash Victims Said Not Guinea Pigs  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Marine Corps' top general said he is
bothered that some family members of victims of last weekend's
Osprey aircraft crash believe the dead Marines were callously
sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   One grieving mother, Christina Mercier, said her son,
24-year-old Keoki Santos, had been uneasy about the Osprey, a
hybrid airplane and helicopter that critics contend is
technologically troubled.
</P>
<P>
   Santos, a rifleman assigned to the 1st Marine Division, was
among 19 Marines killed when the MV-22 Osprey carrying them on a
training mission nose-dived into the ground Saturday night while
trying to land at an airfield in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Marines' deadliest air crash since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ''They killed him,'' Mercier said. ''They wanted him to be a
guinea pig for these new airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. James Jones, commandant of the Marine Corps, said in an
interview Tuesday that family members deserve a clear explanation
of the Osprey and its history of extensive flight testing. He said
some have formed the mistaken view that the Osprey, which first
flew in 1989, is an experimental aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are certified airworthy aircraft,'' Jones said, on which
all tests have been completed. The Osprey that crashed was one of
four such aircraft participating in an exercise meant to evaluate
how they would coordinate with other Marine aircraft during a
real-life mission such as a hostage rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't put people at risk,'' Jones said. ''There is no such
thing as human guinea pigs in this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey that crashed came off the production line in January
and had 135 hours of flight time.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Fred McCorkle, the Marines' top aviation official, told
a Pentagon news conference Tuesday that Jones was deeply troubled
by comments suggesting that the fatal Osprey flight was a risky
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can tell you that his heart is broken that anyone feels that
way, and it's really because of misinformation,'' McCorkle said.
''These are operational aircraft that we plan on flying for years
in squadrons in the Marine Corps and are production aircraft and in
no way test aircraft. And we are trying to get the word out to the
families now to let them know that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle told a Pentagon news conference that flights of the
remaining Ospreys would resume unless the initial investigation
reveals a major mechanical or design flaw. In that case, the Osprey
fleet would be grounded, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've talked to a lot of people on this particular accident ...
and I've had nothing so far to lead me to believe that we would
have to (ground) them,'' McCorkle said. Flights of the four
remaining production-model Ospreys were temporarily halted
immediately after the accident at Marana, Ariz., as a gesture of
sympathy for the families of the 19 Marines killed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, McCorkle said, ''We have no indication what caused the
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle said that on Tuesday the remaining Ospreys resumed
taxiing and other ground operations. ''I think that we will return
to the air in the very near future,'' he said without mentioning a
specific date.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Marines' plan to resume flying Ospreys before
the crash investigation is completed, Pentagon spokesman Rear Adm.
Craig Quigley said, ''We are confident that the Marine Corps will
do the right thing and make the right decision as to when and under
what conditions flights will resume.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Tuesday, Jones also said blast from the
explosion of the Osprey that crashed rocked another Osprey that had
arrived at the airfield first and was hovering nearby about 30 feet
off the runway. The jolt caused the Osprey to make a hard landing,
but it was not damaged, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers -- Boeing Co. and Bell Helicopter Textron -- are
due to deliver 11 Ospreys to the Marines this year. McCorkle said
those 11 will cost an average of about $57 million apiece.
Eventually the Marines are to field 360 of them to replace aging
CH-46 helicopters. The Navy plans to buy 48, and the Air Force will
get 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
