<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glickman To Make Sugar Decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman says a
decision is near on whether the government should buy $100 million
worth of surplus sugar to prop up domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department is considering buying 250,000 tons of
sugar to give away overseas or to sell at a deep discount for
refining into ethanol, a gasoline additive.
</P>
<P>
   With domestic sugar prices down 25 percent from a year ago,
growers are threatening to forfeit to the government as much as
$550 million worth of sugar pledged as collateral on federal
marketing loans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to act fairly soon,'' Glickman said at a Tuesday news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the government's sugar program, including candy
makers and consumer activists, say the USDA should allow sugar
prices to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee, Richard Lugar,
said USDA never should have given loans to sugar farmers that
allowed for forfeitures.
</P>
<P>
   ''To compound that flawed decision with an unprecedented
sugar-buying bonanza is unjustified and should not be under
consideration,'' Lugar, R-Ind., said Monday in a letter to
Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   The government guarantees farmers a minimum price for domestic
sugar through the loan program and quotas on imports, but increases
in domestic production are making it difficult for USDA to control
domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
   Growers who put their sugar up as collateral for a federal loan
have the right to forfeit the crop to the government if prices fall
below the guaranteed price.
</P>
<P>
   The loan forfeitures could cost as much as or more than the
proposed sugar purchase, government analysts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0203 </TRAILER>
