<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norwood Steers Health Care Debate  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some call Rep. Charlie Norwood the ''ghost''
member of the congressional committee trying to reach a compromise
on health care reform. He's not physically on the panel, but is a
strong presence who spooks those who seek only moderate changes.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, R-Ga., attends most of the committee meetings, sitting
quietly in the back of the room, arms crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ''They all know I'm in there,'' Norwood said. ''Don't you think
for a minute they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, a dentist elected to Congress in 1994, has become the
key figure as Congress attempts to reach a compromise on a health
care bill. He has enlisted the support of Democrats and vowed to
fight any ''watered-down'' proposal. Even opponents concede
Norwood's opposition likely would kill any plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Norwood is almost going to have veto power'' on the measure
crafted by the committee, Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., recently
told a business group that opposed the House health care bill,
which Norwood co-authored.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood wants people with health insurance to choose their own
doctors and hospitals. And he wants them to be able to sue their
insurance companies, something opposed by House Republican leaders
and the Senate GOP, who say costly litigation would drive up
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood is a staunch conservative who generally is aligned with
the Republican majority. But he persuaded just under a third of his
GOP colleagues to vote for his reform measure last year. It passed
with near-unanimous support from House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   After the Senate passed its bill, a conference committee was
appointed. When House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., failed to
include Norwood on the panel, Norwood supporters cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unfair, and grossly so,'' said Rep. John Dingell, a
Michigan Democrat who co-authored the bill with Norwood. ''The
leadership deliberately stacked the conference, all of which is
morally wrong and raises serious ethical questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said he's not upset by the snub.
</P>
<P>
   ''A speaker can't afford to have too many rebels in his ranks,
or he can't govern,'' Norwood said, proceeding to rattle off the
numerous advantages of not sitting at the conference table.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd have to mind my manners. There would be protocol in there,
and I'd have to pretend to be grateful that I was on the
conference. From the outside, I can do whatever I need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said Hastert deserves credit for allowing the House to
debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''All he had to do was pick up the phone, and we would not have
had the debate at all,'' Norwood said. ''He let the House work its
will. It takes a good man to be able to do that. He knew when that
debate started we were going to win and he was going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how close the conference committee is to a
compromise. Conferees were to meet last Thursday, but they canceled
it so they could talk in private.
</P>
<P>
   Though Norwood isn't privy to the private meetings, his
supporters on the conference -- whose names he won't divulge -- have
told him there has been movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't have to be exactly my way,'' Norwood said. ''That's
not a reasonable request. I don't care what words they use or how
they phrase it, but the intent of the bill has to be there for us
to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pollack, president of Families USA, a consumer advocacy
group which supported Norwood's bill, said he is confident Norwood
will deliver the votes if the committee emerges with a palatable
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Norwood thinks a proposal is sensible, he will bring most
of his colleagues with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0203 </TRAILER>
