<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASNE Chief: Newspapers Too Distant  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The death knell of the newspaper business has
been rung before, and always prematurely, through the ages of the
telegraph, radio and TV.
</P>
<P>
   But while newspaper editors doubt the Internet will manage to
slay their business, either, they aren't taking the competition
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Good newspapers are going to be fine but the competitive
stakes are as high as they've ever been,'' William R. Burleigh,
president and CEO of E.W. Scripps Co., told the American Society of
Newspaper Editors on Tuesday at its annual conference.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur O. Sulzberger Jr., chairman of the New York Times Co. and
publisher of The New York Times, said newspapers have survived the
advent of other media because they have remained the best at
delivering news.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the paper in newspaper that defines us,'' he said.
''It's the news in newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sulzberger said, ''You can't really tell where you're
going,'' in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility of newspapers was commonly held out as their
best asset against the fragmentation of news and information
sources resulting from the explosive growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But that bond with readers has been frayed, according to an ASNE
study being released today that finds people perceive an aloofness
and bias in newspapers and think they make too many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Papers tend to hear frustration and anger when they ask readers
how their communities are portrayed, said N. Christian Anderson
III, ASNE president and publisher of The Orange County Register in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their mirror shows a different picture, and it says we have
not connected,'' he told the conference's opening session, in a
point geared especially to minority communities but meant for all.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we spend too much capital on coverage that shows
people living at the extremes of community issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he saw no symptoms that the newspaper industry
will be fatally stricken by online competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Still, over the long haul we must think and act differently,''
he said. ''We need to learn more about how our readers and would-be
readers live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary B. Pruitt, president and CEO of the McClatchy Co., said
that with the multiplicity of news and information sources,
''virtually every media outlet is losing share.''
</P>
<P>
   But the narrative power of newspapers will see the good ones
through, he predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian May Meet His Dad in D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno on Tuesday night
postponed a planned trip to Miami amid reports that Elian Gonzalez
would be brought to Washington for a meeting with his father.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest twist in Elian saga, a Cuban exile group held a
Capitol Hill news conference Tuesday night and announced that
Elian's Miami relatives would bring the 6-year-old shipwreck
survivor to Washington for a meeting with his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, at noon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly before midnight, Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle
who has been caring for Elian since he was rescued, emerged from
the house in Miami and declared that the meeting was off.
</P>
<P>
   He said Elian did not want to go to Washington, so no one from
the Miami family would go. The crowd erupted with cheers.
</P>
<P>
   A government official said that the Justice Department was still
trying to confirm that such a meeting would take place. An attorney
for the boy's father also would not comment on reports of a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
Maria Cardona, said efforts had been under way late Tuesday and
early Wednesday to arrange a meeting between the father and Elian's
Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''While no meeting is yet officially confirmed, we continue to
focus on trying to get all of Elian's family to communicate and are
trying to resolve this promptly and cooperatively,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official said the talks were continuing
into the early hours Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Mas Santos, chairman of the Cuban American National
Foundation, told reporters Tuesday night that Lazaro Gonzalez would
bring the boy to Washington for the long-awaited reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Mas said the meeting would be closed to all non-family members
except Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder and Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J. He said the meeting would occur at noon at a
place yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   ''After four and a half months, the private meeting that this
family has so yearned for with Juan Miguel Gonzalez tomorrow will
be a reality,'' Mas said. He said the family and the Justice
Department had both agreed to the details.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be at a neutral site, and there's basically
going to be a resolution of the situation,'' Jose Cardenas,
Washington director the Cuban exile group, told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was announced at a Capitol Hill news conference.
Torricelli did not attend the news conference, but his spokesman,
Richard McGrath, confirmed that the senator was involved in the
negotiations to bring the boy to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senator Torricelli, Eric Holder and Greg Craig (the father's
attorney) worked out the arrangements,'' according to a source
close to the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said Torricelli has been actively engaged in the issue,
but wouldn't confirm that a meeting had been arranged for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The senator has been working for a period of time to keep
discussions going between the family and the Justice Department,''
McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   A government official said Tuesday night that a Justice
Department letter to the Miami relatives has been drafted and
proposes that they transfer Elian at Opa Locka airport, near Miami,
on Thursday. That letter has not been sent and is on hold, pending
developments in Washington on Wednesday, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear late Tuesday to whom Elian would be transferred
Thursday under the government plan, but it would be either to Juan
Miguel if he goes to Opa Locka, or to another of Elian's
great-uncles, Manolo Gonzalez. The great-uncle would then fly with
the boy to another location to meet the father.
</P>
<P>
   If these sketchy reports about what might happen in Washington
Wednesday fall through, the government would then go ahead and send
the letter. It was because of the reports of a meeting that Reno
postponed her plan to go to Miami on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the ongoing discussions said it was
possible that the Miami relatives would travel to Washington with
Elian on Wednesday to meet with the father. This source said that
Juan Miguel's attorney, Greg Craig, had said that the father was
willing to meet with the Miami family but only if the boy was
transferred to him before that.
</P>
<P>
   Craig meet for two hours Tuesday afternoon with Reno and Holder,
and met the father Tuesday night at the home of Cuban diplomat
outside Washington. Craig left the house near midnight and refused
to answer questions shouted at him about the reported meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The source familiar with the discussions said that the plan was
for the Miami relatives to meet at noon in Washington with Juan
Miguel with no lawyers or government officials in the room, but the
source said Holder and Torricelli were supposed to be on hand in
the same building.
</P>
<P>
   This source noted that when the plan was announced Tuesday
evening, there was no mention of transferring Elian to Juan Miguel.
The source was unable to say whether this was because no transfer
was planned or because the Miami relatives and their allies did not
want to announce a transfer agreement until after they left Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, the Miami relatives asked to talk to the
father, but said they would only do so in Florida and added that
they would not relinquish the boy at such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's possible return to her hometown -- where Cuban protesters
have displayed signs depicting her with horns and blaming her for
the Waco confrontation -- would come at a crucial time in the Elian
case.
</P>
<P>
   His Miami relatives have resisted her goal of reuniting the
6-year-old boy with his father this week, balking at handover plans
and continuing to press their court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements were for the custody transfer were still being
worked out, said the official, who added that any meetings
involving Reno wouldn't alter the timetable being worked out for
Elian's return.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, who discussed the situation with the
attorney general in Washington on Tuesday, said Reno was ''very
willing to meet Lazaro and any member of the Gonzalez family and
wants to meet with community leaders in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Writers Alex Veiga in Miami and Jesse J.
Holland and David Ho in Washington contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
