<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Seeking Egypt Funds  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Egyptian authorities, unhappy with the
suggestion that a co-pilot may have deliberately crashed EgyptAir
flight 990, still will be asked to contribute to the cost of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt asked the United States to help determine the cause of
last October's crash and a prominent congressman said Tuesday he
will seek reimbursement for some of the expected $17 million cost
of the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian officials have angrily rejected suggestions that one of
the plane's co-pilots, who took the controls before he was
scheduled to do so, may have deliberately crashed the plane on Oct.
31, killing all 217 aboard including 101 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have found no indication of a mechanical or weather-related
event that could have caused the crash,'' National Transportation
Safety Board chairman Jim Hall said Tuesday in testimony for the
House Transportation aviation subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   He added that, while the cause remains undetermined, the
movements of the plane were ''consistent with a deliberate action
on the part of one of the crew members.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall told the subcommittee that his agency is recommending that
video recorders be installed in the cockpits of commercial
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Such a recording, he said, might have helped settle questions
about what caused the Boeing 767 to plunge into the ocean off the
Massachusetts island of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   He said the investigation has cost about $13 million to date. He
expects the final total to be about $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who was paying for the work, Hall said the money was
coming from the board's budget, adding that he planned to seek a
supplemental appropriation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Lipinski, D-Ill., wondered whether the Egyptian
government had been asked to contribute to this cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't made that request,'' Hall said. ''I didn't feel it
would be appropriate for me, heading the investigation, to make the
request.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski responded: ''I'll see to it that the request is made by
someone for whom it isn't inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank LoBiondo, R-N.J., quickly seconded Lipinski,
expressing surprise that Egypt hadn't been approached earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed in international waters, meaning the
investigation is the responsibility of Egypt, where the aircraft
was registered.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement sent to the subcommittee following the hearing,
the Egyptian Civil Aviation Authority said Egypt already had
offered to help pay for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over two months ago the government of Egypt offered Chairman
Hall financial support for the cost of the investigation. We were
informed that we would be contacted when this need arose. This
important point was not explained clearly at today's hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Hall's testimony, the Egyptian statement said it
was too early to rule out mechanical failure as the cause of the
crash or to determine that available data was consistent with a
deliberate act by a crew member.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee also raised the question of whether pilots
should receive psychological testing and whether standards need to
be tightened for ability to speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Associate FAA Administrator Thomas McSweeney said a general
psychological evaluation is a standard part of the semiannual
medical examination required for all commercial transport pilots.
</P>
<P>
   There was agreement on a need to be sure that foreign pilots
flying to the United States speak English.
</P>
<P>
   McSweeney noted that the International Civil Aviation
Organization recommends that English be used in international
flights. He said the FAA is working with that group to establish an
official glossary of terms to help avoid misunderstandings between
pilots and air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board: http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: http://www.faa.gov
</P>
<P>
   House Transportation Committee:
http://www.house.gov/transportation/
</P>
<P>
   Air Line Pilots Association: http://www.alpa.org
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir: http://www.egyptair.com.eg/
</P>
</TEXT>
