<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharif Appeals Hijacking Conviction  </HEADLINE>
By ZAHID HUSSAIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- Ousted Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
today appealed a life sentence from hijacking and terrorism
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a good chance to get the decision reversed,'' said
Sharif lawyer Azizullah Sheikh, who filed the appeal in the
provincial Sindh High Court. ''There are very serious flaws in the
judgment. There is a definite lack of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   An anti-terrorist court last week found Sharif guilty of
hijacking and terrorism but acquitted him of attempted murder and
kidnapping on Oct. 12, the day his dismissal of Gen. Pervez
Musharraf caused the army to seize power in Pakistan. Sharif was
accused of refusing to let a passenger airliner carrying Musharraf
and 197 others land in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   After gaining full control, the army ordered the aircraft to
land. The plane apparently had only seven minutes of fuel remaining
when it touched down.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's six co-defendants, including his younger brother
Shahbaz, were acquitted. However, the Musharraf-led government has
since filed several corruption charges against the men, who remain
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution also has said it will appeal the acquittals.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-terrorist court that conducted Sharif's trial was set
up during his term in power to hand out quick justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0215 </TRAILER>
