<DOCNO> APW20000412.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For at least one day, Giuliani chooses baseball over politics  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In the end, a couple of speeches upstate didn't
have quite the same attraction as the home opener of the reigning
World Series champion Yankees. Especially if you are Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of a campaign swing through Rochester and Buffalo,
Giuliani is headed for the Bronx today to take in opening day at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Long before I was a politician, I was a Yankee fan, what can I
tell you?'' the unrepentant mayor told a City Hall news conference
Tuesday. ''This is me. I'm a Yankee fan. I love the Yankees. I
haven't missed an opening day since I've been the mayor...I can't
imagine not being there when the Yankees opened, unless it was an
emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   And where will Hillary Rodham Clinton -- his rival for the U.S.
Senate and herself a self-proclaimed Yankees fan -- be that day?
She's opting for Buffalo, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was asked about Giuliani's schedule change, she
managed a good-natured dig at the mayor's campaign and slipping
poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had a tough couple of weeks. It might be good for him to
go to a game,'' Clinton said while campaigning in Albany on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's scheduling conflict arose after forecasts predicted
snow and rain for the city and baseball officials canceled
Tuesday's home opener against the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who like all die-hard Yankees fans had waited all
winter for the game -- which will include a ceremony celebrating the
team's World Series victory last year -- had cleared his schedule in
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the weather didn't cooperate and the mayor's schedule was
rearranged -- starting with the postponement of appearances before a
women's group in Rochester and a fund-raiser in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was seen as key because Giuliani has been criticized
lately for his lack of upstate campaign appearances. Recent polls
show that the mayor has surrendered his lead over Clinton and the
race has slipped into a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Stephen Minarik III, the Republican Party
chairman in Monroe County, which encompasses Rochester, said he
understood Giuliani's choice of a baseball game uptown instead of a
campaign event upstate -- even though his wife had been involved in
the planning.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is the mayor of the city of New York (and) the New York
Yankees are an institution within the city of New York, so let's
cut the guy some slack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davis, Erie County's Republican Party chairman, agreed,
saying Buffalonians would not hold it against the mayor come
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's doing the right thing,'' said Davis. ''I'm a big baseball
fan, I understand. People understand. Buffalo is a Yankees town
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added that the postponement of Giuliani's trip to Buffalo
gives him an opportunity to take in a home opener of his own: The
Buffalo Bisons, the Triple A affiliate of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Davis however, did have one minor regret. ''I wish he had
invited me to sit next to him at the Yankees game,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 0216 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0062 </DOCNO>
