<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo's Governor Defends Comments  </HEADLINE>
By MARI YAMAGUCHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo's outspoken governor today defended comments
in which he told Japanese troops to expect foreigners living in
Tokyo illegally to riot if a major earthquake strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Shintaro Ishihara's remarks stirred up a storm of protest. But
the governor -- well known for his nationalist, right-wing views --
said today that he has no intention of backing down.
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara said he was referring only to foreigners living
illegally in Japan and blamed the media for taking his comments out
of context.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why should I apologize?'' he said. ''Was there anything wrong
with what I said?''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a ceremony for army troops on Sunday, Ishihara said
foreigners living in Tokyo illegally have ''repeatedly committed
atrocious crimes'' and suggested the military should be on alert
because they ''could be expected to riot'' if a major disaster were
to hit the city.
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders were quick to distance themselves from
Ishihara's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea objected and North Korea called the statements
''heinous.'' About 700,000 Koreans live in Japan, making them the
largest minority. Many are descendants of laborers forced to work
here during Japan's colonization of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara's remarks were particularly insulting to Koreans here
because thousands were massacred after a 1923 earthquake because of
untrue rumors they had poisoned wells and were setting fires, the
Mainichi, one of Japan's largest newspapers, said an editorial
today.
</P>
<P>
   ''Surely, Gov. Ishihara has not forgotten that,'' the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also pointed out that foreigners did not riot
after a 1995 earthquake killed more than 6,000 people in the port
city of Kobe, despite a large foreign community in the city.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Ishihara also used a derogatory term for
people from Korea and Taiwan living in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Ishihara is trying to use foreigners as a scapegoat at
a time when many people are feeling insecure about the economy and
the political situation,'' Hitomi Yamamoto, a Tokyo assemblywoman,
said at a small rally outside City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara said today that he stood by his use of the word but did
not intend it to include Koreans or Chinese living in Japan
legally.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he reiterated that he considers illegal foreign
residents, ''which includes many Chinese,'' to be
''troublemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara's comments, though hardly mainstream, are not without
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have long cited ethnic and cultural homogeneity as
a factor behind the country's high degree of social order and
relatively low crime rates. Many fear a greater foreign presence
will disturb that, even though economists say Japan must accept
more immigrants to counter low fertility rates and fuel economic
growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0229 </TRAILER>
