<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Plans To Push Final Budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are ready to push a compromise
$1.8 trillion budget through Congress now that House-Senate
bargainers have resolved their differences over taxes, defense and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said Tuesday that having bridged their major
gaps, the House would vote on the fiscal 2001 spending plan on
Thursday, with the Senate voting later that day or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
compromise will allow a five-year tax cut of at least $150 billion
and up to about $215 billion. That is about $25 billion less than
the House approved and $25 billion more than the Senate provided.
</P>
<P>
   The budget will set aside up to $40 billion for the possible
creation of a new Medicare prescription drug benefit and other
overhauls in the health-insurance program for the elderly and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   But gone is Senate-approved language that would have let any
senator bring a prescription-drug bill to the chamber's floor by
Sept. 1 if there had been no prior legislative action on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The budget will also contain the Senate-approved figure of $311
billion for defense for 2001, $4 billion more than the House's
number and 7 percent more than this year.
</P>
<P>
   The budget sets overall tax and spending figures, but leaves
specifics for later legislation. It does not need President
Clinton's signature.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP budget also plans $1 trillion in debt reduction through
2005. It assumes spending increases for education, veterans and
biomedical research and unspecified reductions in other domestic
programs, but such decisions will await later bills.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Democrats say the GOP plan cuts taxes too deeply and
lacks sufficient domestic spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 0341 </TRAILER>
