<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sens. Push Transplant Proposal  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An effort by a
transplant-surgeon-turned-senator to broker a compromise on how to
distribute the nation's limited supply of donated organs to
transplant patients was set to move forward today, even as
negotiations continued.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, patients who live in the same area as
donors get the first crack at organs, even if a sicker patient
lives just outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has proposed requiring broader
sharing of organs and basing organ distribution on who is most in
need of a transplant rather than on geography. The Department of
Health and Human Services also wants to increase its authority over
the private company, United Network for Organ Sharing, that holds
the government contract to run the distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   But United Network and many transplant centers -- particularly
smaller hospitals -- fear that eliminating geographic barriers would
siphon away locally donated organs to other centers and jeopardize
their programs.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is which side should have the power to write rules
governing the distribution of organs, and what those rules should
be. Rather than a partisan issue, it generally pits lawmakers from
major recipient states that have large transplant centers against
those from high-donor states where patients now get transplants
fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., a former heart and lung transplant
surgeon, has attempted for months to settle the dispute between HHS
and the network.
</P>
<P>
   His still-evolving proposal would allow the transplant network
to write allocation policy. But if HHS and the private contractor
cannot agree, an expert committee would make the final policy
decisions, based on a set of guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Frist met Tuesday with HHS Secretary Donna Shalala and Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., to try to work out a compromise. Shalala
wants the guidelines to explicitly call for sharing organs over
much larger geographic areas, but Frist has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   No deal was reached in the meeting, but Senate staff were
continuing to talk. On Wednesday, the Senate Health, Education,
Labor and Pensions Committee was set to consider Frist's bill, with
or without a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a bipartisan group of senators hinted on Tuesday they
would block any legislation that allows organs to continue to go to
the closest patients rather than to the sickest.
</P>
<P>
   The House has backed United Network, passing legislation that
would strip HHS of its authority to set policy and overturn its
proposed new rules. The Clinton administration has promised a veto.
</P>
<P>
   The group, led by Sens. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., and Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., unveiled a proposal that essentially mirrors the
new Clinton administration regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your zip code has a lot more to do with your receiving an
organ than your state of health,'' said Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill.,
who joined Fitzgerald, Schumer and Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa.
''That's just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The senators said they would wait to see what Frist's final bill
looks like before deciding on a strategy. But they said that
anything that does not increase public accountability is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will pass a good bill in the United States Senate, or we
will pass no bill,'' Santorum said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,800 people die each year -- about 13 per day --
waiting for organ transplants. There currently are 68,530 people
waiting for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: United Network for Organ Sharing:
http://www.unos.org
</P>
<P>
   HHS Division of Transplantation: http://www.hrsa.gov/osp/dot
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
