<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan to reunite Elian Gonzalez, father on hold  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A government plan to reunite Elian Gonzalez
with his father at a Miami-area airport Thursday is on hold as
officials wait to see whether the boy's Miami relatives and his
father can arrange an exchange of their own, a government official
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Cuban exile group had told a Capitol Hill news conference
yesterday night Elian's Miami relatives would bring the 6-year-old
shipwreck survivor to Washington for a meeting with his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, at noon today.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly before midnight, Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle
who has been caring for Elian since he was rescued off the Florida
coast in November, emerged from his house in Miami and said the
meeting was off.
</P>
<P>
   He said Elian did not want to go to Washington, so no one from
the Miami family would go. A crowd outside erupted with cheers.
</P>
<P>
   A government official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Justice Department was still trying to confirm such a meeting
would take place. An attorney for the boy's father also would not
comment on the initial reports of a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
Maria Cardona, said efforts had been under way late Tuesday and
were continuing early today to arrange a meeting of the families.
</P>
<P>
   ''While no meeting is yet officially confirmed, we continue to
focus on trying to get all of Elian's family to communicate and are
trying to resolve this promptly and cooperatively,'' Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official said the talks were continuing
into the early hours today. But with the situation in flux,
Attorney General Janet Reno last night postponed a trip to Miami
she had planned for today.
</P>
<P>
   A government official yesterday said a Justice Department letter
to Elian's Miami relatives had been drafted and proposed they
transfer Elian at Opa Locka airport, near Miami, on Thursday. That
letter has not been sent and is on hold, pending developments in
Washington, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Mas Santos, chairman of the Cuban American National
Foundation, told reporters last night that Lazaro Gonzalez would
bring the boy to Washington for the long-awaited reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Mas said the meeting would be closed to all non-family members,
but that Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder and Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., would be just outside. He said the meeting
would occur at noon at a place yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   ''After four and a half months, the private meeting that this
family has so yearned for with Juan Miguel Gonzalez tomorrow will
be a reality,'' Mas said. He said the family and the Justice
Department had both agreed to the details.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be at a neutral site, and there's basically
going to be a resolution of the situation,'' Jose Cardenas,
Washington director the Cuban exile group, told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli did not attend the news conference, and his
spokesman, Richard McGrath, would only confirm the senator was
involved in the negotiations to bring the boy to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear late Tuesday to whom Elian would be transferred
Thursday under the government plan, but it would be either to Juan
Miguel if he goes to Opa Locka, or to another of Elian's
great-uncles, Manolo Gonzalez. The great-uncle would then fly with
the boy to another location to meet the father.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no meeting of the family in Washington today, the
government then would go ahead and send the letter. It was because
of the reports of a meeting that Reno postponed her plan to go to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Another source familiar with the ongoing discussions said Juan
Miguel's attorney, Greg Craig, had said the father was willing to
meet with the Miami family, but only if the boy was transferred to
him before that.
</P>
<P>
   Craig met for two hours Tuesday afternoon with Reno and Holder,
and met the father Tuesday night at the home of Cuban diplomat
outside Washington. Craig left the house near midnight and refused
to answer questions shouted at him about the reported meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The source said the plan was for the Miami relatives to meet at
noon in Washington with Juan Miguel with no lawyers or government
officials in the room, but the source said Holder and Torricelli
were supposed to be on hand in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   This source noted that when the plan was announced Tuesday
evening, there was no mention of transferring Elian to Juan Miguel.
The source was unable to say whether this was because no transfer
was planned or because the Miami relatives and their allies did not
want to announce a transfer agreement until after they left Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Writers Alex Veiga in Miami and Jesse J.
Holland and David Ho in Washington contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Miami relatives: http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
</TEXT>
