<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Kennedy Denies Guard's Claim  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL ZOLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Rep. Patrick Kennedy disputes a security
guard's claim that he grabbed and shoved her at Los Angeles
International Airport last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''When all the facts become public, people will see that the
press reports don't reflect what actually happened,'' Kennedy said
in a brief statement Tuesday night. ''I apologized for this
unfortunate incident at the time and continue to regret that it
occurred. I sincerely hope that this matter can be resolved soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Patton, 58, said Kennedy grabbed and pushed her the night
of March 26, after she told him his bag was too big to fit through
an X-ray scanner.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman, son of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., then
allegedly grabbed Patton's arm and cursed at her while ordering her
out of the way. Patton complained of injuries to her left shoulder.
She filed a battery complaint with police on or about April 1.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed against Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Patton, reached at her home Tuesday, said she was in pain but
declined further comment. She referred calls to her attorney, Paul
Trump, who did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have reviewed a surveillance video of the incident,
but have not made it public.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shows there appears to have been physical contact between
Ms. Patton and Mr. Kennedy,'' Los Angeles police Lt. Horace Frank
said. ''She said she was battered at a preboard checkpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides met with detectives Tuesday. Kennedy's
chief of staff, Tony Marcella, said Patton's attorney has
approached them hoping for a settlement. Marcella would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not forwarded the case to the city attorney, whose
office would determine whether to file charges against Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   William Lynch, chairman of the Rhode Island Democratic Party,
accused Patton of distorting the facts to profit at the
congressman's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ''She started to look at this thing and heard cash register
sounds in her head,'' said Lynch, who said he discussed the
incident with Kennedy two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said Kennedy had some ''inadvertent contact'' with Patton but
he did not grab or shove her, as she claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's resigned to the fact that because his name is Kennedy,
these types of things that ordinarily wouldn't mean anything are
totally blown out of proportion,'' Lynch said Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
