<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down72.56; Dow Up 99.05  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed at the start of trading today.
Technology shares came under pressure after a Goldman Sachs analyst
lowered his estimate for Microsoft's revenue in the last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 99.05 at 11,386.13.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 72.56 at 3,983.34, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 1.25 at 1,501.84.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 3 11/64 to 80 45/64. This morning, Goldman Sachs
analyst Rick Sherlund cut his revenue estimate for the company's
fiscal third quarter to $5.75 billion from $5.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund said in a research note that personal computer sales
during the quarter appear to have missed Goldman Sachs's earlier
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a further negative for sentiment in a poor tech
market,'' Sherlund said. Computer makers slumped on the news; Dell
fell 2[ to 53 5/16 and IBM fell 2 11/16 to 116 7/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund maintained his third-quarter earnings estimate on
Microsoft of 41 cents a share, compared with 35 cents a year ago,
noting that the lower revenue would likely be offset by gains in
the investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan rose 5 9/16 to 140 5/16, buoying the Dow. The
investment bank easily exceeded Wall Street's earnings estimates,
posting first-quarter profits of $3.37 a share. Analysts surveyed
by First Call/Thomson Financial had anticipated earnings of $2.81 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 130.29 million
shares, behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.73 to 508.40.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.5 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.3 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.3 percent.
</P>
