<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Probing Kaiser Permanente  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- State regulators are investigating
complaints that Kaiser Permanente requires psychiatrists to
prescribe depression and anxiety medications for patients they
haven't examined.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations are being investigated by the state Department
of Corporations, the Los Angeles Times reported Wednesday, and stem
from a lawsuit filed Monday by a former Kaiser psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas S. Jensen of San Diego has accused the health
maintenance organization of firing him for refusing to prescribe
medicine for patients he did not personally examine. He asked the
court to halt Kaiser's policy on such prescriptions, which are
often delivered at the behest of social workers or family
therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say prescriptions from absentee psychiatrists endanger
patients, threaten the public and violate the American Psychiatric
Association's codes of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was trained that you don't prescribe medicines for patients
you've never seen,'' Jensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser acknowledged its policy differs from standards generally
accepted by the psychiatric community. The company has 30 days to
answer the allegations in Jensen's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis Cook, coordinating chief of psychiatrists for
Kaiser's Southern California operations, said the policy allows
Kaiser psychiatrists to treat more patients.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's very ethical,'' said Cook, who added that no
injuries have resulted from Kaiser's medication policy.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrists can refuse to prescribe drugs if the case does not
seem to warrant it, Cook said. However, they must agree in
principle to prescribe drugs without examining patients if the HMO
believes there is an obvious prescriptive solution to a patient's
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are also given follow-up appointments with a
psychiatrist about three weeks later and instructed to phone Kaiser
if any side effects develop, Cook added. People with severe
psychiatric or psychological conditions must see a psychiatrist
before medication is prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser is the nation's largest not-for-profit health maintenance
organization, serving 8 million members in 11 states and the
District of Columbia. Almost 6 million of its patients are in
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
