<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 168.42; Dow Up 56.46  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks fell sharply for a third
straight session today after a Goldman Sachs analyst lowered his
estimate for Microsoft's revenue in the last quarter. Blue-chip
shares rose after a strong earnings report from J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index
was down 168.42 at 3,887.48. The index had dipped more than 200
points lower.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 56.46 at 11,343.54, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 9.81 at 1,490.78.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 4] to 79{. This morning, Goldman Sachs analyst
Rick Sherlund cut his revenue estimate for the company's fiscal
third quarter to $5.75 billion from $5.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund said in a research note that personal computer sales
during the quarter appear to have missed Goldman Sachs's earlier
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a further negative for sentiment in a poor tech
market,'' Sherlund said. Computer makers slumped on the news; Dell
fell 2| to 52 13/16 and IBM fell 2 11/16 to 116 7/16 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund maintained his third-quarter earnings estimate on
Microsoft of 41 cents a share, compared with 35 cents a year ago,
noting that the lower revenue would likely be offset by gains in
the investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's slide provided the latest catalyst for the ongoing
decline of the Nasdaq. The index, which set a closing record of
5,048.62 on March 10, has tumbled 23 percent since then, and is now
down 4.7 percent in the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's decline picked up steam last week, when the index
fell more than 400 points over the course of two wildly volatile
sessions. Now, analysts are divided on whether the index is headed
back toward its low point of about 3,650 or poised for a round of
bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, analysts say, the volatile action has brought
some welcome skepticism to the technology market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors will be more discriminating in their buying of
technology and Internet stocks,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief
market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan rose 3 5/16 to 138 1/16, buoying the Dow. The
investment bank easily exceeded Wall Street's earnings estimates,
posting first-quarter profits of $3.37 a share. Analysts surveyed
by First Call/Thomson Financial had anticipated earnings of $2.81 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 338.99 million
shares, behind Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 7.36 to 502.77.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
