<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ink Painting Exhibit Compelling  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN AFFLECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- The interplay of dark and light, pictures and
words. The portrayal of simple subjects, expressing a religious
path to enlightenment: birds, mountains, scholars.
</P>
<P>
   These elements fascinated artists in the Far East hundreds of
years ago and tie together a subtle but compelling new exhibit at
the Cleveland Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition of 33 pieces titled ''Ink Paintings and
Ash-Glazed Ceramics: Medieval Calligraphy, Painting and Ceramic Art
From Japan and Korea'' runs through May 28 and will appear only in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It's made up of 33 paintings and ceramic pieces from the private
collection of George Gund III, a businessman, philanthropist and
vice chairman of the Cleveland Cavaliers pro basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   The works date from the 14th century to the 17th century. They
don't represent a comprehensive artistic history of the period --
they're not meant to -- but they give the viewer a taste of themes
and techniques of the time, along with a few glimpses of the work
of famous artists.
</P>
<P>
   ''The paintings and calligraphy in this exhibition share two
fundamental characteristics: the imagery arises from a brush laden
with ink; and the ideas behind the imagery originate in Buddhist
religious thought,'' Michael R. Cunningham, the museum's curator of
Japanese and Korean art writes in his introduction to the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   To an eye more familiar with Western painting from the same era
-- the age in which Michelangelo and Leonardo da Vinci lived -- the
ink paintings seem austere.
</P>
<P>
   The scrolls on which the works are painted are weathered. The
tones of ink paintings, or suibokuga, are shades of gray and black.
</P>
<P>
   But the viewer quickly notices the fine brush work, which sets
off contrasts between light and dark, the love of nature that runs
through the work, and the beauty of the calligraphy that adds
artistic balance to the picture itself and carries a message to
complement the work.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also covers the period when ink painting gained
popularity in Japan, inspired by an influx of works from Chinese
Buddhist monks.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest piece in the collection is ''Geese in a Landscape,''
an anonymous painting with calligraphy by Issan Ichinei, a Chinese
monk sent to Japan as an unofficial emissary in 1299.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is simple, with an almost coarse quality in the
bands of ink which create a slanting sandbar at the bottom of the
hanging scroll.
</P>
<P>
   Three geese stand together on the sandbar in wonderfully
natural, almost vulnerable, poses: one with its neck raised to
honk, another preening, the third dipping its head toward the
water.
</P>
<P>
   The monk's calligraphy, meanwhile, in the middle right of the
work provides a counterweight to the geese, framed on the left by a
slim reed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's an inscription that really talks to the painted image
and vice versa,'' Cunningham said on a recent tour of the exhibit.
''It's this kind of painting that begins to develop in the 14th
century in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, the inscriptions and paintings could be used as tools
to bring enlightenment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A tougher natural image comes from another bird painting, ''Hawk
on a Tree Branch.'' It was done by Toki Tomikage, a samurai, who
celebrated the bird of prey's strength by putting it near the
center of the painting, feathers puffed out against high winds as
it perches on a dead branch.
</P>
<P>
   Again, lines of calligraphy provide visual balance and a verse
that begins with this image: ''It is a quiet place with a dead tree
and a cold rock. A majestic hawk is perched there, its thoughts far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the exhibit are four works by Ikkyu
Sojun, a brilliant and eccentric Zen monk who lived in the 15th
century. The unacknowledged son of an emperor, he was essentially
abandoned at a temple as a child to be raised there.
</P>
<P>
   A passionate man with deep religious convictions, Ikkyu grew
into a harsh critic of Zen monastic institutions, accusing them of
being corrupt. He was unafraid to openly defy Zen authorities and
conventions by frequenting big city inns and brothels.
</P>
<P>
   Ikkyu's vigor is captured in a gorgeous piece of calligraphy
called ''Reflections of Priest Foyen.'' Unlike many of the delicate
inscriptions in the exhibit, Ikkyu's characters are bold and
striking, as is the verse itself. The poet declares ''Life is a
mirage,'' and later says, ''Be it movement or stillness, coldness
or warmth. One's own shame and regret come from such delusions.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most accessible works in the exhibit are several
ceramics from Japan. The vessels, originally made for everyday use,
have a natural ash glaze that helped seal them and gave them an
attractive finish.
</P>
<P>
   They began to be collected as art objects in the 18th century
and, with their use of rough and simple decoration, would be at
home in a modern art fair.
</P>
<P>
   But like their ink painting counterparts, they reveal an
appreciation of natural beauty that flowered in medieval Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
