<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Esther Williams Still Buoyant at 77  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- The comedian Fanny Brice once
cracked about Esther Williams: ''Wet she's a star, dry she ain't.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment was to haunt Williams throughout her movie career.
Even though her underwater extravaganzas enriched her and MGM, one
ambition would continually elude her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to do a 'dry' movie,'' she recalls. ''I went to
(studio executive) Benny Thau and said, 'I would love to play in
''Cass Timberlane'' with Spencer Tracy; to act with someone of
Tracy's stature would be my dream. I can't spend my career with
Johnny Johnston and Peter Lawford.'
</P>
<P>
   ''And Benny told me: 'Esther, wet you're a star.'''
</P>
<P>
   For a dozen years in 16 aquatic-musicals, Williams sold millions
of movie tickets. Originally hired as MGM's answer to 20th Century
Fox's Sonja Henie, she eclipsed the skating queen in fame and
longevity. She proudly claims to have inspired a new Olympic sport
-- synchronized swimming, which was introduced in the 1984 Los
Angeles games.
</P>
<P>
   At 77, Williams' face is wider, her broad-shouldered body
heftier than in her bathing beauty days. But she retains the same
zest she exhibited in her movies.
</P>
<P>
   She continues with her line of swimsuits, in myriad patterns and
styles. She has her own Web site, designed by her computer whiz
son, Kim Gage, so she can keep in touch with fans. She tours the
lecture circuit discussing her life and career. She is tireless in
promoting her tell-all autobiography, ''Million Dollar Mermaid,''
which aroused a noisy reaction when published last September.
</P>
<P>
   Williams lives with her fourth husband, Edward Bell, a former
college professor and actor, now her business manager, in a
hillside house above Los Angeles' Coldwater Canyon. You can tell
it's a pricy neighborhood. Microsoft billionaire Paul Allen tore
down Rock Hudson's old house next door and is building his own
palace.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams-Bell house is traditionally furnished with
overstuffed couches, a crystal chandelier over the grand piano. The
clutter of photographs in a bookcase are mostly of Williams'
children (Benjie, Susan, Kim) and grandchildren. No sign of her
first three husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there's a swimming pool, one with an underwater
machine that simulates a river current. More exercise that way.
</P>
<P>
   As a nonstop talker, Williams ranks with her friend Debbie
Reynolds (they once planned a TV talk show together but dropped the
idea). She is -- has always been -- frank, sparing no one, including
herself.
</P>
<P>
   She also is unfailingly optimistic. Did that evolve from a happy
childhood?
</P>
<P>
   ''Not particularly,'' she says. ''After I was born, my mother
told my sister Maureen: 'This is the fifth one; you take her. I
don't want to raise any more kids, I want to get out in the world
and see what's going on.'
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother was ahead of her times. She was a psychologist when
there weren't many women psychologists. She got out of the house by
handing me over to Maureen. Maureen was a wonderful sister; she
taught me how to swim ...
</P>
<P>
   ''My father was so in love with my mother that he didn't care
what happened to his five kids. When we'd go to Daddy with a
problem, he'd say, 'Go talk to your mother; she has all the
answers.'
</P>
<P>
   ''A happy childhood? I made it happy because of my swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   Her swimming progressed from neighborhood public pools in Los
Angeles to training at the L.A. Athletic Club to a national
championship in the 100-meter freestyle, then three berths on the
1940 Olympics team. When the games were canceled because of World
War II, she sold and modeled clothes at I. Magnin's department
store.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old's first taste of show business came when Billy
Rose cast her to star with Johnny Weissmuller in the Aquacade at
San Francisco's Pan-Pacific Exposition. That attracted the
attention of MGM, which brought her to Culver City for a screen
test.
</P>
<P>
   She started the test with a young contract player, Dan Dailey.
Then the King himself, Clark Gable, strode onto the stage,
accompanied by his wife, Carole Lombard. He insisted on doing the
test with the dazed Williams, and he included three kisses. Then he
walked off, saying to Lombard, ''Well, baby, I told you I was gonna
kiss me a mermaid today.''
</P>
<P>
   After her debut in an Andy Hardy picture and a bit in ''A Guy
Named Joe,'' Williams made her big splash in ''Bathing Beauty,'' a
huge success. She would be spending much of the next decade in the
tank the studio built for her on Stage 30.
</P>
<P>
   Being the world's No. 1 mermaid had its hazards. She almost
drowned in an underwater scene when a set worker accidentally
closed off her only exit.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the matter of her co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Van Johnson, who made five pictures with me, didn't know how
to swim,'' she recalls. ''So I had to teach him, and in some of the
scenes I held him up with my hand under his back. Ricardo Montalban
was working out at a gym, and he wasn't buoyant. While I swam, he
was walking on a plank. People with dense muscles have trouble
swimming; I'll bet Arnold Schwarzenegger has that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunate in her career, Williams had less luck with husbands.
</P>
<P>
   She was not yet 18 in 1940 when she took time between Aquacade
shows to marry a handsome young medical student, Leonard Kovner.
The marriage was idyllic until MGM made her a contract offer. He
was opposed to her becoming an actress. He also refused to consider
having children. When he became physically abusive, she says, she
fled their tiny honeymoon home. A divorce followed.
</P>
<P>
   On the rebound, she fell for handsome, 6-foot-6 soldier Ben
Gage, who had been a band singer and Bob Hope's radio announcer.
They married after his discharge in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage produced three children, a partnership in a
restaurant and other ventures -- and mismanagement of Williams'
money affairs. Outwardly it seemed a perfect match: the tall,
smiling Gage and everyone's favorite mermaid. But there was private
conflict because of his drinking, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know that he would have a few drinks before we went
out together,'' she says, citing one gala dinner at the Beverly
Hills Hotel when Gage passed out and slid under the table.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was when I began my friendship with Fernando (Lamas),''
Williams said. ''He took me on the dance floor and said, 'You wanna
get him out of here; it's going to take some logistics.' It took
six waiters to remove him. Fortunately, this was before the
tabloids, so nobody took any pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams kept the marriage going as long as she could because of
the children. But she won a divorce in 1959, telling the judge:
''Your honor, I'm really tired of being what my husband does for a
living.'' He had managed to leave her $750,000 in debt to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Lamas had first impressed Williams when he was cast
opposite her in ''Dangerous When Wet.'' A former swimming champion
in Buenos Aires, he was her only costar to be an expert swimmer.
Their romance began after her second divorce and the end of his
tempestuous affair with Lana Turner. The marriage to Williams in
1969 was his fourth.
</P>
<P>
   As a husband, Lamas turned out to be funny, charming,
over-sexed, unpredictable and imperious. He demanded that she
abandon her career and devote herself to him. She agreed -- her
career was on the wane, anyway -- with the proviso that he cease his
lifelong pursuit of women.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage took a toll on Williams' relationship with her
three children.
</P>
<P>
   ''His reasoning was: 'I love little babies. But as soon as they
have an opinion, I want to get rid of them and let 'em live with
somebody else,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''His own tortured childhood made him want no other child to
have it any better. His father died when he was 1, his mother when
he was 4. Because of the paternal nature of Argentina, he was put
in the care of the paternal grandmother, who was, I believe,
certifiably insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamas limited her contacts with Benjie, Susan and Kim, and she
now calls him ''an overbearing dictator -- I think he was schooled
with Peron.'' Yet she stayed with him for 22 years and nursed him
through lymphoma until his death in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have developed a philosophy about why movie stars have such
a hard time having a happy marriage,'' Williams says. ''It's
because your No. 1 thought is how to do your job. The job is so
compelling and so draining, because you have all kinds of chances
of failing; the failure element is always looming.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need men under the wrong circumstances; things can't take a
natural evolution. You have a man who is slightly hypnotized by who
you are -- and maybe not slightly, but a lot. You're trying to find
the real one, and you're never presented with the real one.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams thought she had found the real one in Jeff Chandler,
with whom she starred in ''Raw Wind in Eden'' after she left MGM.
Her account of discovering that he was a cross-dresser proved to be
the most controversial part of her autobiography. Chandler's
friends and fans assailed her, claiming the late actor had no such
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   She sticks to her story:
</P>
<P>
   ''We went together for three years. If he had this aberration of
cross-dressing and it would be part of the marriage contract, I
would have to hear about that on the second date, not three years
later when we're very involved with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''The children loved him. What was I going to say to my two boys
and my daughter when their new daddy wanted to wear Mommy's
clothes?''
</P>
<P>
   Putting it in the book was a way of trying to understand it, she
says. ''Remember, in 1960, we didn't have all the psycho-babble of
today ...
</P>
<P>
   ''I loved Jeff. When I went up those stairs (in his house), I
did not know he was getting into flowered chiffon. I was going up
to tell him I would accept his marriage proposal. I've often felt
that when you've made your choice, life will offer you a visible
test of what it would be like. I've had several experiences where I
got to the edge of the cliff, then drew back. That happened with
Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Official Esther Williams Web site:
http://www.esther-williams.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Facts about Esther Williams' life and career:
</P>
<P>
   Born: Aug. 8, 1922, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming achievements: world records for 880 breaststroke relay,
medley relay; national champion in 100-meter freestyle; three
berths in the canceled 1940 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Show business debut: Billy Rose's Aquacade, San Francisco
Exposition, 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Film debut: ''Andy Hardy's Double Life,'' 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Major films: ''Bathing Beauty,'' 1944; ''Thrill of a Romance,''
1945; ''Easy to Wed,'' 1946; ''Fiesta,'' 1947; ''This Time for
Keeps,'' 1947; ''On an Island with You,'' 1948; ''Take Me Out to
the Ballgame,'' 1949; ''Neptune's Daughter,'' 1949; ''Duchess of
Idaho,'' 1950; ''Pagan Love Song,'' 1950; ''Texas Carnival,'' 1951;
''Skirts Ahoy,'' 1952; ''Million Dollar Mermaid,'' 1952;
''Dangerous When Wet,'' 1953; ''Easy to Love,'' 1953; ''Jupiter's
Darling,'' 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Marriages: Leonard Kovner, 1940-1945; Benjamin Gage, 1945-1959,
three children; Fernando Lamas, 1959-1982; Edward Bell, present.
</P>
<P>
   Autobiography: ''Million Dollar Mermaid,'' 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
