<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: Dove Awards  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Country cedes the spotlight to the
Christian music industry on April 20, when the 31st annual Dove
Awards will be presented at the Grand Ole Opry House. TV star
Kathie Lee Gifford will host the show.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford, co-host of ''Live With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee,'' last
played the famous hall in the late 1970s as a cast member of ''Hee
Haw Honeys,'' a short-lived spinoff of ''Hee Haw.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not what one would call a critical hit,'' Gifford said.
''However, it was a wonderful experience for me. It was my first
time working in Nashville.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gospel Music Association's Dove Awards give Christian music
the opportunity to reach for an audience outside its subculture, so
it will be firing its big guns for the syndicated show.
</P>
<P>
   Sixpence None the Richer, a Christian band that crossed over
with the pop hit ''Kiss Me,'' will debut its new single ''Melody of
You.'' Dolly Parton will join Gifford for ''Only My Pillow Knows,''
a duet from Gifford's new album ''Born for You.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stars include dc Talk, Steven Curtis Chapman, CeCe Winans
and Jaci Velasquez.
</P>
<P>
   For the mainstream audience, producers have booked Parton,
Alison Krauss and teen opera star Charlotte Church.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had been a member of the Gospel Music Association years ago
and had done several gospel albums years and years ago,'' said
Gifford, who is taking over hosting duties from John Tesh.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always loved gospel music, even though it wasn't the kind
of music I was making any more. I'd been away long enough, is
really what it came down to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The show will be held on the first anniversary of the shootings
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. Michael W. Smith, last
year's best new artist, will perform ''This Is Your Time,'' which
was inspired by the shootings. The song is nominated for song of
the year, pop-contemporary recorded song of the year and short-form
music video.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is also nominated for best artist, songwriter and male
vocalist.
</P>
<P>
   Other nominees for best artist are Chapman, Avalon, Point of
Grace and Sixpence None the Richer.
</P>
<P>
   Toby McKeehan of the trio dc Talk received the most nominations:
six individual and four with the group.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman has nine nominations, including best artist and male
vocalist.
</P>
<P>
   Sixpence None the Richer received three major nominations --
group of the year, artist of the year and Leigh Nash as female
vocalist of the year -- as well as special event album for
''Streams.''
</P>
<P>
   County music legend George Jones and Vestal Goodman are
nominated for the song ''Angel Band'' on the ''Vestal and Friends''
album in the country recorded song category. Bluegrass artist
Krauss is nominated in the same category for ''I Give You to His
Heart'' on ''The Prince of Egypt-Nashville'' album.
</P>
<P>
   And in the country album category, veteran performer Glen
Campbell is nominated for ''A Glen Campbell Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said she is happy that Christian singers have a national
showcase, even if it is just once a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have people like Michael W. (Smith), Sandi Patty and Kathy
Troccoli on our show quite often -- not often enough for my taste,''
said Gifford, who is leaving ''Live With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee'' this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Dove Awards are nominated and selected by the 5,500 industry
workers who are members of the Gospel Music Association. The GMA
was formed in 1964 to promote the Christian music industry.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Web site for the Dove Awards: http://www.doveawards.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
