<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Spotlights Texas Music  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE MABIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Tex. (AP) -- Stewart Ramser couldn't believe the idea
hadn't been tried before: a high-quality magazine dedicated to the
multifarious music of the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has become Ramser's reality.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Music made its national debut earlier this month, hitting
newsstands from California to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the things we want to do is cover all of the genres we
have, like Tejano. We have an article about a rap band from Fort
Worth in the second issue. We want to really be diverse. Texans
like to read about other Texans, regardless of their musical
tastes, I believe,'' Ramser said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramser got the idea for the magazine while he was on vacation in
Hawaii in 1998. He was relaxing on a beach when a radio station
began playing an entire set from Texas artists.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of a sudden, it just hit me. I had been out of the state
six-plus years and I missed a lot of great music, and there wasn't
really a place to turn to read about it,'' the Fort Worth native
said. ''There were great local papers and market-free weeklies, but
those aren't distributed outside of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rolling Stone or the other national publications would
occasionally cover Texas artists, but I knew that there was this
thing with Texas music that was very diverse and that a lot of
people were very passionate about. So it just hit me that I'm going
to write a business plan about a magazine and also tie in a Web
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramser -- neither a musician nor a journalist -- cashed out his
retirement plan, emptied his savings, borrowed from friends and
poured his soul into Texas Music.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 people subscribed to the first issue, released in
Texas and a handful of other states in January. Houston-born Lyle
Lovett was on the cover that sold more than 38,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Ramser, who holds business degrees from the University of Texas
and UCLA, remembers the debut well.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were doing it all ourselves. We got into two stores Friday
afternoon. I told myself, 'I'm not going to go back and bug the
stores every day to see how my magazine's doing.' Sunday, I go back
to the two stores and they sold out immediately. They were like,
'Get us twice as many.'''
</P>
<P>
   Issue No. 2, featuring the Flatlanders, was distributed
nationwide and to more than 1,000 subscribers in 40 states. About
50 more subscribers a week are signing up, Ramser said, and
national advertisers are coming slowly but surely.
</P>
<P>
   The next national issue will be released in June.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Music is as diverse as the state itself. Topics range from
a behind-the-scenes look at ''Austin City Limits'' to a profile of
the Texas A&AMP;M University marching band. Big names with Texas ties
are scattered throughout the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Cosgrove of the music TV show ''Austin City Limits'' said
Texas is a great stage on which to shine a national spotlight
because of its diversity of artists.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's any state that's worthy of a magazine that covers
music within its borders, it's Texas,'' Cosgrove said. ''Because of
the diversity of the state and the styles that have influenced
music that's happening today, I mean you can go down to the border
toward Mexico and you've got a story. You can go toward Louisiana
and you've got a story there. You can go to Lubbock and you've got
a story. ...
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost like what we do, only it's on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Texas Music Web site: http://www.texasmusiconline.com
</P>
</TEXT>
