<HEADLINE> Gardner Recalls 'The Fantasticks'  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Actress Rita Gardner remembers a time when ''you
could put on a show in an attic or a basement and people would
come.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was experimental and interesting, and it was cheap to do a
show off-Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Gardner recalls ''The Fantasticks,'' which cost
$16,000 to produce 40 years ago. It is still performed at the
Sullivan Street Playhouse in Greenwich Village, where it opened on
May 3, 1960, and is one of the longest running plays in history.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, best known for the song ''Try to Remember,'' is
based on Edmond Rostand's ''Les Romanesques.'' The story is a
reverse ''Romeo and Juliet'' in which parents invent a feud to
bring their children together.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Orbach, now one of the stars of NBC's ''Law and Order,''
played the part of El Gallo, the narrator. Gardner was the girl and
Kenneth Nelson was the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''My favorite song was at the end, a duet with the boy, 'They
Were You.' I sang 'Round and Round,' 'This Plum Is Too Nice' and
'Soon It's Gonna Rain.' Jerry Orbach started with 'Try to
Remember.' I don't think any critic chose that song as special. But
singers started to record it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fantasticks'' was not Gardner's first off-Broadway show.
She was in ''Hex,'' an Amish musical, and ''Nightcap,'' a revue of
Jerry Herman songs. When she read about ''The Fantasticks'' in the
trade publication Variety, she thought it was a revue. She called
to request an audition, but producer Lore Noto told her ''the
writers know who they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I convinced him to hear me sing,'' she said. ''It was in
(composer) Harvey Schmidt's apartment. They had me come back and
back again, and I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   In rehearsals, the cast had a good time but was unsure what the
whimsical show was about, Gardner said. ''Nobody thought about how
difficult it would be or would it last. We just were putting on a
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the reviews.
</P>
<P>
   '''Ernest in Love,' a musical based on 'The Importance of Being
Earnest,' got all the raves. It came and went,'' Gardner said.
''Noto was told to close. He wouldn't, even if we played for five
people. The theater has 150 seats. I think tickets were $5.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came when ''The Fantasticks'' played in East
Hampton on nearby Long Island for a week in August. ''All the posh
people saw it and told their friends. Audiences started to grow,''
she said. ''The album started to help the show, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner left the show after nine months for a part in the movie
''One Plus One.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, her career has had its ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   ''You get into that middle place where you're too old for some
things and too young for some things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She performed in ''Eleanor, an American Love Story'' at Ford's
Theatre in Washington, D.C., playing the part of Franklin
Roosevelt's mother Sara. She toured as the mother in ''Kiss of the
Spider Woman'' for eight months. Her favorite roles in regional
theater were in ''The Workroom,'' a story about the Holocaust, and
''Lucy's Lapses,'' about Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just did a 'Law and Order' where I played a grandmother who
sells used undergarments on the Internet. It's very funny. I would
never get that 10 years ago. Now I'm reaching the point I can play
those parts. It's a lot of fun. I don't mind at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner has put together a cabaret act, ''Try to Remember -- a
Look at Off-Broadway,'' which she performs each Saturday night
following ''The Fantasticks.'' She talks about the original cast
and sings ''Fantasticks'' songs, including ''Try to Remember.'' She
also performs songs from other off-Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought, 'Why not do something I was a part of and try to
make it enjoyable for people?''' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
