<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of April
16-22:
<TEXT>
<P>
   65 years ago: Fredric March and Charles Laughton starred in the
film ''Les Miserables.'' John Carradine had a bit part as a student
radical.
</P>
<P>
   40 years ago: Elvis Presley took a train from Memphis, Tenn., to
Hollywood to begin work on the film ''G.I. Blues.'' Presley had
recently been discharged from the Army.
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: Rod Steiger starred in Sidney Lumet's ''The
Pawnbroker.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Hollies played a weeklong engagement in New York with
Little Richard and others. The band also recorded an appearance on
the popular TV show ''Hullabaloo.'' It was the British rock group's
first visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: Reggae musician Bob Marley played at Zimbabwe's
Independence Day celebrations in Salisbury, calling it the greatest
honor of his life.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Entertainer Eddie Murphy taunted homosexuals and
others protesting his appearance at Brandeis University. The
protestors had called on Murphy to donate his $60,000 comedy-show
fee to the Boston AIDS Action Committee. ''Ha,'' he said onstage at
the university before a crowd of 2,000. ''Besides, it's only
$50,000.'' About 75 people demonstrated outside as Murphy told
jokes inside.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: An anti-apartheid concert was held at London's
Wembley Stadium honoring black South African leader Nelson Mandela.
Performers included Peter Gabriel, Neil Young, Tracy Chapman, the
Neville Brothers and Bonnie Raitt. A sellout crowd of 72,000
attended the concert to celebrate Mandela's release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   And Paul McCartney sang old Beatles hits for 130,000 fans jammed
into Rio de Janeiro's Maracana soccer stadium. McCartney performed
a number of his own songs before launching into ''The Long and
Winding Road'' and ''Hey Jude.'' Fans lit cigarette lighters,
cheered wildly and sang along as McCartney performed.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: Leonardo DiCaprio played musician-poet Jim
Carroll in ''The Basketball Diaries.'' The 20-year-old DiCaprio
said he chose the part because he felt he could explore the
character.
</P>
<P>
   And pop singer Michael Jackson welcomed 46 youngsters on a visit
to his 2,800-acre Neverland ranch in Los Olivos, Calif. The
children were winners of an essay contest about the world's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken one year ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''Welcome to church!'' -- Singer Dolly Parton, as she dedicated
the Southern Gospel Music Hall of Fame and Museum at her Dollywood
theme park in Pigeon Forge, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
