<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 155.22; Dow Up 74.15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Swooning technology stocks, led by a slide in
Microsoft, deepened the Nasdaq composite's retreat Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Microsoft is a component of the Dow industrials,
Wall Street's best-known indicator was holding on to gains as money
continued to flow into traditional blue-chip issues.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was down more than 4.5 percent, or by 3.81\ a share,
at 80.06\ in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq briefly fell as much as 203 points and was down
155.22, or 3.8 percent, at 3,900.68 by early afternoon. The
technology-focused index now has fallen almost 23 percent from its
peak of 5,048.62 reached on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 74.15 at 11,361.23.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft prices fell after Goldman Sachs analyst Rick Sherlund
cut his revenue estimate for the software company's fiscal third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a further negative for sentiment in a poor tech
market,'' Sherlund said.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been slumping amid worries that upcoming
first-quarter earnings reports won't justify the high prices of
tech issues.
</P>
<P>
   Among Old Economy stocks, J.P. Morgan rose sharply on a strong
earnings report, buoying the Dow.
</P>
