<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Audio reviews from The Associated Press:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Sao Salvador'' (Putumayo) -- Ricardo Lemvo &AMP; Makina Loca
</P>
<P>
   ''Sao Salvador'' is an instantly engaging trip through
Afro-Caribbean pop. Ricardo Lemvo gleefully mixes styles: Cuban son
with Congolese rumba, merengue with soukous. His love of American
soul comes through, as well, especially on the deeply funky
''Nganga Kisi.'' The emphasis in his Afro-Cuban mix, though, is
almost always on the African elements, and the band is tight enough
to go instantly wherever Lemvo points it.
</P>
<P>
   You do not need to be an ethnomusicologist to appreciate ''Sao
Salvador.'' All you need is ears to listen, and it would help to
have a foot to tap, too. The overall effect is joyous and
wonderful, making ''Sao Salvador'' riotously addictive, essential
for fans of Afro-pop and a good starting point for those interested
but not sure where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''Orfeu'' (Nonesuch) -- Caetano Veloso
</P>
<P>
   Caetano Veloso is sometimes called the Brazilian Bob Dylan, and
is renowned as one of his country's greatest singer-songwriters.
''Orfeu'' is a soundtrack, full of orchestrated (and occasionally
over-orchestrated) pieces, so it won't really prove that point to
those unfamiliar with his work. Still, it's an interesting and
frequently lovely piece of work, full of gently swaying bossa novas
and raucous sambas, a sort of sampler of Brazilian music. The
highlight is the breezy, bittersweet ''Os Cinco Bailes da Historia
do Rio,'' which is simply Veloso's voice and Heitor TP's lyrical
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''Good Things'' (Tone-Cool) -- Toni Lynn Washington
</P>
<P>
   Toni Lynn Washington is the real deal, a soul-blues singer with
a rich, smoky voice she uses to mine each phrase for all its
emotion. The tight, funky horn arrangements propel ''Good Things,''
but it's Washington's vocal prowess that really raises it a cut
above. ''Good Things'' should appeal to fans of Ruth Brown, Aretha
Franklin or other great soul singers.
</P>
<P>
   --By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''Get Over It'' (Atlantic Records) -- Mr. Big
</P>
<P>
   Hard rock fans relish Mr. Big's new release ''Get Over It.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitar whiz Richie Kotzen, who replaced the popular Paul
Gilbert, has filled his shoes quite nicely and has added a touch of
his own style to the band. The track ''Static'' has Kotzen giving
his best Hendrix impersonation and Billy Sheehan backing him with
dazzling bass licks.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, ''Get Over It'' finds singer Eric Martin moving from
the pop-metal scene of the '80s to a more personal, insightful
style. ''My New Religion'' addresses the need for one to accept
life's risks in order to find reward.
</P>
<P>
   ''Get Over It'' is Mr. Big's first U.S. release in five years,
but the band has not lost a beat.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Gerard O'Leary, Associated Press Writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
