<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 156.18; Dow Up 120.07  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks fell sharply for a third
straight session today after a Goldman Sachs analyst lowered his
estimate for Microsoft's revenue in the last quarter. Blue-chip
shares rose after a strong earnings report from J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite
index was down 156.18 at 3,899.72. In volatile trading, the index
had dipped to a loss of as much as 200 points in early trading and
again at midday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 120.07 at 11,407.15, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 3.30 at 1,497.29.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 4] to 79{, depressing the Nasdaq and hemming in
the Dow's advance. This morning, Goldman Sachs analyst Rick
Sherlund cut his revenue estimate for the company's fiscal third
quarter to $5.75 billion from $5.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund said in a research note that personal computer sales
during the quarter appear to have missed Goldman Sachs's earlier
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a further negative for sentiment in a poor tech
market,'' Sherlund said. Computer makers slumped on the news; Dell
fell 2{ to 52 15/16 and IBM fell 4} to 114] on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund maintained his third-quarter earnings estimate on
Microsoft of 41 cents a share, compared with 35 cents a year ago,
noting that the lower revenue would likely be offset by gains in
the company's investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's slide provided the latest catalyst for the ongoing
decline of the Nasdaq. The index, which set a closing record of
5,048.62 on March 10, has tumbled 23 percent since then, and is now
down more than 4 percent in the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's decline accelerated last week, when the index fell
more than 400 points over the course of two wildly volatile
sessions. Now, analysts are divided on whether the index is headed
back toward its low point of about 3,650 or poised for a round of
bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, analysts say, the volatile action has brought
some welcome skepticism to the technology market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors will be more discriminating in their buying of
technology and Internet stocks,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief
market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports continued to drive the market. Enron rose 3
7/16 to 71} after reporting first-quarter earnings of 40 cents a
share. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 37 cents a share. The
strong report confirmed expectations that energy companies will
show the sharpest profit growth for the recently ended quarter.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan rose 5| to 140], buoying the Dow. The investment
bank easily exceeded Wall Street's earnings estimates, posting
first-quarter profits of $3.37 a share. Analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial had anticipated earnings of $2.81 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial stocks rose amid expectations that they, too,
will report strong earnings. American Express rose 7 11/16 to 152~.
</P>
<P>
   Clorox rose 2] to 39 11/16 after the company secured an
arrangement with online grocer Webvan to sell its products over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 765.46 million shares
at midafternoon, compared with 678.21 million at the same time
Tuesday. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by a margin of nearly three
stocks to one.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.90 to 504.23.
</P>
</TEXT>
