<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papers Take Steps To Restore Trust  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Newspapers have found that readers will
forgive them their trespasses if they own up to them.
</P>
<P>
   Making corrections more prominent and making efforts to connect
up close with readers -- even letting them help edit stories -- are
identified in an editors' study as ways to rebuild trust with a
public that sees papers as aloof and even biased.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Newspaper Editors, three years into an
examination of the profession's credibility, heard Wednesday from
editors who took unusual and sometimes elaborate steps to involve
readers in what they do, part of an ASNE project.
</P>
<P>
   ''Readers and non-readers alike voiced overwhelming faith that
these kind of credibility initiatives could achieve their goal,''
says the study, released at the ASNE convention.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts were aggressively promoted so readers would get the
message. But editors were cautioned not to expect quick and
sweeping results, because steps to bring a paper closer to the
community are bound to involve only a small portion of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Eight newspapers acted as test sites last year, following up on
national surveys that found most readers perceive papers to be
disconnected from their concerns, acting for profit or an agenda
instead of the community interest and making too many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Among steps taken in response:
</P>
<P>
   --Florida Today in Melbourne invited citizens to work alongside
copy editors, proofreading stories before they went into the paper.
</P>
<P>
   --In Texas, the Austin American-Statesman set up public meetings
to get people to dissect what appeared in the paper, then published
their observations.
</P>
<P>
   --In Colorado Springs, Colo., The Gazette formed ''audit teams''
from the community to advise on coverage of blacks, Hispanics,
women and youth, and reported their findings in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   --The Daily Press in Newport News, Va., sent teams to
neighborhoods not in the grip of any particular crisis and profiled
one neighborhood a month.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also held weekly editorial board meetings in
restaurants, where citizens could attend, and has set aside space
each day, separate from letters to the editor, where readers can
gripe about coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors were initially shocked when reporters showed up and
said, ''We're here because nothing's happening ... we're just here
to talk about your lives,'' Editor Will F. Corbin told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Other papers experimented with ''reader advocates'' and
redoubled efforts to admit and fix mistakes. They found prominent
corrections improved good will.
</P>
<P>
   ''Errors can be forgiven but confession is required,'' said
research consultant Judy Pace Christie.
</P>
<P>
   Polling indicated almost eight in 10 readers feel better about a
paper when they see corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that the selection and placement of stories often leave
readers suspecting bias, several editors tried publishing
explanations of how such judgments are made, sometimes putting
those accounts on the front page.
</P>
<P>
   But that step had limited success; while it engaged some
readers, others confused the explanations with news summaries. As
well, there was a limit as to how much people wanted to know about
a paper's innards.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, a reader advocate's position rotates among the staff
at the Sarasota Herald-Tribune and serves as a one-stop shop for
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Editor Janet Weaver said she also paid bonuses to news
assistants for avoiding mistakes in compiling listings. But she
gave up on that, in part because the newsroom felt accuracy was
basic to the job and not something to be rewarded on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregonian in Portland stopped emphasizing the sensational
aspects of its crime coverage and broadened its examination of
youth issues by bringing more young voices into the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Inquirer focused on its New Jersey readership,
making coverage of South Jersey a ''paper within a paper.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the San Jose Mercury News in California, an accuracy and
fairness checklist became required reading before most stories
could get into the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Something as simple as double-checking phone numbers that appear
in the paper can pay off, said Executive Editor David Yarnold.
''Credibility is in large part about getting back to basics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1510 </TRAILER>
