<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Push for Victims' Rights  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers should pass a constitutional
amendment to protect victims' rights and give a voice to those the
system ''failed to protect,'' supporters urged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote on the measure after the Easter
recess. Supporters Wednesday urged support as the nation marked
National Crime Victims' Week.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment will give crime victims ''certain
basic rights,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz and one of the measure's
sponsors. ''The scales of justice need balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif. and also a sponsor, said the
Constitution guarantees 15 basic rights to defendants ''but there
is not one word written in the U.S. Constitution on behalf of crime
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would ensure that victims have the rights to
reasonable notice of court proceedings and an offender's release or
escape, the right to attend and be heard at legal proceedings and
the right to an order of restitution.
</P>
<P>
   A similar proposal is pending in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Roper, co-chair of the National Victims Rights Amendment
Network, said she was locked out of the judicial process when her
22-year-old daughter Stephanie was kidnapped, raped and murdered 18
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unlike those who make the criminal choice, you don't have any
rights,'' Roper said.
</P>
<P>
   The measures would need to gain two-thirds majorities in the
House and Senate as well as ratification by three-fourths of state
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   The White House supports an amendment but has expressed concern
that the language of the current proposals may impede law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov/home/thomas.html?57,18
</P>
<P>
   The bills are S.J. Res. 3 and H.J. Res. 64.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
