<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unilever Bulks Up, Then Slims Down  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE STANLEY, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Like the guy at the diner who orders a hot-fudge
sundae and a diet cola, Unilever on Wednesday gobbled up the Ben &AMP;
Jerry's ice cream business even as it downed Slim-Fast Foods.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.6 billion spending spree raises the question of whether
these deals will create corporate indigestion at a time when the
Anglo-Dutch Unilever is cutting down its lineup of consumer brands
and eliminating 10 percent of its jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unilever is a bit schizophrenic,'' said Andy Smith, a consumer
products analyst at Schroders investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's trying to downsize its portfolio on the one side and yet
trying to boost performance in its core brands on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, the consumer products company behind such household
names as Lipton, Vaseline and Pepsodent, plans to slash 25,000 jobs
over five years as it tries to reverse a slump in profits and its
share price.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has headquarters in England and the
Netherlands, announced the cuts in February as part of a global
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Unilever disclosed plans to concentrate on just
400 of its current 1,800 brands. Among the businesses under review
are fragrance and cosmetics unit Elizabeth Arden and its European
bakery operations.
</P>
<P>
   However, restructuring doesn't mean that Unilever is swearing
off acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically what they admitted is that the portfolio is too
complex,'' Smith said after an analysts' conference call with
Unilever executives. ''It has too many brands, and what they're
trying to do is cut out the losers and keep the winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Unilever's wide array of brands includes Calvin Klein
fragrances, Dove soap, Close-Up toothpaste and Q-tips swabs. It
also is the world's largest ice cream company, with brands
including Good-Humor, Breyers, Popsicle and Klondike.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the company's $2.3 billion buyout of Slim-Fast Foods
Co. and $326 million purchase of Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade Inc. are
''strategically very sensible acquisitions'' over the long term,
even though they are likely to dilute Unilever's earnings per share
on a short-term basis.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to agree. Unilever's stock jumped 4.8 percent
from Tuesday's close to end trading in London at about $6.90 a
share, based on current exchange rates. That helped Unilever shares
recover some of the ground lost in recent months as investors
abandoned stodgy industries such as consumer goods for the glitter
of high-tech shares.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are the overwhelming consumers of Slim-Fast products,
but the brand of diet products has strong potential in Europe,
Smith said. Slim-Fast sales increased by 20 percent last year,
though operating profit margins slipped from 22 percent to 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's plugs a gap for Unilever in the premium end of the
ice cream market. At the same time, it gives Unilever a strong
product with which to compete against Nestle's Haagen-Dazs brand,
the analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever hopes to trim its overall costs by 4 percent to 5
percent over the next five year as part of its $5.3 billion
restructuring drive.
</P>
<P>
   The company's 1999 net profit slipped 5 percent to $2.97
billion, in spite of a 2 percent rise in sales last year to $43.7
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1527 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
