<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 182.10; Dow Up 89.97  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks fell sharply for a third
straight session today after a Goldman Sachs analyst lowered his
estimate for Microsoft's revenue in the last quarter. Blue-chip
shares rose after a strong earnings report from J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was down 182.10 at 3,873.80 and appeared
poised for its first close below 4,000 since Jan. 31. In volatile
trading, the index dipped to a loss of as much as 200 points in
early trading and again at midday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 89.97 at 11,377.05, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 4.97 at 1,495.62.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 4 9/16 to 79 5/16, depressing the Nasdaq and
hemming in the Dow's advance. This morning, Goldman Sachs analyst
Rick Sherlund cut his revenue estimate for the company's fiscal
third quarter to $5.75 billion from $5.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund said in a research note that personal computer sales
during the quarter appear to have missed Goldman Sachs's earlier
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a further negative for sentiment in a poor tech
market,'' Sherlund said. Computer makers slumped on the news; Dell
fell 2 11/16 to 52} and IBM fell 5[ to 114 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund maintained his third-quarter earnings estimate on
Microsoft of 41 cents a share, compared with 35 cents a year ago,
noting that the lower revenue would likely be offset by gains in
the company's investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's slide provided the latest catalyst for the ongoing
decline of the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ''If investors think there's a prick in the bubble, that gives
them a reason to get out of some stocks that are making them
nervous anyway,'' said Robert M. Balentine, chief executive officer
of investment advisory firm Balentine &AMP; Co. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The index, which set a closing record of 5,048.62 on March 10,
has tumbled 23 percent since then, and is now down more than 4
percent in the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's decline accelerated last week, when the index fell
more than 400 points over the course of two wildly volatile
sessions. Now, analysts are divided on whether the index is headed
back toward its low point of about 3,650 or poised for a round of
bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, analysts say, the volatility has brought some
welcome skepticism to the technology market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors will be more discriminating in their buying of
technology and Internet stocks,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief
market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports continued to drive the market. Enron rose 3} to
72 1/16 after reporting first-quarter earnings of 40 cents a share.
Analysts had anticipated earnings of 37 cents a share. The strong
report confirmed expectations that energy companies will show the
sharpest profit growth for the recently ended quarter.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan rose 5 5/16 to 140 1/16, buoying the Dow. The
investment bank easily exceeded Wall Street's earnings estimates,
posting first-quarter profits of $3.37 a share. Analysts surveyed
by First Call/Thomson Financial had anticipated earnings of $2.81 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial stocks rose amid expectations that they, too,
will report strong earnings. American Express rose 7 9/16 to 152}.
</P>
<P>
   Clorox rose 2~ to 40 3/16 after the company secured an
arrangement with online grocer Webvan to sell its products over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 893.94 million
shares, compared with 786.72 million at the same time Tuesday. On
the Nasdaq, decliners led by a margin of three stocks to one.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.13 to 502.00.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
