<HEADLINE> Buchanan: Hoffa in My Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
Laurie Kellman
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sharing a stage with unlikely allies, Reform
Party presidential hopeful Patrick Buchanan on Wednesday promised
protesting Teamsters he would appoint union president James Hoffa
to his Cabinet and oppose normal U.S. trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Approving such status for China, which President Clinton wants,
would hand American jobs and money to a nation with a poor human
rights record, Buchanan told several thousand Teamsters gathered in
the Capitol's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's something that unites us all. It's the belief that
citizens of the United States are citizens first before they're
consumers and there are values higher than money,'' Buchanan said,
speaking alongside Rep. David Bonoir, D-Mich., Rep. Bernard
Sanders, I-Vt, and other political foes on issues besides trade.
''This battle's about the American family.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade, the centerpiece of Buchanan's third-party presidential
bid, is the link between him and thousands of union members
gathered in Washington to protest next week's meetings of the World
Bank and International Monetary Fund. Buchanan also was present in
Seattle earlier this year when protests turned into riots at a
World Trade Organization meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan registers in single digits in polls that show Democrat
Al Gore and Repubican George W. Bush in a close race.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a Former Republican, said his administration would not
include a trade representative that would cut deals with nations
that pose threats to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I get there, it won't be (U.S. Trade Representative)
Charlene Barshefsky sitting down in Beijing, it'll be Jim Hoffa,''
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered and chanted Hoffa's name.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the audience of Teamsters were there less to support the
politicians such as Buchanan than show opposition to a trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to hand jobs to China,'' said trucker Jack Silver
of Brooklyn, N.Y. ''If he's for that, I'm for that. But that
doesn't mean I'm for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think he's presidential material,'' said Roger Hacker
of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   But Angelo Barca of Yonkers, N.Y. said Buchanan ''is the only
one who's making sense'' on family issues and trade. ''These people
don't know what they're talking about,'' he added, gesturing to his
fellow Teamsters who are backing other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: World Bank: http://www.worldbank.org
</P>
<P>
   International Monetary Fund: http://www.imf.org
</P>
</TEXT>
