<HEADLINE> Moves in Aluminum Merger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French aluminum group Pechiney, which has planned
to merge with Canada's Alcan Aluminum and Switzerland's Algroup,
said Wednesday that the companies plan to file a revised merger
plan with the European Commission by April 30 or will abandon plans
for a three-way combination.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger goes through, the new company would be the world's
largest aluminum producer, with a market capitalization of $19
billion and revenue of $17.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't found an agreement to file to the EU,'' Pechiney
spokeswoman Fabunne de Brebisson said Wednesday. If the groups
don't file by April 30, they will drop merger plans, she said. But
she said the group was not abandoning merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies are trying to renegotiate a linkup that
would satisfy European antitrust regulators who rejected a merger
between Alcan and Pechiney last month. The commission said the
merger would have created ''dominant positions in a number of
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   It already has approved a deal between Alcan and Algroup.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies are looking at measures that would satisfy
the EU's concern, but don't want to ''undermine the rationale of
the merger,'' Alcan spokesman Marc Osboren said.
</P>
<P>
   If merger talks between Alcan and Pechiney break down, Alcan may
be forced to re-negotiate its $4.1 billion deal with Algroup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
