<HEADLINE> Soybeans Rally; Grains Also Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybeans bounced back strongly after falling to
two-week lows Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, advancing on
changing weather forecasts. Grains also rose.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans initially slid for a second straight day on predictions
of more showers this weekend in the Midwest. But prices found
resistance and commodity funds began a buying surge after some
private forecasts scaled back expected rainfall totals for this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The increase was limited by the off-and-on rainy outlook for
soybean growing areas, including southeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat climbed sharply higher in sympathy with soybeans.
Market-watchers said the forecasts for a drier weekend in the
central United States supported the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Corn also rose after falling for the previous seven sessions.
Traders said the mild rally was a response to a decline deemed
overdone.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 3{ cents to $2.68\ a bushel; May
corn rose 2\ cents to $2.34 a bushel; July oats rose } cent to
$1.19 a bushel; May soybeans rose 9{ cents to $5.37{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures were sharply higher.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .12 cent to 69.15 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .23 cent to 84.52 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose 1.70 cent to 75.07 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose the
limit 3 cents to 95.67 cents a pound.
</P>
