<HEADLINE> U.K.'s Thomson Travel Rejects Offer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Thomson Travel PLC, Britain's biggest chartered
tour operator, on Wednesday rejected a sweetened buyout offer of
$2.32 billion in cash from Germany's C&AMP;N Touristic AG.
</P>
<P>
   C&AMP;N's latest offer of $2.32 a share was made on condition that
the Thomson board recommend the deal to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomson said the price ''would not reflect the value of the
business and its prospects'' under a company-wide review that aims
to cut annual costs by at least $80 million and invest in new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''Accordingly, if such an offer were to be made, the board would
unanimously recommend shareholders to reject it,'' the company said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from C&AMP;N, a joint venture
between Kardstadt-Quelle AG and Deutsche Lufthansa AG. It says
Thomson's poor financial performance has placed it in a vulnerable
position.
</P>
<P>
   On April 5, Thomson turned down a cash offer from C&AMP;N of $2.08
per share that would value the British company at $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, founded in 1965 and one of the first tour groups to fly
large numbers of Britons to Mediterranean resorts, issued three
profit warnings last year, the most recent because of poor sales
related to millennium New Year's holidays.
</P>
<P>
   C&AMP;N, Europe's third-largest tour business, is eager to gain a
foothold in Britain, where it currently has no presence. It
increased its holding of Thomson stock to 4.8 percent at the time
of the earlier bid, up from 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The German company was formed from a merger in 1998 of
Lufthansa's charter airline Condor Flugdienst GmbH and Karstadt
Quelle's tour operator NUR Touristic GmbH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
