<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Wants Bush's Plans Scrutinized  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The day after Republican George W. Bush jumped
into the health care debate, Democrat Al Gore accused his rival of
''political malpractice'' and prodded newspaper editors to give
Bush's proposals a close examination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I worked in journalism long enough to know that some claims
demand serious scrutiny,'' Gore told the annual conference of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors. Just out of the Army, Gore
worked for The Tennessean in Nashville in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate also addressed, in
response to one editor's question, the possibility that the
independent counsel investigation into Whitewater and the Monica
Lewinsky affair could yet yield criminal indictments against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, would Gore consider a presidential pardon for his
partner of eight years?
</P>
<P>
   ''President Clinton is way ahead of you on this. He said
publicly some time ago that he would neither request nor accept a
pardon, so that's the answer to that question,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke the day after Bush, the Texas governor and GOP
presidential candidate, proposed tax credits to help working people
buy health insurance. Bush's health plan came after an
environmental speech and emphasis on an education initiative -- all
designed to encroach on issues where Gore believed the upper hand
was his.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ''wants us to believe he's committed to issues like
education, health care and the environment,'' Gore said today.
''Let's face it. The Bush approach on these issues is a headline
without a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued: ''The hundreds of thousands of uninsured
children and families in his own state of Texas who have no health
insurance ... do not have it because of the political malpractice
of the Bush administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he would accept a presidential-debate
invitation from any newspaper editor in the conference room. An
editor from Vancouver, Wash., immediately invited him. ''I
accept,'' Gore said, adding that it was up to the newspaper to get
Bush to accept as well.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has pressed for debates early in the campaign season. Bush
has said there will be plenty of time in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, asked today in St. Louis for a response to
Gore's new criticism, said, ''Not right now, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer defended the governor's record,
saying he had presided over improvements in Texas health care and
signed a patients' bill of rights. A significant piece of that
legislation, giving patients the right the sue insurance companies,
became law without his signature.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worse Al Gore is doing in the polls, the more he attacks
and misrepresents the governor's record,'' said Fleischer. ''Pretty
soon, Al Gore will say he invented health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had gentler words for families affected by the Columbine
school shootings, who say last April's tragedy should qualify as a
disaster whose victims are eligible for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would certainly have a positive feeling about that,'' Gore
said, noting that Clinton was in Denver today and planned to meet
with some of the families.
</P>
<P>
   From one hotel conference room, Gore headed to another where he
and fund-raising pro Terry McAuliffe joined forces to light a fire
under the two dozen prominent Democrats working on the May 24
Washington gala starring Clinton and Gore. McAuliffe put the
fund-raising goal for that bluejeans-and-barbecue evening at $7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also held forth at a small, $500,000 luncheon for the
Democratic National Committee at the Washington home of former New
York Rep. Tom Downey, now a government consultant whose clients
include Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's ongoing solicitation for the Democrats included a $1
million dinner Tuesday night, $3.5 million in appearances last week
and a packed weekend of fund-raisers coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, he is entertaining Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura at a
private dinner at the vice presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore and Ventura said their meeting would be as much a
social opportunity for them and their wives as a chance to talk
issues. A coveted endorsement by Ventura, the nation's best-known
independent officeholder, was not in the works for today, the aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just won't happen,'' said Ventura spokesman John Wodele.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner with Ventura, Gore was headed to Charlotte, N.C.,
to make good on a rain check to Marie G. Davis Middle School when
he canceled a visit last week to be in Washington with a sick
friend.
</P>
<P>
   The eight hours he planned to spend Thursday immersed in the
school's routine follow his school day Tuesday at Avondale
Elementary in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when opposition to the state's mandated proficiency
tests is growing, the Democratic presidential candidate said he
supported such tests as a way ''to measure the performance of the
students'' and ''a fair and accurate way to get a measurement of
how the schools are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
