<DOCNO> APW20000412.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal judge approves state changes to Megan's Law  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A federal judge who once threatened to stop
sex offender notifications now says the state attorney general has
a ''reasonable method'' for distributing the community warnings
allowed by Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Joseph Irenas ended the latest
challenge to the law Wednesday by approving the state plan
requiring people who get such notices to sign promises not to
discuss the information.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Irenas said the notification guidelines were
unconstitutional, in part because authorities routinely allowed
details about sex offenders to go far beyond court-ordered bounds.
He allowed the notifications to continue while the matter was
appealed by the state public defenders office, representing sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling prompted supporters -- including Maureen Kanka, whose
daughter's rape and murder gave birth to Megan's Law -- to push for
a change in the state constitution. They want an amendment to
broaden the law and allow legislators legal room to put details
about sex offenders on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The state public defender tried to convince Irenas that by
including a sex offender's street address in the packet of
information distributed, the state violated the felon's privacy
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do not sign the waiver will not be given the
offender's exact address, the judge said. And others, like school
employees and business owners, only will see notices that do not
include the address.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mandate this court issued to defendants was not to create
a perfect system, but one reasonably calculated to get the
information to those with a 'particular need for it' while
avoiding'' those who do not need it, Irenas wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A warning notice with the ''general area'' where a sex offender
lives is not ''information of an extremely personal or private
nature,'' he said. And ''in today's world'' many people have access
to once-private information like home addresses, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In most cases, a person with the inclination and Internet
access can discover another's home address without great effort,''
Irenas said. If he declared such avenues to information off-limits,
''very little information would be free from constitutional
protection,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. said he is ''gratified'' by
the decision, especially since the judge ''recognized we weren't
pandering to any special interest group'' with the revised
guidelines. The office chose to issue the new guidelines rather
than appeal the January ruling, Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It strikes a balance. That's what we tried to do and that's
what the judge recognized,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The public defender is reviewing the decision, spokesman Jeff
Beach said in a prepared statement. The sex offenders the office
represents ''have expressed their disappointment in Judge Irenas'
ruling and we are weighing the options on how to proceed,'' Beach
said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's law categorizes convicted sex offenders into three
levels, based on the perceived threat the felons present. For those
labeled most at risk of committing another crime, the law allows
prosecutors to provide an offender's name, address and photo to
residents living in a carefully defined area. All offenders are
required to register with police, once out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law is named for Megan Kanka, a 7-year-old Hamilton
Township girl who was raped and murdered in July 1994 by a
convicted sex offender who lived across the street from her Mercer
County home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
