<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Money for National Lakes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House on Wednesday approved $250 million
in grants over five years to help states clean up the nation's
lakes. It separately authorized a six-year $180 million program to
continue Chesapeake Bay restoration work.
</P>
<P>
   The clean lakes bill, sponsored by Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y.,
would put new life in a program that has fallen out of use in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The program was a provision of the 1972 Clean Water Act, but the
Environmental Protection Agency has not sought funding in recent
years, asking states to use money from other pollution programs to
clean up their lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to have a national program because certainly acid rain
is something that crosses state lines,'' Transportation Committee
Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., said.
</P>
<P>
   The House action said Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., ''will
send a clear message that we care about restoring and protecting
our nation's 41 million acres of freshwater lakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also increases from $15 million to $25 million a
year money available for the study of acid rain effects on lakes.
It adds four lakes -- Otsego and Oneida in New York, Raystown in
Pennsylvania and Swan in Minneapolis -- to a demonstration project
list receiving priority funding.
</P>
<P>
   The second bill approves $30 million a year to continue the
Chesapeake Bay Program, run by the EPA with the cooperation of the
states of Virginia, Pennsylvania and Maryland and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   It creates a new office within the EPA dedicated to implementing
efforts to restore the waters and the wildlife of the 64,000 square
mile watershed.
</P>
<P>
   The clean lakes bill passed 420-5 and the Chesapeake Bay bill
418-7. Both need Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Lakes bill number is H.R. 2328
</P>
<P>
   The Chesapeake Bay bill is H.R. 3039.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
