<P>
   Forrester: E-Retailers Will Bust
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Most retailers that operate entirely on the
Internet will be out of business by next year, a respected
consulting firm predicted in a report that fired another blow to
the battered online shopping industry. Intense competition combined
with an ongoing selloff in dot-com stocks will result in a rapid
rise in buyouts and bankruptcies in the coming months, according to
Forrester Research Inc. The fallout has already begun. Lawyers and
consultants are getting swamped with calls for help from companies
in distress.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Reports Net Loss
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Leading media conglomerate Time Warner Inc.
reported higher earnings in most of its business areas today but
still posted a net loss for the first quarter due mainly to a
write-down in the troubled music retailer Columbia House. Time
Warner reported a net loss of $101 million, or 8 cents per share,
for the three months ended March 31. Excluding the $220 million
charge for Columbia House, a $46 million charge related to its
pending acquisition by America Online Inc. and gains of $28 million
on sales of cable systems, the company earned 5 cents per share,
beating analysts' estimates of 2 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones Earnings Double in 1Q
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones &AMP; Co. reported today that its income
nearly doubled in the first quarter of the year, driven by big
gains in advertising revenues from The Wall Street Journal. Not
counting a profit from the sale of a financial publishing unit, Dow
Jones earned $79.2 million during the three months ended March 31,
or 88 cents per share, beating analyst forecasts of 80 cents per
share. Including the gain from selling Dow Jones Financial
Publishing Corp., the company had net earnings of $88.7 million, or
98 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   IMF Releases Optimistic Forecast
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world economy, after being staggered by a
global financial crisis, regained its footing in 1999 and will grow
this year at 4.2 percent, the fastest pace in more than a decade,
the International Monetary Fund forecast today. It also expects
growth to continue sill-strong 3.9 percent in 2001. The IMF also
revised its estimate last year's growth to 3.3 percent, up sharply
from the 1998 figure of 2.5 percent. But the IMF also cautioned
that a sudden plunge in the U.S. stock market and a ''hard
landing'' for the U.S. economy could be risks to its forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Globalization Groups Protest
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Anti-globalization groups, hoping to repeat
the success they had in disrupting the World Trade Organization
meetings last year in Seattle, are staging a protest rally at the
U.S. Capitol today in advance of the IMF and World Bank meetings.
The AFL-CIO hoped to attract 10,000 demonstrators against one of
the Clinton administration's top priorities, granting China
permanent normal trade relations. Thousands of union members have
rallied at the Capitol and lobbied lawmakers to protest a bill that
would give permanent normal trade status to China instead of annual
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Post Office Switches to Dot-Com
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The post office, reflecting the growth of its
electronic business, has changed the address of its Internet site
from www.usps.gov to www.usps.com. Addresses that end in ''gov''
are generally used by government agencies, and the Postal Service
is a semi-independent part of the government. But it is expected to
pay its own way and engages in many commercial activities including
sales of stamps and stamp-related merchandise as well as its newly
launched electronic bill paying service. So the decision was made
to switch, said Norman Cloher, manager of online services.
</P>
<P>
   Freight Carrier Has Cash Concerns
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Shares of air-freight carrier Kitty
Hawk plummeted more than 80 percent today after the company warned
investors it could soon run out of cash. Kitty Hawk said late
yesterday that it will be forced to restate its 1999 profits and
report a larger first-quarter loss than analysts had expected. It
also said accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young will report that it cannot
assure stockholders the company can remain in business. Kitty Hawk
said it is working with lenders to restructure its debt and is
looking for buyers of some of its assets. Kitty Hawk stock was down
3 19/32 at 29/32.
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry Being Bought by Unilever
</P>
<P>
