buying Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, the ice-cream maker founded by two
former hippies and known for its social activism, and Slim-Fast
Foods Co., a privately owned Florida outfit that makes nutritional
supplements and food for people who want to lose weight. Today's
Ben &AMP; Jerry's deal follows an effort by a group led by one of the
company's co-founders, Ben Cohen, to take the company private.
Unilever is to pay $43.60 per share to buy the Vermont-based
company that has carefully honed a tie-dyed, anti-corporate image
in its two decades of existence. That would be a nearly 25 percent
premium over Ben &AMP; Jerry's closing price Tuesday of $34.93}.
</P>
<P>
   Moves in Aluminum Merger
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French aluminum group Pechiney, which has planned
to merge with Canada's Alcan Aluminum and Switzerland's Algroup,
said today that the companies plan to file a revised merger plan
with the European Commission by April 30 or will abandon the
three-way plans. If the merger goes through, the new company would
be the world's largest aluminum producer, with a market
capitalization of $19 billion and revenue of $17.4 billion. The
three companies are trying to renegotiate a linkup that would
satisfy European antitrust regulators who rejected a merger between
Alcan and Pechiney last month. The commission said the merger would
have created ''dominant positions in a number of markets.'' It
already has approved a deal between Alcan and Algroup.
</P>
<P>
   U.K.'s Thomson Travel Rejects Offer
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Thomson Travel PLC, Britain's biggest chartered
tour operator, today rejected a sweetened buyout offer of $2.32
billion in cash from Germany's C&AMP;N Touristic AG. C&AMP;N's latest offer
of $2.32 a share was made on condition that the Thomson board
recommend the deal to shareholders. But Thomson said the price
''would not reflect the value of the business and its prospects''
under a company-wide review that aims to cut annual costs by at
least $80 million and invest in new technology.
</P>
