<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spider-Man Creator Signs With D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's the comic book equivalent of Coke
executives joining the Pepsi Generation.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Lee, the legendary Marvel Comics guru and creator of
Spider-Man and The Hulk, has signed on to work with his former
arch-enemies at D.C. Comics. Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ''How could I say no?'' Lee asked Wednesday from his California
office. ''What a kick this is. And even if I fall on my face, I
think people will get a kick out of this.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, I hope I don't fall on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, Lee will be allowed to recreate the lives
and times of DC's most recognizable characters. Will Superman make
it from Krypton to Metropolis? Will Batman find his Robin? What of
Wonder Woman?
</P>
<P>
   It's all up to Lee, who says the only boundary is his
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every kid who has ever picked up one of his comics wondered
what Stan would do if he ever worked on the DC heroes,'' said Paul
Levitz, executive vice president and publisher of DC Comics. ''And
now we can deliver their dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger, once unthinkable, became possible in 1998 when
Marvel emerged from bankruptcy. Lee's exclusive contract was voided
and replaced with a lifetime deal requiring him to spend just 10
percent of his time with the company.
</P>
<P>
   So when DC approached with their proposal for ''Just Imagine
Stan Lee Creating ...'', he jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beautiful thing about it is that I start from ground
zero,'' Lee said. ''The toughest thing is deciding, 'How would I do
this?' It's almost like I'm somebody else thinking, 'How would Stan
Lee do this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Even better, he will work with some of the business' top
artists: longtime Marvel collaborator John Buscema, ''Watchmen''
illustrator Dave Gibbons, and Bruce Timm of the animated ''Batman''
and ''Superman'' animated television series.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 77, remains the comic book industry's pre-eminent figure,
even after 60 years in the business.
</P>
<P>
   The creator of Spider-Man, The Hulk and The X-Men, he is still
chairman emeritus of Marvel. His most recent endeavor is Stan Lee
Media; his stanleemedia.com website is home to his animated on-line
comic book, ''The 7th Portal.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is under a considerable amount of secrecy, but Lee
said he had already written his Wonder Woman piece and was halfway
through Superman.
</P>
<P>
   Any hints about what happens, Stan?
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have Superman coming from Krypton,'' he quickly
replied. ''If I was going to come up with any name for a planet, it
would probably be Lee-tron.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
