<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Looks To Keep Elderly at Work  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At age 61, Sherman Sorem faced an increasingly
common retirement dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   His company, Fisher Controls International, was downsizing and
offered him an early retirement buyout or a less-demanding,
lower-paying job.
</P>
<P>
   Sorem wanted to keep working, but it would have ultimately meant
a smaller pension, since, like most corporate retirement benefits,
his are based on earnings during the final few years of service.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'No, you're not going to beat me out of that. I'll
take early retirement,''' said Sorem, now 65.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sorem has needed expertise, the company still asks him
to come back to work for a few weeks each year. But the
Marshalltown, Iowa, retiree and his wife Nancy, 62, wonder why
there wasn't a better way.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of labor shortages caused by the humming economy
and with a huge wave of baby boomers nearing retirement age,
Congress is beginning to wonder the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to make sure federal laws don't hurt older workers.
Our economy will depend on it,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley,
R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate Special Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, Congress has repealed the Social Security
earnings limit, removing the threat of reduced federal retirement
benefits for those who continue to work past age 65. President
Clinton signed that legislation into law Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Now lawmakers are considering how to break down private-sector
barriers for older workers, such as outdated tax and pension laws
that often result in penalties against people who work past a
certain age. The aging committee explored options at a hearing last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Among ideas being considered are legislation that would make it
easier for companies to design phased pensions, allowing partial
collection of benefits starting at age 59{ by those who continue to
work part time.
</P>
<P>
   That's similar to rules governing 401(k) retirement savings
accounts, a newer employee benefit that is increasingly popular but
does not have the advantage of guaranteeing a continuous old-age
income, as pensions do.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the elderly say better age discrimination laws
also may be needed to ensure that older workers get equal
opportunities for training to keep up with changing technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the time it is a subtle discrimination that occurs,''
said Joseph Perkins, president of the AARP, the nation's largest
organization of older adults.
</P>
<P>
   Like Social Security, many laws and attitudes shaping today's
retirement options developed around the time of the Great
Depression, when high unemployment made it desirable to encourage
older Americans to leave the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. Now a thriving economy creating plentiful
jobs has many employers scrambling to hold on to workers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the huge baby boom generation has reached middle age.
Rising life expectancies mean many will live for decades past what
has been considered ''normal'' retirement age, between ages 60 and
65.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 13 percent of Americans currently aged 65 and older
work, according to AARP. But a 1998 AARP poll of baby boomers found
that eight in 10 intend to keep working at least part time in old
age -- because they think they will need extra cash, or for
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Hy-Vee Inc., a supermarket chain with 210 stores across the
Midwest, is among companies taking steps to attract and keep older
workers.
</P>
<P>
   In help-wanted advertisements, Hy-Vee promises flexible
scheduling -- including three-season jobs, allowing for winters
spent in warmer climes. ''Your experience and maturity are assets
we find valuable to our success,'' the ads say.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Special Committee on Aging hearing testimony on older
workers: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)aging/hr47.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
