<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Medical Boards Overworked  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators are beginning steps to
increase the safety of thousands of people enrolled in medical
research, but the local medical boards primarily responsible for
such oversight remain overworked and undertrained, says a new
inspector general report.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest gaps: Once regulators agree to let a medical
experiment start, there is little independent monitoring of how
patients fare day-to-day, meaning early warning signs of risk may
be missed.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health and Human Services' inspector general
first warned in 1998 that the protection system for Americans
enrolled in clinical trials was in jeopardy, and urged reforms to
better assure patient safety.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ''minimal progress has been made,'' the inspector
general said in an update to that investigation released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The government has taken some steps to improve -- indeed, the
National Institutes of Health's Office of Protection from Research
Risks last year began more aggressively enforcing patient
protections. And the recent public outcry over the death of an
Arizona teen-ager in a gene therapy study should serve ''as a
catalyst'' for yet stronger protections, the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Among the improvements the report cites:
</P>
<P>
   --Between April 1997 and May 1998, the OPRR had conducted an
on-site investigation of only one medical center, but between June
1998 and last month that number rose to 10. OPRR last year began
more aggressively enforcing safety regulations, and suspended
federally funded research at seven medical centers that broke such
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are compelled to keep people who are in experiments out of
harm's way. Concern for the interests of the subject must always
prevail over the interests of science and society,'' OPRR chief Dr.
Gary Ellis said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   --The Food and Drug Administration has increased its on-site
safety investigations, from 213 in 1997 to 336 last year. The FDA
also now better informs medical oversight boards when it catches
scientists involved in misconduct, information those boards need to
judge the researchers' ongoing work.
</P>
<P>
   But federal regulators rely on local help in making sure that
people are properly informed of the risks of clinical trials and
that side effects are caught early. Institutional review boards, or
IRBs, at hospitals are supposed to do that job -- but that safety
net continues to be shaky, Wednesday's report says.
</P>
<P>
   Some IRBs are asked to approve 2,000 clinical trial designs
every year, in addition to overseeing whether ongoing studies harm
people. IRB members are so overworked that some have acknowledged
they don't even question the safety of an ongoing study unless
someone dies.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the inspector general recommended in 1998 that
many experiments be given an independent monitoring board to
oversee ongoing studies. Wednesday's report concluded that hasn't
happened.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the nation's most high-profile clinical trial
tragedy -- the death of Jesse Gelsinger, 18, from a gene therapy
experiment -- the FDA found University of Pennsylvania researchers
failed to properly report side effects and had no outside monitors
to sound the warning, either.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has now ordered that all gene therapy studies have
independent monitors. The new report urged extending that rule to
other medical experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The government also needs to better educate IRB members about
federal safety rules, and find ways to insulate these boards from
conflicts of interest -- a growing concern as more and more research
at hospitals and academic medical centers is funded by industry.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.dhhs.gov/progorg/oei/whatsnew.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1810 </TRAILER>
