<HEADLINE> Army: Fighting in Senegal Kills 18  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- The army forced back secessionist rebels
attempting to cross into southern Senegal from Guinea-Bissau, the
military said late Tuesday. At least 18 people were killed in the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily armed rebels crossed into the southern enclave of
Casamance early Tuesday and attacked army positions in the frontier
village of Sara Wali, the military said in a statement late that
day.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels were forced back over the border in heavy fighting,
the statement said. Three government soldiers and 15 rebels were
killed, according to the military, which did not say how many
people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's assault took Senegal by surprise. President Abdoulaye
Wade has made peace in Casamance a priority of his new government,
and rebel leader Rev. Diamacoune Senghor has said his election
could lead to a breakthrough in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are fighting for autonomy in Casamance, which is
separated from most of the rest of this West African country by
Gambia. More than 1,200 people have been killed since the rebellion
began in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who reportedly receive military aid from
Guinea-Bissau, claim Casamance was never colonized by the French as
part of Senegal and so should remain independent. France disputes
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Wade's election last month ended the 40-year rule of the
Socialist Party, which has governed since independence from France
in 1960.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
