<HEADLINE> Beefy British Farmers in Calendar  </HEADLINE>
By JILL LAWLESS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- It gives a whole new meaning to the term
''beefcake.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve British farmers have bared all in a calendar designed in
part to draw attention to the nation's beleaguered beef industry.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Meat British Beef'' calendar features a dozen farmers from
southwest Devon county in a variety of pastoral poses.
</P>
<P>
   A naked Mr. March smiles from the cab of his tractor, while Mr.
November, clad only in a cap and rubber boots, sits astride a
horse. Others preserve their modesty with strategically placed corn
stalks, cauliflower and bales of hay.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought it would be nice to draw attention to farmers in a
positive way -- and to show they've had the shirts taken off their
backs,'' said Nicola de Pulford, a Devon farmer and photographer
who took the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The broad smiles of the models, who range in age from their late
20s to early 40s, mask the ailing state of Britain's farm sector.
Beef farmers have been clobbered by bans imposed by several
countries, including France, over concerns about bovine spongiform
encephalopathy, or ''mad cow'' disease.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the group's Web site can simultaneously order a
calendar and sign a petition calling for a ban on French produce
and for Prime Minister Tony Blair's government to do more to help
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are farming families who are desperately struggling,''
the farmer-photographer de Pulford said. ''A lot of livestock
farmers just feel they can't go on. Farmers don't want money from
the government. All they want is a fair price for the goods they
are selling.''
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the calendar project will go to a cooperative
formed by the participants and to a farmers' charity.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar has been a hit, selling 14,000 copies through mail
order since it was released in November and spawning a series of
personal appearances by the models -- including a ''Full
Monty''-style strip routine at a charity event.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tony Blair has said he wants farmers to diversify,'' de
Pulford said. ''What better kind of diversification is there?''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The group's site, http://www.rawbeef.co.uk
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
