<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Region Sets Telework Goals  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER ANDES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Telecommuting will work only if bosses accept
that real work is done at home, say leaders around the nation's
capital who hope the practice can help solve the area's traffic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Many employers imagine the employee ''home in bunny slippers and
lounging in an easy chair with the kids running around,'' said Ada
Posey, a policy adviser with the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, telework increases an employee's productivity and at
either no cost or a savings to the employee and employer, said
Posey, who was among the panelists Wednesday at a Metropolitan
Washington Council of Governments' discussion on the benefits of
telework.
</P>
<P>
   COG's Board of Directors, comprised of leaders from the District
of Columbia and surrounding jurisdictions, unanimously approved a
resolution Wednesday to have at least 600,000 employees, or 20
percent of the regional workforce, working at home at least one day
a month. That would mean 70,000 fewer vehicles on area roads each
day. Currently, approximately 12 percent of the workforce
telecommutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Automobile Association of America cites telecommuting as
among tools the region can use to decrease congestion, said Mantill
Williams, a AAA Mid-Atlantic region spokesman. Road expansions and
additional bridges also are necessary, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Through telecommuting, companies are better able to retain and
recruit employees, who tend to feel more appreciated and are more
productive, and the region benefits from improved air quality and
fewer traffic collisions, said Gerald E. Connolly, chairman of
COG's Board of Directors and a member of the Fairfax County, Va.,
board of supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Weidenfeld, a telework coordinator for Maryland,
telecommutes one day a week and estimates he saves approximately
$1,000 a year in automobile costs. The savings more than paid for
the technology he needed to establish a home office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Kelley, a data analyzer with The Marasco Newton Group in
Arlington, Va., said telecommuting has reduced stress in her life,
particularly when she has to work late. Kelley said she is able to
relax and have dinner with her husband before finishing her work at
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1825 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman sorry for her role in double murder  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The state's star witness against two
brothers accused in the killings of an 8-year-old boy and his
mother said she lied about what she told police.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Lee told police she acted as a lookout and then
watched as Adrian Peeler gunned down Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and
his mother, Karen Clarke, in their Bridgeport home on Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who agreed to testify against Adrian and his brother,
Russell, is now in the federal witness protection program. She
pleaded guilty in May to conspiracy to commit murder. In exchange
for her testimony, prosecutors had said they would ask for a
sentence of no more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But in a rambling letter she wrote to her lawyer in December--
after she struck a deal with prosecutors-- Lee talks about wanting
to do less time in prison.
</P>
<P>
   She says she has been lying about the case, but she doesn't get
specific.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that I have told them is lies,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to make this thing right and deep down inside (God
knows) that I did not have anything to do with the murder.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, she writes, ''I can't not live with myself telling
a lie on the Peelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler's lawyer, John Walkley, said he interprets the
letter as a complete reversal by Lee and will ask that the charges
against his client be dismissed based on the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ''She said she wasn't involved and the Peelers were not
involved,'' Walkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It confirms what I've known all along, that she was never
there and that she had been lying about it from Day One,'' Walkley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's attorney, Richard Reeve, refused to comment on the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Jonathan Benedict could not be reached for comment. A
message was left at his home late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was released Wednesday in Bridgeport Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 33, lived across the street from B.J. and his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In her earlier statement to police, Lee said that after agreeing
to help the brothers, she paged Russell Peeler the day of the
murders to let him know the mother and son had arrived home.
</P>
<P>
   She said Adrian Peeler arrived within five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she walked to Clarke's house with Adrian. When she rang
the doorbell, Clarke opened the door slightly after Lee identified
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Adrian Peeler then pushed the door open, sending
groceries flying.
</P>
<P>
   As B.J. and his mother ran up the stairs, Adrian chased them,
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard the shot and the little boy was reaching out for his
mother,'' Lee said. ''He was yelling, 'Mommy, Mommy, Mommy,
Mommy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she heard a shot coming from the bedroom where Clarke
had run.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler then came out of the bedroom, where B.J. was still
screaming for his mother. Then Adrian Peeler shot B.J. in the head,
Lee told police.
</P>
<P>
   In letters Lee wrote to three Bridgeport police officers written
at about the same time she wrote the letter to her lawyer, Lee says
she's found God and is looking for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know what I did was wrong. I get down on my knees every
night and ask God to forgive me for what I have done to the boy and
his mother,'' Lee wrote in a letter to Detective Dwayne McBride.
</P>
<P>
   She also says she is grateful to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God that my life is still here because the Peelers did
not kill me and that is a blessing from God,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Peelers are accused of killing B.J. and his mother to stop
the boy from testifying against Russell in the 1998 murder of
Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr. The boy had witnessed an
earlier driveby shooting in which Russell attempted to kill Snead
and was expected to be the prosecution's star witness.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is now under way for Russell Peeler's trial,
which is expected to begin later this month. Adrian Peeler's trial
is expected to begin this summer.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the brothers could face the death penalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
