<HEADLINE> Pacific Rower Has 8 Toes Amputated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Rescued French rower Jo Le Guen was
recovering well Wednesday after doctors amputated eight of his toes
damaged by gangrene during his aborted attempt to row across the
Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors removed all five toes from Le Guen's left foot and three
middle ones from his right foot, said medical sources at the navy
hospital in Punta Arenas, Chile's southernmost city.
</P>
<P>
   The toes were removed from the joints without breaking the
bones, the sources said. He will be able to walk, but will probably
need a prothesis, they said. The remaining toes will help Le Guen
stay balanced, they added.
</P>
<P>
   Le Guen, an experienced rower, was plucked from the sea last
Monday, 61 days and one-third of the distance into his 5,580-mile
solo voyage from Wellington, New Zealand, to Cape Horn, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Le Guen, the 52-year-old father of five, wanted to draw
attention to the damage being done to the world's oceans by
pollution. He gave up his journey and abandoned his boat,
''Keepitblue,'' after doctors suspected he had developed gangrene
in both his feet.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to reporters, Le Guen said Tuesday that loosing his
toes, is ''still not far from the minimum price.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was first rescued, three of Le Guen's toes had turned
black, apparently damaged by rubbing against the foot straps he
used while rowing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
