<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Legal orphans' languish with understaffed state agencies, busycourts  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- They're ''legal orphans'' -- children who
have been legally freed from abusive families, but not yet adopted
by new ones.
</P>
<P>
   And more and more of them are stuck in the system.
</P>
<P>
   New laws have pushed state agencies and courts to move faster on
child abuse cases that traditionally left kids in foster care for
years.
</P>
<P>
   It's working -- in part. More abusive parents are losing their
rights to their children. But, while adoptions are increasing, they
are not keeping pace with the number of children legally available
for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Understaffed state agencies and busy courts are creating a raft
of children in a legal limbo, failing to accomplish the goal of
giving abused kids stable homes, child advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   They also predict that the backlog of waiting children will get
even worse because Gov. Christie Whitman's proposed budget offers
no new funding for the state centers that oversee these adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   The state's five adoption centers are the most understaffed of
all the Division of Youth and Family Service's offices, state
figures show.
</P>
<P>
   And they're juggling more cases.
</P>
<P>
   From 1997 to 1999, there was a 73 percent increase in the number
of abused children who were being freed for adoption, going from
about 700 to 1,230, according to Andy Williams, DYFS spokesman.
During that same time, adoption placements increased only 21
percent, going from about 670 to 810, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of these children live in foster homes that
will eventually adopt them. The state must find homes for the
others.
</P>
<P>
   There are not enough workers to process the paperwork to
finalize adoptions and find adoptive homes, said Ceil Zalkind,
associate director of the Association for Children of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, the number of children being overseen by the
Adoption Resource Centers has increased 32 percent, from about
3,000 to nearly 4,000, according to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Staffing has increased 17 percent, from 114 caseworkers in
January 1999 to 134 currently, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are being totally inundated with cases because of the
(federal) Adoption and Safe Family Act,'' said Charles Cohen, union
shop steward for the Northern region adoption center.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government enacted the law in 1997 to prevent abused
children from spending years in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ''The agency did not prepare for the cases coming into the
adoption centers,'' he said. ''We are totally unable to provide
services for these children.''
</P>
<P>
   A governor-appointed panel on DYFS recommended that staffing
ratios be brought up to national standards. But, more than two
years after the panel's report was issued, those ratios have
actually gotten worse at the adoption centers, according to state
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption caseworkers are juggling 35 to 40 cases, instead of the
recommended 12 to 20 cases, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no justification for it,'' said Zalkind, who also
chairs the DYFS-appointed Adoption Service Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey enacted its law in March 1999 to comply with the
federal statute.
</P>
<P>
   Under both laws, the state must move to terminate the rights of
parents whose children have been in foster care for 15 of the
previous 22 months. Children who have been in foster care for 12
consecutive months must get a ''permanency'' hearing before a
judge.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when the federal government enacted the law, about
8,950 New Jersey children were in foster homes, group homes or
state institutions, Williams said. The law requires all of those
children to be in a permanent placement by the beginning of July.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with the shorter deadlines for all other children,
is creating an overload of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the problem may be with the court system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know that it's the adoption resource centers that are
not moving the cases,'' said Williams. ''It still takes time to get
these cases through the court system.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack McCarthy, director of child court services, said the
judiciary has doubled the number of judges handling these cases,
but even with that, it's been difficult to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our sense is the resources we've added at some point will meet
the filings,'' he said. ''Right now, we're in the peak of this
backlog reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that the adoption centers are failing to move
cases quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time a case spends in case preparation (at the adoption
centers) is too long,'' he said. ''It's taken four, five, sometimes
six months to get these complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Farrand, president of the New Jersey Foster Parents
Association, is trying to adopt two of her foster children. She had
to wait two months to get an adoption worker assigned to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption caseworkers oversee the adoption process, which
includes creating a medical history, collecting school records and
writing a narrative about the child's history with DYFS.
Caseworkers also work with foster and adoptive parents and help
recruit adoptive homes.
</P>
<P>
   State officials knew that more children would be transferred to
the adoption centers, under the new laws, Williams said. They also
knew staff was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking at what our current resources are and figuring
out what our options are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zalkind's adoption committee recently asked Department of Human
Services chief Michele Guhl to request more money for the budget
that begins July 1 to hire more adoption caseworkers. The committee
also urged Guhl to ask for one-shot funding to clear up the backlog
of children awaiting adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is serious,'' Zalkind said. ''This is a one-time
opportunity to provide permanent homes for children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
