<HEADLINE> Elian Judge Indicted Over Donation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A state judge who granted custody of Elian Gonzalez
to a great-uncle in Miami has been charged with illegally accepting
a $200,000 campaign contribution.
</P>
<P>
   A two-count misdemeanor indictment issued Tuesday charged
Miami-Dade Circuit Judge Rosa Rodriguez with illegally accepting
the money and failing to report it on required financial disclosure
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Each count against her carries a possible punishment of one year
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney John Thornton Jr. said Rodriguez is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The law is clear that judicial candidates can borrow money in
excess of $500,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-month investigation examined a loan to her 1998
campaign when she was first elected to the bench. She didn't
mention the money on one disclosure report but said on another that
it came from her brother Hugo, an assistant federal public
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Rodriguez borrowed the money from Miami attorney K. Gabriel
Bach, loaned it to his sister, and she loaned it to her campaign,
the brother's attorney Howard Srenbick said Wednesday. Bach did not
immediately return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The loan was made under a 1982 opinion from the state Division
of Elections that unlimited loans to candidates rather than
campaigns are permitted, Srebnick said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will find that Judge Rodriguez has a lot of company in
judges and other officials who have borrowed money from family
members and friends for running a campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Rodriguez told state election officials that she
''inadvertently omitted'' the loan from a disclosure form. After
learning she was under investigation, she said in October that she
was repaying the $120,000 balance to Bach.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez entered the national spotlight in January when she
ordered Elian to stay in Miami until a custody hearing could be
held. It was later disclosed that she had paid $60,000 to Armando
Gutierrez, the spokesman for Elian's Miami relatives, as a campaign
consultant for her judicial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Supreme Court has the power to decide whether to
take action against Rodriguez, a Puerto Rican native and Yale law
school graduate, which could include suspension or removal from the
bench.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
