<HEADLINE> Ex La. Gov.: Tape Misinterpreted  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A secretly taped conversation about
splitting the proceeds of a proposed tugboat deal is being
misinterpreted by prosecutors, former Gov. Edwin Edwards testified
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the first time in my life I thought of something and
then realized on sober reflection that it's not the thing to do,''
Edwards, 72, said during his second day on the witness stand in his
federal racketeering trial.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who faces up to 350 years in prison if convicted on all
counts, maintained a calm demeanor during intense cross examination
regarding his financial relationship with former Treasure Chest
Casino owner Robert Guidry.
</P>
<P>
   Guidry, early in the three-month trial, testified he paid
Edwards and two others as much as $1.5 million in extortion money
for help in getting a riverboat casino license.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards admitted discussing a plan to get money out of Guidry in
the Feb. 27, 1997, taped conversation. But he said it was money
Guidry owed him, his son Stephen and friend Andrew Martin for
legitimate legal, lobbying and consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the younger Edwards and four other men are
co-defendants. Prosecutors say they were involved in a series of
extortion and bribery schemes involving the licensing of riverboat
casinos before and after Edwards' last term ended in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the taped conversation, Martin and the Edwardses also are
heard discussing a way to rent a tugboat to Guidry, then hike up
the rental fee. They also discuss charging Guidry for made-up work.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is heard on the tape saying ''we get 30-30-30.''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Jim Letten asked Edwards whether that was a
reference to the payments the men were receiving from Guidry.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards first said he had no idea what Martin was talking about.
Then, he said prosecutors overlooked the fact that Martin used the
word ''get,'' instead of ''getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was referring to what the men would ''get'' from the
aborted boat deal, not on what prosecutors said the men already
were ''getting'' from Guidry, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate to have my whole life hang on a couple of words,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
