<HEADLINE> Time Warner Reports Net Loss  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Leading media conglomerate Time Warner Inc.
reported higher earnings in most of its business areas Wednesday
but still posted a net loss for the first quarter due mainly to a
write-down in the troubled music retailer Columbia House.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner reported a net loss of $101 million, or 8 cents per
share, for the three months ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the $220 million charge for Columbia House, a $46
million charge related to its pending acquisition by America Online
Inc. and gains of $28 million on sales of cable systems, the
company earned 5 cents per share, beating analysts' estimates of 2
cents per share, as reported by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   In the same quarter a year ago, Time Warner reported net profits
of $120 million, or 10 cents a share, which included a one-time
gain of $215 million from the early termination of a video
distribution agreement with MGM. Without the gain, Time Warner
broke even in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 7.5 percent to $6.55 billion from $6.09 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a discussion with reporters about first quarter earnings,
Time Warner executives said their combination with America Online
was going smoothly and was expected to close by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   They recognized concerns among investors about the complexity
involved in integrating the two very different companies, but said
they remained confident about the strategy of merging the online
reach of AOL with Time Warner's vast array of traditional media
assets spanning movies, cable TV, music and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ''I acknowledge we're going to make a lot of mistakes here, but
no one else is on this playing field,'' Time Warner chairman and
CEO Gerald Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty write-down on Columbia House was the main dark spot on
an otherwise good quarter for Time Warner. The struggling direct
sales company, which is half-owned by Sony, is going through a
major restructuring as it loses business to the likes of
Amazon.com. In March the companies called off a planned merger
between Columbia House and CDNow, an Internet music retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner reported operating gains in all its business
segments except for music, which has been slumping for the past few
quarters. Time Warner is hoping to revive this part of its domain
by merging its music operations into a joint venture with EMI,
which was announced in January.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gains in earnings came from Time Warner's cable
businesses, which include cable networks such as TBS, HBO and
Cinemax as well as delivery of cable subscription services.
</P>
<P>
   HBO has been having a good run with its hit series ''The
Sopranos,'' and TBS and TNT also had better results despite a
downturn in World Champion Wrestling, which faces tough competition
from the World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Operating results from cable systems rose 13 percent during the
quarter due to higher advertising revenues and subscription rates
as well as the continued rollout of digital cable and high-speed
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   The 450,000 customers receiving next-generation digital cable
still represent a small part of Time Warner's total customer base
of 12.7 million. Time Warner is the country's second-largest cable
provider behind AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's publishing arm, which includes Time Inc., the
nation's largest magazine publisher, also had higher results. The
company credited higher advertising revenues at titles such as
Fortune and InStyle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the music division, Time Warner's publishing operation also
had a laggard direct sales arm that was dragging down results, the
Book-of-the-Month Club. That unit is also going through a revamp to
meet the challenges of online retailers and discount chains, and is
being merged with Doubleday Direct, the book club owned by the
German media conglomerate Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's stock, which has been moving in tandem with the
shares of AOL, was off $5.75 at $90 on the New York Stock Exchange,
while AOL shares were down $3.81\ at $62.68\.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1838 </TRAILER>
