<DOCNO> APW20000412.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador Writes U.N. Catnap Guide  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations is known for its
marathon talkfests that can put even the most seasoned diplomats to
sleep. Now there's hope for an antidote.
</P>
<P>
   Former French Ambassador Alain Dejammet has done a service to
all his colleagues by writing a 14-page, tongue-in-cheek guide to
the best places at U.N. headquarters to escape the boredom and
catch a catnap.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sleeping at the United Nations,'' a pocket-sized guide in
French with a little kitty on the cover, was one of Dejammet's
parting gifts before leaving the post in March for a new
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, the dry-witted ambassador ranks 12 lounges,
consultation rooms and sitting areas around the U.N. complex on a
scale of 1-20 for their comfort, light, calmness and frequency of
use.
</P>
<P>
   Dejammet then gives an overall ranking, ranging from
''ill-advised,'' (known by its symbol of !!!) to ''exceptional''
(which gets a ranking).
</P>
<P>
   ''Impression of being in an abandoned monastery, in spite of the
snores,'' Dejammet wrote of the periodical room at the U.N.
library, which got three stars: very agreeable.
</P>
<P>
   The conference room of the European Union liaison office got
high marks for comfort: ''Abundance of coffee and delicious little
cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But it lost points for calmness. ''Even without meetings, a nap
can be interrupted at any moment by the sudden arrival of an
Eurocrat demanding details of the French position concerning the
promotion of rights of young girls in crises affecting landlocked
countries,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Meditation Room, which sits across the street from U.N.
headquarters, got the worst score. Its blue Chagall windows evoke a
''draculesque crypt,'' while the squeaking sneakers of tourists
allow for little meditation, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Only the French office at the United Nations, which is used for
private consultations, earned four stars and the unflinching praise
of Dejammet who evoked a Matisse masterpiece in saying it was where
everything was ''luxe, calme et volupte.''
</P>
<P>
   ''One speaks of old ministers who never reappeared after a
conference in the 'little bureau','' he said nostalgically.
</P>
<P>
   It got marks of 20 all around, ''but the price to pay was the
risk incurred of being a member of the French delegation,'' added
Dejammet, who himself wasn't known to have dozed off during long
debates or conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The book could be a best seller among U.N. diplomats -- but
Dejammet hasn't disclosed whether he plans to publish it. He first
shared it with the French newspaper Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Ambassador Nancy Soderberg said Wednesday copies had
already been circulated and discussed among council members and
that she considered it a ''whimsical legacy'' that Dejammet had
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time I go into a corner of the U.N. I will think of
Alain Dejammet with renewed delight'' she told reporters. Dejammet
was one of the hardest working diplomats at the United Nations
''and no one begrudges him a moment's rest in a quiet corner where
you all can't find him,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1839 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Earnings Double in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones &AMP; Co. reported Wednesday that its
income nearly doubled in the first quarter of the year, driven by
big gains in advertising revenues from The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting a profit from the sale of a financial publishing
unit, Dow Jones earned $79.2 million during the three months ended
March 31, or 88 cents per share, beating analyst forecasts of 80
cents per share, as reported by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Including the gain from selling Dow Jones Financial Publishing
Corp., the company had net earnings of $88.7 million, or 98 cents
per share.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period a year ago, the company earned $40.9 million
or 44 cents per share before a special gain, and net earnings of
$51.5 million or 56 cents per share including the gain.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the New York-based Dow Jones rose 25 cents to $72.12{
in trading at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones' revenues jumped 25 percent during the quarter to $579
million from $462 million in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues from publishing, which makes up the majority of the
company's business, rose 35 percent compared to a year ago thanks
to significant gains in advertising in The Journal, where ad
lineage grew 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas editions of the paper also did well. Dow Jones also
reported a 23 percent gain in ad lineage in its European edition
and 27 percent gains in its Asian edition.
</P>
<P>
   The company also reported a 10 percent increase in revenues from
electronic publishing, which include Dow Jones Newswires, Dow
Jones' interest in its news database with Reuters PLC called
Factiva, as well as online operations such as WSJ.com. The number
of subscribers to WSJ.com grew to 438,000 as of March 31, up 55
percent from the same time a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growth in revenues from electronic publishing,
income from the division fell 37 percent to $8.5 million as the
company continued to make new investments in building up those
businesses. Dow Jones has said it is considering issuing a separate
class of stock to track some or all of its Internet assets.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the company's Ottawa community newspaper group rose
9 percent to $81 million amid a 7 percent gain in advertising
lineage.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Dow Jones broke out results for its joint
ventures with Hearst Corp. in SmartMoney magazine, SmartMoney.com,
and a newly launched parenting magazine called Offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones' stake produced revenues of $7.2 million, up 31
percent from the same time a year ago, while its share of the
operating loss was $3.6 million, due to larger investments to build
up SmartMoney.com, compared to operating profits of $500,000 a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.dowjones.com
</P>
</TEXT>
