<HEADLINE> Labor Opposes U.S.-China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As thousands of labor activists rallied
Wednesday against a U.S.-China trade bill, Commerce Secretary
William Daley released a report showing the measure would benefit
every state.
</P>
<P>
   The union members protested outside the Capitol while their
leaders pressed lawmakers to vote against a bill that would give
permanent normal trade status to China. They claim the measure
would cost U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James P. Hoffa told some 5,000 cheering
members that corporations supporting the legislation have lost
their moral compass. He said China should be forced to improve its
human rights record before being granted the trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to put China on probation'' before granting them
trade favors, Hoffa said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Daley released a study for every state
showing how each would benefit from enhanced trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Commerce Department said Washington state would
see major tariff reductions for aircraft, paper and wood products;
Pennsylvania would gain from the removal of import restrictions for
construction and medical equipment; and Louisiana -- where half the
current exports to China are agricultural products -- no longer
would have to compete against export subsidies for China's
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce officials planned to distribute the reports to
lawmakers before they head home for next week's spring recess.
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill would end annual congressional review of China's
trade status and ease China's entry into the Geneva-based World
Trade Organization. It is supported by President Clinton but
opposed by a mix of labor, environmental groups and some human
rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a partisan issue, as illustrated by the speakers at
the rally, who ranged from socialist Rep. Bernard Sanders of
Vermont to conservative Reform Party presidential hopeful Pat
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Washington, a 23-year-old General Motors Corp. worker
from Warren, Mich., who missed four days of work to come to the
protest, said those who support the trade bill will have to answer
to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Senate and the House of Representatives, we just want them
to listen to us,'' he said. ''We can vote them out of office. We
can make a point just as well as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley said labor groups and environmentalists have a ''knee
jerk'' reaction against trade, blaming it for a variety of ills
when in fact technology improvements have more to do with job
losses than trade.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is scheduled for a House vote the week of May 22. No
vote has been scheduled in the Senate, where it has wide bipartisan
support. A majority of House Democrats are believed to oppose the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Department state-by-state studies:
http://chinapntr.gov/statebystate8.htm
</P>
<P>
   White House working group on China: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign against bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
