<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Slide for a Second Day  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bonds tumbled Wednesday for a second
straight day as traders continued to snap up bonds of corporations
and agencies such as Fannie Mae, which offer higher returns.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dipped } point,
or $7.50 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, rose to 5.81 percent from 5.76 percent late
Tuesday. On Monday, the yield had fallen to an 11-month low of 5.66
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Traders were looking for safe harbors for their money as
technology and blue-chip stocks plunged Wednesday. But with returns
relatively low on government bonds, investors looked to high-grade
corporate bonds and other relatively safe securities, such as the
mortgage-backed bonds of quasigovernment agencies Fannie Mae and
Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, short-term notes fell 1/16 point to
3/32 point, while intermediate notes fell \ point to { point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.81 percent as the
discount fell 0.01 percentage point from Tuesday to 5.66 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.05 percent, as the discount fell 0.05
percentage point to 5.80 percent. One-year yields were 6.11 percent
as the discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 5.80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 5.94 percent from 5.75 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 5/32 at 95 29/32. The average yield to
maturity was 5.92 percent, up from 5.91 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
