<HEADLINE> Expectation Shadows Gen. Powell,  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Five years after he ruled out running for
president and three years since be began talking almost full-time
about children, retired Gen. Colin Powell still gets The Questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Um, thank you,'' he began Wednesday when the topic inevitably
arose about his political future, or non-future, or his interest in
a Cabinet job, or not.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never had any political inclination,'' he told the
American Society of Newspaper Editors at its annual convention,
stressing ''never.'' ''Political life is not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said later he would consider any nonpolitical role
offered to him by a president or president-elect, keeping alive the
possibility he'd end up in the Cabinet if Republican George W. Bush
wins the presidential election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Powell, a registered Republican, ruled out being
Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff does not deny
his popularity. Indeed, he recognizes it as a commodity and puts it
to use as head of America's Promise, an organization for children
formed in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But he said his consistently high rankings in public esteem, as
measured by polls, have never been tested in the political arena
and therefore don't mean anything politically. ''That number you
always see is a popularity number,'' he said. ''It's not a
political number.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he hasn't had a moment's regret since deciding
against running for president after giving the idea much thought in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to bring a certain passion and commitment to it, and
you have to have a certain need for it,'' he said. He said he
realized he did not possess those qualities for politics.
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't been shy about weighing in on some political
issues. Powell recently urged members of Congress not to amend the
Constitution to ban flag burning and he spoke forcefully Wednesday
in favor of granting China normal trade status on a permanent
basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
