<HEADLINE> Clinton To Protect Giant Sequoias  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ancient groves of giant sequoia redwoods will
come under permanent federal protection under an order to be signed
by President Clinton, setting aside 355,000 acres of California
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to announce his decision Saturday in a visit to
Sequoia National Forest in central California, White House
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have campaigned for years for greater
protection for the sequoias, some of which are 3,000 years old and
measure 100 feet around the base. But critics complain that
Clinton's announcement is politically motivated, threatens
recreation and will cost precious timber jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is nothing more than political posturing,'' said Rep.
George Radanovich, R-Calif., whose district includes part of the
proposed monument. ''I think it's more for a legacy and
presidential politics than for the health of the sequoias.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists warmly welcomed Clinton's expected
announcement but said the key would be the extent of restrictions
imposed on the Forest Service for cutting trees and building roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really are going to have to wait a little bit to see how
much latitude he leaves the Forest Service,'' said Nathaniel
Lawrence, senior attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council. ''The president is going to have to help them by tying
their hands so they don't go off and do what they reflexively do.''
</P>
<P>
   The trees will be designated a protected monument under the 1906
Antiquities Act, which allows presidents -- without congressional
approval -- to safeguard objects of historic and scientific
interest. It is the same law that President Theodore Roosevelt used
to set aside the Grand Canyon in 1908 and President Carter invoked
to establish large sections of Alaska wilderness in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has angered some western lawmakers and local officials
by invoking the Antiquities Act on previous occasions to set aside
millions of acres of land for special protection.
</P>
<P>
   Radanovich said the sequoia decision ''exemplifies the reason
why we should alter the Antiquities Act.'' The congressman is one
of three lawmakers sponsoring a bill to block the monument with an
18-month federal study of how to protect the trees.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of California's remaining giant sequoias are part
of Sequoia National Forest, outside the protective boundaries of
nearby Kings Canyon, Sequoia and Yosemite national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ancestors of the giant sequoias once grew as far east as
Colorado and Wyoming; now these precious trees are only found on
the west slope of the Sierra Nevadas,'' Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman said in a letter to Clinton recommending creation of
Sequoia National Monument. ''To insure the permanent survival of
these ancient giants we must provide them with permanent
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill last year to alter the Antiquities Act was approved by
the House but died in the Senate. It would have limited a
presidential order for monuments to 5,000 acres, rather than the
current designations without any limits on size.
</P>
<P>
   ''By our bill, we were trying to get the president to focus on
the science of the issue,'' Radanovich said. ''This helps Clinton
secure environmental support for Gore -- the support of the radical
environmental groups that advise this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have acknowledged that Clinton's use of
the Antiquities Act is part of an attempt to leave an environmental
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The sequoia announcement will be made during a trip that begins
Friday with an education speech and political fund-raisers in
Atlanta and then moves west to California. After visiting Sequoia
National Forest, Clinton will continue to Los Angeles for a
fund-raiser Saturday night with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After a day off Sunday, Clinton will begin a two-day tour to
encourage investment in areas of the country that are not
benefitting from the economic good times. He will start his trip
Monday in East Palo Alto, Calif., which has been left behind from
Silicon Valley's prosperity. Later that day, the president will
visit a Navajo Indian reservation at Shiprock, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   He will conclude his trip Tuesday with an appearance in Chicago
at a high-technology show, COMDEX, where he will encourage efforts
to narrow the ''digital divide'' between computer haves and
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will return to Washington on Tuesday and set out again
Wednesday, this time to help dedicate a memorial in Oklahoma City
in honor of the 168 people killed in the Oklahoma City bombing five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service: http://www.fs.fed.us/
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service: http://www.nps.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
