<HEADLINE> Key Events in Sam Sheppard Case  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Key events in the Sam Sheppard murder case:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- July 4, 1954: Marilyn Sheppard, 31, four months pregnant,
beaten to death in bed in Bay Village, a Cleveland suburb.
</P>
<P>
   -- July 30, 1954: Her husband, Dr. Sam Sheppard, arrested.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dec. 21, 1954: Sheppard convicted of murder, sentenced to life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nov. 8, 1959: Richard Eberling, former window washer for the
Sheppards, caught burglarizing homes in Cleveland. In his
possession are two of Mrs. Sheppard's rings.
</P>
<P>
   -- July 16, 1964: Sheppard released from prison after federal
judge finds he was denied fair trial because jurors not shielded
from heavy publicity.
</P>
<P>
   -- June 6, 1966: U.S. Supreme Court grants Sheppard new trial.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nov. 16, 1966: Jury acquits Sheppard at retrial.
</P>
<P>
   -- April 6, 1970: Sheppard dies of liver failure at 46.
</P>
<P>
   -- July 7, 1984: Eberling convicted of killing elderly widow
Ethel Durkin for her $1.5 million estate. Gets life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 19, 1995: Sheppard's son, Sam Reese Sheppard, files
wrongful imprisonment lawsuit against the state of Ohio through his
father's estate.
</P>
<P>
   -- April 29, 1996: Durkin's former nurse says Eberling told her
he killed Mrs. Sheppard. Eberling denies making such a statement.
</P>
<P>
   -- Feb. 4, 1997: Family lawyer says DNA tests show blood found in
Sheppard's home could be Eberling's.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sept. 17, 1997: Sheppard's body exhumed and tissue samples
taken for DNA testing. Body later cremated and put back next to
Mrs. Sheppard in cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jan. 13, 1998: Attorneys argue before Ohio Supreme Court about
whether wrongful imprisonment lawsuit should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   -- March 5, 1998: Family attorney says DNA tests on Sheppard's
body exclude him from bloodstains around the Sheppard home.
</P>
<P>
   -- July 25, 1998: Eberling dies in Ohio prison.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dec. 2, 1998: The Ohio Supreme Court clears way for trial on
wrongful imprisonment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 5, 1999: Mrs. Sheppard's body exhumed on order of county
prosecutors, along with fetus she was carrying. DNA and other tests
performed. Prosecutors say they point to Sheppard as killer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jan. 31, 2000: Wrongful imprisonment trial begins with a week
of hearings before Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Court Judge Ronald
Suster as attorneys try to limit evidence.
</P>
<P>
   -- Feb. 14, 2000: Opening statements delivered at wrongful
imprisonment trial.
</P>
<P>
   -- April 12, 2000: Jury rejects claim that Sheppard was
wrongfully imprisoned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
