<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Rose': An Exhausting Account  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Critic
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Survivor.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly isn't a better word to describe the title
character in ''Rose,'' Martin Sherman's exhausting account of one
woman's journey through 20th-century Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm inching towards dust, and sometimes I wish it'd hurry,''
this 80-year-old wonder says, commenting on her imminent demise.
But before she goes, Rose has a story to tell, a solo saga that
fills Broadway's Lyceum Theater for more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trip packed with so much detail -- and enough monumental
incidents -- that you often lose sight of the character and focus
instead on the next big event that will envelop her. For all its
narrative, the tale is strangely superficial, despite the
emotionalism of its subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Rose is played by Olympia Dukakis, an actress of
enormous charm and commonsense, not to mention stamina and
solidity. She anchors Sherman's drama even when it threatens to get
overwhelmed by history.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis sits for the entire play on a wooden bench in Rose's
present-day Miami Beach apartment -- and talks. The old lady is
sitting shiva, mourning a death that is never fully explained until
the end of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Rose is back in her Russian childhood, describing
her parents. There's a hypochondriac father, who one day took to
his bed and then never stopped dying. And her saint-like mother
who, even in the face of famine, made sure there was food on the
table. And there are the pogroms, Cossacks on big horses and with
big whips, destroying everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   These details are among the best in the play, but Sherman has
eight decades of history to cover, so he quickly moves on. When
Rose follows her brother to Warsaw, she meets Yussel, a painter and
the one true love of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Their marriage as well as their young daughter's life ends in
the Warsaw Ghetto during World War II. After the war, Rose finds
herself in Germany and then on a ship, traveling to Palestine. On
board, she meets an American named Sonny Rose. Her stay in the
Mideast is brief, but she marries Sonny and gets the unlikely full
name of Rose Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny brings Rose to America and a new life, renting beach
chairs along the boardwalk at Atlantic City. After the birth of a
son, the marriage falters, but Rose doesn't, eventually getting a
job managing the kitchen at the Majestic Hotel. When Atlantic City
declines, Rose finds new employment -- and eventually a new husband
-- in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's son, Abbie, finds his way to Israel -- and eventually so
does Rose, as a visitor. She becomes embroiled in disputes over the
West Bank, and finds herself a supporter of Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
   Alienated by the violence, Rose wonders where she fits in, if
not in Israel. ''Maybe there is a joy in not belonging ... a
restless people produces restless minds,'' she sighs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ''Rose'' has to depend on the considerable talent of
Dukakis to turn this history lesson into a celebration of the
toughness of the human spirit. The actress embodies that strength,
something that ''Rose'' -- the play -- only hints at.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1910 </TRAILER>
