<HEADLINE> Bolivian Protests Subside  </HEADLINE>
By PETER McFARREN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- Shops and schools in Cochabamba reopened
Wednesday as a week of violent anti-government protests that had
shut down Bolivia's third largest city subsided and a nationwide
strike to protest a presidential ''state of siege'' decree fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   In La Paz, several hundred students threw stones at police who
responded with tear gas in the second straight day of clashes. The
skirmishes lasted several hours before winding down.
</P>
<P>
   But protests eased across most of the country after the
government and protest leaders reached a deal late Monday to end
the violent protests led by thousands of farmers and workers angry
over government proposed water rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bolivian capital, turnout was meager for a 24-hour
general strike called Wednesday by the Bolivian Workers
Confederation, the country's largest union confederation, in
defiance of the stage of siege decreed by President Hugo Banzer on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Banzer called for the security crackdown after weekend protests
turned violent, leaving six dead. Still in effect, the state of
siege suspended many constitutional guarantees, allowing police to
detain protest leaders without a warrant, restricting travel and
political activity and establishing a curfew.
</P>
<P>
   The protests erupted April 3 in Cochabamba, 350 miles east of La
Paz, over the water price hike and then spread to rural regions,
fueled by the economic crisis in South America's poorest nation.
Cochabamba was isolated and shut down by roadblocks and violence
for a week, and peasants in the countryside shut down virtually all
intercity traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, schools reopened in the city of 500,000, as
did businesses and markets.
</P>
<P>
   For Banzer, the weeklong protests have been the biggest test of
his presidency since assuming elected office in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Talks mediated by the Roman Catholic Church continued Wednesday
between the government and worker groups to end any remaining
protests. Road blocks continued Wednesday in an area north of La
Paz where violent confrontations took place over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The protests began with a strike by a Water Rights Committee
against water price increases of 20 to 80 percent, which the
government said were necessary to expand the city's water supply
system and help build a $70 million dollar tunnel to carry water
across the Andes Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement that ended the protests, the government
canceled the contract for the water expansion projection with an
international water consortium, and it revised a water law to end
fees for well water.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economic crisis Bolivia and the region has been going
through no doubt contributed to the problems here,'' Information
Minister Ronald MacLean told The Associated Press. ''When a crisis
hits us we do not have a cushion to absorb its impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 1911 </TRAILER>
