<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French ambassador's legacy: best places to snooze at the UN  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations is known for its
marathon talkfests that can put even the most seasoned diplomats to
sleep. Now there's hope for an antidote.
</P>
<P>
   Former French Ambassador Alain Dejammet has done a service to
all his colleagues by writing a 14-page, tongue-in-cheek guide to
the best places at U.N. headquarters to escape the boredom and
catch a catnap.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sleeping at the United Nations,'' a pocket-sized guide in
French with a little kitty on the cover, was one of Dejammet's
parting gifts before leaving the post in March for a new
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, the dry-witted ambassador ranks 12 lounges,
consultation rooms and sitting areas around the U.N. complex on a
scale of 1-20 for their comfort, light, calmness and frequency of
use.
</P>
<P>
   Dejammet then gives an overall ranking, ranging from
''ill-advised,'' (known by its symbol of !!!) to ''exceptional''
(which gets a **** ranking).
</P>
<P>
   ''Impression of being in an abandoned monastery, in spite of the
snores,'' Dejammet wrote of the periodical room at the U.N.
library, which got three stars: very agreeable.
</P>
<P>
   The conference room of the European Union liaison office got
high marks for comfort: ''Abundance of coffee and delicious little
cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But it lost points for calmness. ''Even without meetings, a nap
can be interrupted at any moment by the sudden arrival of an
Eurocrat demanding details of the French position concerning the
promotion of rights of young girls in crises affecting landlocked
countries,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Meditation Room, which sits across the street from U.N.
headquarters, got the worst score. Its blue Chagall windows evoke a
''draculesque crypt,'' while the squeaking sneakers of tourists
allow for little meditation, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Only the French office at the United Nations, which is used for
private consultations, earned four stars and the unflinching praise
of Dejammet who evoked a Matisse masterpiece in saying it was where
everything was ''luxe, calme et volupte.''
</P>
<P>
   ''One speaks of old ministers who never reappeared after a
conference in the 'little bureau','' he said nostalgically.
</P>
<P>
   It got marks of 20 all around, ''but the price to pay was the
risk incurred of being a member of the French delegation,'' added
Dejammet, who himself wasn't known to have dozed off during long
debates or conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The book could be a best seller among U.N. diplomats -- but
Dejammet hasn't disclosed whether he plans to publish it. He first
shared it with the French newspaper Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Ambassador Nancy Soderberg said Wednesday copies had
already been circulated and discussed among council members and
that she considered it a ''whimsical legacy'' that Dejammet had
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time I go into a corner of the U.N. I will think of
Alain Dejammet with renewed delight,'' she told reporters. Dejammet
was one of the hardest working diplomats at the United Nations
''and no one begrudges him a moment's rest in a quiet corner where
you all can't find him,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 1915 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upstate officials call for federal help on Indian land claims  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials from seven upstate New York counties
lobbied lawmakers on Capitol Hill Wednesday for federal help with
their battle over Indian land claims.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, a Democrat, and Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a
Republican, pledged support with getting negotiations over the
Oneida land claim back on track. Those talks broke down last week.
And the lawmakers promised to again press the Justice Department to
remove landowners there from a federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to try and ask the Justice Department to be more
of a mediator than a plaintiff, in other words to recognize that
there are two sides to this,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas filed a lawsuit in 1974 seeking the return of
250,000 acres in Oneida and Madison counties they claim were
illegally purchased by the state. In 1998, the federal government
sided with the Oneidas and filed an amended complaint asking that
20,000 landowners in the two counties be added as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have said they have no intention of removing
the property owners from their land. But that has done little to
soothe fears.
</P>
<P>
   ''Landowners are innocent third parties to these land claims and
need to be left out of these claims ... so they don't have to worry
about in any way the security of their homes and their
businesses,'' Oneida County Executive Ralph Eannace Jr. said after
meeting with Schumer, Boehlert and staff members from a handful of
other New York lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Oneida County, elected representatives from
Madison, Cayuga, Seneca, Greene, Onondaga and Sullivan counties
were in Washington Wednesday. The county lawmakers also met with
officials from the Justice Department's Indian Resources Section.
</P>
<P>
   Justice spokeswoman Christine Romano said Wednesday ''we are
convinced settlement is in the best interest of all the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Oneida Indian officials did not immediately return a phone call
seeking comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There are several land claim battles brewing in New York
covering a wide swath of land upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a federal court jury in Syracuse recommended a $36.9
million award to the Cayugas to compensate the tribe for 64,015
acres of lost ancestral lands in Cayuga and Seneca counties. A
final judgment on the award will be made by a judge this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Madison and Oneida counties, the U.S. Supreme Court found in
1985 that the land was taken illegally and ruled the Oneidas were
entitled to compensation. Last week, out-of-court negotiations
collapsed. Settlement Master Ron Riccio called an impasse saying
not every party was committed to the process.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, from Oneida County, said he was encouraged because
federal officials had told him that the Oneida Indians were subject
to the Clean Water Act and needed a federal permit to dredge in
Oneida Lake. The Indian tribe has claimed that they did not need
federal permits.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said he was hopeful negations cold resume over the
Oneida dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best way is negotiation not litigation,'' Boehlert said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bullock who attended the meeting for Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're not at the table you can't make any progress. At the
very least we would like to see negotiations start up again,''
Moynihan's chief of staff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-12-00 1916 </TRAILER>
