<DOCNO> APW20000412.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine arrested in methamphetamine ring that operated from Phillybarbershop  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODBURY, N.J. (AP) -- Nine people were arrested Wednesday in a
series of raids that authorities said dismantled a methamphetamine
ring that operated out of a south Philadelphia barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Louis Santaguida, 53, of Philadelphia, the
brother of noted criminal defense attorney Joseph Santaguida, who
has defended numerous people accused of being members of the
Philadelphia-southern New Jersey mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Two pounds of methamphetamine, 8.5 pounds of marijuana, $193,000
in cash and three firearms were seized in the raids, according to
U.S. Attorney Robert Cleary, who announced the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We dismantled a major methamphetamine ring that has, up until
now, operated unscathed in Pennsylvania and New Jersey,'' Cleary
said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests wrapped up an 11-month probe that began with a tip
developed in a drug arrest in Clementon. While they wouldn't say
who gave it, representatives of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration, the Philadelphia district attorney's office and the
Gloucester County Prosecutor said the information led them to a
drug ring centered at Rocco and Elmer's Hair Styling, located on
Seventh Street in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hair cutting was not the chief business at Rocco and
Elmer's,'' said Cleary, who called it a front for the alleged ring.
Philadelphia District Attorney Lynne Abraham said the ring was
selling ''poison in our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Using telephone wiretaps, undercover agents and surveillance,
agents cracked the ring, Cleary said. On six different occasions,
undercover agents bought ''meth'' or ''crank'' -- as it is known
among users -- from members of the ring for up to $12,000 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects used code language to disguise their conversations,
but one wiretap caught Louis Grosso, 36, of Havertown, Pa., asking,
''You got anybody that needs meth? The crank, the meth?''
</P>
<P>
   The first buy came June 17 at the Lindenwold apartment of
Richard Zammer, 34, according to a criminal complaint filed against
Louis Santaguida and naming the others.
</P>
<P>
   The supplier was identified as Sammy Bonaccurso, 55, of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Santaguida and Billy Cicalese, 54, of Philadelphia,
distributed the methamphetamine to the others for sale in New
Jersey and Pennsylvania, according to a criminal complaint filed
against Santaguida.
</P>
<P>
   All nine were charged with conspiracy to distribute and
possession with intent to distribute methamphetamine. Each could
face 10 years to life in prison, and $4 million in fines, if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   One suspect remained at large. He is Thomas Sees, 36, of
Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the nine charged federally, Joan Gallagher, 35,
of Cherry Hill, was charged with third-degree possession of
marijuana and methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary would not say whether a mob link was suspected in the
drug sales. Asked about Louis Santaguida's relationship to the
lawyer Santaguida, he would say only: ''I don't really want to get
into that. People's familial relationships are not what this case
is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any of the suspects were members of organized crime,
Cleary said: ''Not as charged.'' Joseph Santaguida, who has
defended alleged mob boss Joseph ''Skinny Joey'' Merlino, couldn't
be reached for comment about the arrests; he did not return a
telephone call to his law office.
</P>
<P>
   They were arrested at 17 locations -- their homes and/or
businesses, Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Louis Santaguida, Cicalese, Bonaccurso, Grosso,
Sees and Zammer, the suspects were identified as Vincent Gori, age
unavailable, of Turnersville; Theodore Iannone, 43, of Egg Harbor
Township; and Dominick Imbesi, 49, of Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
