<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Franks takes lead over Gormley in county endorsements for GOPprimary  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- In a primary race in which the candidates
are little known, securing endorsements from county Republican
organizations could be crucial in deciding who becomes the GOP
nominee to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In this aspect of the contest, U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley
Heights, has a clear lead over state Sen. William Gormley,
R-Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Franks won the nomination in Bergen County last weekend, the
largest prize of the state's 21 counties. There are 98,000
registered Republicans there, almost 12 percent of the state's
total.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Bergen is an important win. Last week, Franks
and Gormley were neck-and-neck with county endorsements and both
were competitive in Bergen, where Gormley had the backing of a
popular county executive and three Republican state senators.
</P>
<P>
   With the win there, Franks comes away with party endorsements in
six counties representing 275,000 registered Republicans, compared
with four counties endorsing Gormley that represent 169,000
registered Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first run was endorsements and county support, and Franks
got the big prize, which was Bergen County,'' said Republican
political analyst Steve Salmore. ''At this stage he is up.''
</P>
<P>
   It is worth something, political analysts agree, but it does not
end the contest.
</P>
<P>
   On defensive tactics, the Bergen County win was gratifying for
Franks, who has managed to prevent his Margate opponent from
winning any endorsements north of Trenton. Meanwhile, Franks has
secured endorsements in the southern New Jersey counties of
Burlington and Cumberland.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican organizations in a third of the state's 21
counties, including large GOP counties like Morris and Monmouth,
have not endorsed a favorite, and will not. They will remain
''open.'' And they represent roughly one of every three registered
Republicans in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Those open primary zones provide plenty of opportunity for
Gormley, Essex County executive James Treffinger or renegade
Republican Murray Sabrin to draw the votes needed to reduce the
margins that Franks may win in the counties where his name gets
preferential treatment on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Also, political analysts disagree on just how important county
endorsements will prove to be on June 6. Until recently such ballot
endorsement was prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Further, there is the unknown factor of how many new
unaffiliated voters will be drawn to the primary election as the
contest heats up.
</P>
<P>
   As of November, there were 843,534 registered Republicans in New
Jersey, compared with 1.1 million registered Democrats. Swamping
both are the 2.5 million registered voters who have chosen not to
list themselves with either party. They are free to walk into the
primary election booth and to vote in either party's primary
without notice, and their potential impact in a year with a high
voter turnout can be large.
</P>
<P>
   ''Generally in a presidential election year the turnout seems to
be greater, and this year seems to be no different,'' said state
GOP chairman Garabed Haytaian. ''It is not just the (county)
activists who are going to be involved on Primary Day, it is
everyone who comes into play, including independents who might want
to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks' county endorsements give him an edge with 275,000
Republican voters but those counties also are home to 900,000
unaffiliated voters, and any fraction of them could affect the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Salmore noted, the most potent spoiler -- with a
credible chance of an upset win -- is Treffinger, and he will do
most of his spoiling in Franks country. Treffinger has secured the
Essex and Passaic county endorsements, accounting for 89,000
registered Republicans. And he is favored to win endorsement in
Hudson County.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Jim McQueeny said Treffinger has no incentive
to drop out, even if the primary race seems hopeless, because he is
building a base to run for Congress in Essex and Passaic counties
in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
