<HEADLINE> House Chaplain Mass Angers Democrats  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Democratic congressman who also is Roman
Catholic said Wednesday the Republican Party trivialized the
worship service of his faith by organizing a Mass in honor of the
new House chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on the House floor, Rep. Jerry Kleczka of Wisconsin
called it inappropriate for a political organization to sponsor
events using the church and its rituals as if they were the same as
a fund-raising dinner or rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''For them to use the Catholic church in a continuing attempt to
attract Catholic voters is, I think, disgusting,'' Kleczka said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Kleczka was particularly offended that Republican National
Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson and former Rep. Bill Paxon,
R-N.Y., the one-time head of House Republicans' campaign arm, were
readers during Tuesday's service.
</P>
<P>
   RNC spokesman Mike Collins repeated that the Mass, and a
reception afterward at St. Peter's Church on Capitol Hill, were
never an attempt to score political points but only an opportunity
to meet the Rev. Daniel P. Coughlin, who was appointed last month
as the first Catholic House chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think his constituents will find it very interesting that
Congressman Kleczka will find a Mass disgusting,'' Collins said.
''He should be ashamed of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Catholic GOP congressmen were invited, though all lawmakers
were given media advisories.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats had accused GOP leaders of anti-Catholic bigotry
because they at first appeared to pass over a priest with broader
support in favor of a Protestant for the chaplain post.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., repeatedly denied the
charges. His initial choice, a Protestant minister, eventually
withdrew and the speaker unexpectedly appointed Coughlin, from
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Democrats are accusing the RNC of organizing the Mass and
reception as a way to mend fences with Catholics, a large block of
voters who were bruised by the highly divisive and bitter selection
process. Even some GOP aides said they view the events as an
embarrassing blunder by the RNC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
