<HEADLINE> Israel: UN To Determine Border  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak is ready to let the
United Nations determine the final border between Israel and
Lebanon, a senior Israeli official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The offer -- a rare Israeli concession -- is aimed at pressing
Lebanon to secure the border once Israel pulls out.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he will withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon by
July, preferably as part of an agreement with Lebanon and Syria --
the main power in Lebanon -- but unilaterally if need be. Israel has
occupied parts of Lebanon since a 1982 invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli official, who spoke on condition he not be named,
said Israel regards the international border as the line to which
it withdrew its forces after a brief invasion of Lebanon in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the United Nations affirmed the legitimacy of that
border, said the official, who briefed reporters on Barak's plane
as the prime minister returned from talks with President Clinton in
Washington. Israel is willing, however, to let U.N. inspectors make
the final ruling that the pullback is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is an argument about ten meters (yards) here or
there, we will retreat,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United Nations has yet to comment on the proposal,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan recently told Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy he would explore ways of making the withdrawal
a success.
</P>
<P>
   Syria and Lebanon have said they will only recognize the
withdrawal as valid if it is carried out according to U.N.
resolutions. Those resolutions call on Lebanon to prevent attacks
on Israel from its soil -- a commitment the Lebanese have so far
refused to make.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with Syria have broken down over Israel's refusal to offer
a prior commitment to withdraw from all of the Golan Heights, a
strategic plateau captured from Syria in the 1967 war. Barak has
made strong indications that he plans to return the heights, but
wants to retain control over a freshwater lake that supplies 40
percent of Israel's water.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, however, is concerned Syria will allow or even encourage
Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas to attack targets inside Israel
after a pullout from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the Israeli official said, Israel expects
international backing if it has to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   Barak secured U.S. backing for the withdrawal in his Washington
meetings with Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is strange that a country is criticized for withdrawing
from another country,'' Albright said of reactions from Lebanon and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon has also said that if a withdrawal is to conform to the
U.N. resolutions it should account for the hundreds of thousands of
Palestinian refugees in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak agreed that claim would no longer hold, the
official said, should Israel and the Palestinians meet a May
deadline to agree on the outline of a permanent peace treaty -- an
outline that would address the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon on Wednesday, Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas
said they used rockets in an attack on militiamen of the South
Lebanon Army at their Rihan outpost on the edge of an
Israeli-occupied enclave, scoring direct hits.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese security officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the afternoon attack killed one militiaman and wounded
another, who was evacuated to Israel for treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2003 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
