<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Distributor Loses Burger King  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID KOENIG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- AmeriServe Food Distribution Inc. said Wednesday
it will lose its account with 5,800 Burger King restaurants,
costing the bankrupt company $2.2 billion of its $6.2 billion in
annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriServe chief executive Ronald Rittenmeyer said the company
would lay off 1,400 to 1,600 of its roughly 6,000 employees, or
about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is considering whether it wants to continue as
a stand-along company, merge with a partner or sell some of its
assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriServe filed for bankruptcy protection from creditors on
Jan. 31. It received $150 million in temporary financing from its
two largest customers, Burger King and Tricon Global Restaurants
Inc., which operates Pizza Hut, KFC and Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ''While this is unfortunate, you sometimes look at these things
as not a shock,'' said Rittenmeyer of the Burger King defection,
which had been rumored for weeks. ''We will be a smaller company,
but $4 billion is not small.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions that left the company with a heavy debt load caused
the company to miss payments to suppliers, resulting in spot
shortages of food and paper products at some restaurants. The
troubles prompted several customers, including some Burger King
franchisees, to switch to other distributors.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriServe, based in the Dallas suburb of Addison, said
deliveries of food products to Burger King will end in July.
Rittenmeyer said it would not affect the temporary financing, which
runs into August. The company is talking with Chase and Deutsche
Bank about permanent financing.
</P>
<P>
   Rittenmeyer said the company probably won't emerge from
bankruptcy this year.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Burger King leaves Tricon's three restaurant chains
accounting for more than half of AmeriServe's business. Other major
customers are Long John Silver's and Chick-fil-A. Rittenmeyer said
all were committed to stay with AmeriServe.
</P>
<P>
   Tricon and Burger King did not return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriServe got in trouble by expanding too rapidly, with two
major acquisitions in the late 1990s, Rittenmeyer said. Analysts,
however, predict the pattern will be repeated by other
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's been the history of this industry -- ambitious companies
will attempt to roll up the market faster than is prudent,'' said
Rajan Chaudhry, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston. ''They
end up in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaudry said the industry leader, Houston-based Sysco, ''has
been successful because it's balanced its growth and handled
acquisitions carefully. They've been No. 1 for about 20 years, but
No. 2 is always changing. It used to be AmeriServe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
