<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Panel To Probe LAPD  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA DEUTSCH, AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In the wake of a massive scandal in which
officers are alleged to have framed innocent people, the city
Police Commission on Wednesday named an independent panel to
investigate the department and make recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The citizens of Los Angeles have rightly sought an independent
body to investigate the corruption within the police department,''
said Gerald L. Chaleff, president of the Police Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Rampart Independent Review Panel, 24 experts including
attorneys, professors, management consultants and veterans of the
Christopher Commission probe of the Los Angeles Police Department,
plans to issue its recommendations in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen Rampart station officers have quit, been fired
or relieved of duty amid allegations that an anti-gang unit framed,
beat and shot innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty criminal cases involving arrests by Rampart officers have
already been dismissed, and District Attorney Gil Garcetti said
Wednesday he will seek the dismissal of 10 more on Thursday. The
majority of the new cases involved arrests by disgraced ex-officer
Rafael Perez and partner Nino Durden.
</P>
<P>
   The city is expecting an avalanche of lawsuits as a result of
the scandal. Mayor Richard Riordan proposed using the city's
tobacco settlement money to cover liability. But last month the
City Council rejected his idea and voted to set up a reserve fund,
which remains empty as the mayor tries to reconcile it with his
budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the new panel by the Police Commission, the
civilian body that sets department policy, was immediately
criticized by the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern
California. The ACLU said the panel was not truly independent and
it must release its report directly to the public to be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   The model for the new panel will be the Christopher Commission,
which investigated allegations of brutality and racism in the LAPD
stemming from the Rodney King beating.
</P>
<P>
   Chaleff said the group will draw expertise from some of the most
experienced people in the field of criminal justice. All members
are volunteers serving without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Drooyan, former chief assistant U.S. attorney in Los
Angeles and deputy general counsel for the Christopher Commission,
and Jeffrey Eglash, inspector general of the LAPD, will oversee
eight work groups that will probe specific areas of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no limits on what this group can do,'' said Drooyan,
who will also be general counsel to the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Panel member Chuck LaBella, former head of the U.S. Justice
Department's Campaign Finance Task Force, told reporters: ''Our
mission is not to become a fig leaf for anyone, to give political
cover. Our mission is to address the systemic problems and change
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not here as enemies of the LAPD,'' he said. ''We are
here to champion the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters questioned the small representation of minorities on
the predominantly white male panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are reaching out to get more representatives of minority
communities,'' Drooyan said. ''We want our work to have credibility
throughout the entire community.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.lapdonline.org/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2045 </TRAILER>
