<BODY>
<HEADLINE> How Elian Deal Went Wrong  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conflicting accounts emerged Wednesday from
nearly all sides involved in the failed deal to reunite Elian
Gonzalez with his father in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Version One: The Miami relatives had agreed to relinquish the
child to the father.
</P>
<P>
   Version Two: The relatives wanted to meet the father only to
talk about what would be best for the child.
</P>
<P>
   Version Three: The family planned to hand over the child and
then talk the father into defecting to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, agreed to a three-hour meeting
with Miami relatives who have been caring for Elian -- to be held at
the Vatican Embassy in Washington Wednesday -- because he was told
they would relinquish custody of Elian before the meeting, his
lawyer Gregory Craig told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we had an agreement that ... would have transferred
custody of Elian Gonzalez smoothly, peacefully and in an orderly
fashion,'' Craig said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the agreement worked out with help from Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., and representatives of the Cuban American
National Federation was that Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez
and cousin Marisleysis Gonzalez would fly to Washington with Elian
on Wednesday morning and transfer custody to the father.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their only requirement was that Juan Miguel Gonzalez would be
willing to talk with the relatives after the transfer for 30
minutes,'' said Craig, adding that they were to travel to
Washington in a government plane.
</P>
<P>
   He said the father agreed to the proposal even though it later
changed several times in the evening. The number of relatives
increased from two to six, they wanted to come on a private charter
and they wanted Juan Miguel to talk to them for 180 minutes rather
than 30, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel accepted this because ''the essential condition that
we cared about -- and that caused us to agree to this proposal
remained unchanged -- that the family meeting would be preceded by
the transfer of Elian's physical and legal custody to his father,''
Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his client were surprised by the uncle's midnight
announcement outside his Miami house that he would not be bringing
the child to Washington on Wednesday. They were also surprised by
the Washington news conference Wednesday morning in which Cuban
American National Foundation chairman Jorge Mas Santos said there
had been no agreement to transfer custody of the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Mas Santos told reporters that there were no conditions to the
family meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The meeting was not to be a handover of Elian,'' he said.
''The meeting was a forum so this family among themselves could
decide as a family what was in the best interest of Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he viewed the meeting as ''a good opportunity for a
family reunion'' among the relatives who have fought for more than
four months for custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli told reporters that the family had, indeed, agreed to
reunite the father and son -- at the Vatican Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the family believed that once they had Juan Miguel on
church property and the chance to talk to him for three hours, he
would agreed to stay in the United States with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what made them back out of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, emotion overcame logic,'' Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there was the false belief by some of the relatives in
Miami that there were still legal options,'' he said. ''And the
large crowd gathered outside the Gonzalez home in Miami turned
against the agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
