<HEADLINE> 13,000-Acre Wildfire Burns in Fla.  </HEADLINE>
By VICKIE CHACHERE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. (AP) -- A 15,400-acre wildfire burned Wednesday
after destroying three mobile homes, forcing evacuations and
closing roads and a school.
</P>
<P>
   Fire crews initially feared ''very aggressive fire behavior'' as
the blaze burned for a fourth day, but wind worked in their favor,
pushing flames into areas that already had burned.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not too bad. That's much slower progress than we have
had all week,'' state forestry spokesman Gerry LaCavera said
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   An elementary school was closed early Wednesday in the area
about 10 miles east of Naples, or 130 miles south of Tampa.
Residents of 50 homes within a mile of the fire were urged to
evacuate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One firefighter suffered heat exhaustion. A fourth brush truck
to be caught by flames was lost Wednesday. None of the trucks'
operators was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the scorched area is now in ''mop-up,'' with
firefighters working to extinguish small embers and flare-ups,
LaCavera said. The operation is expected to continue for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   The area, dotted with papery melaleuca trees and oil-rich
cabbage palms that have increased firefighters' frustration, was
subdivided in the heyday of Florida swampland sales, leaving miles
of paved roads but few houses.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just kind of sitting on pins and needles waiting to see
what's going to happen,'' said Robert Heed, manager of Kountree
Kampinn RV Resort, about 2{ miles from the edge of the burned area.
</P>
<P>
   The fire started Sunday in the Picayune Strand State Forest,
between Naples and the Big Cypress National Preserve and Everglades
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cause had not been determined, firefighters believe
it was sparked by humans.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency on Wednesday agreed to
pay 70 percent of the state's eligible firefighting costs above
$1,520,356.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Florida's emergency department:
http://www.dca.state.fl.us/bpr/EMTOOLS/wildfire/wildfire.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
