<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Halt to Congo Fighting  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Two days before a new cease-fire agreement
takes effect in Congo, the U.N. Security Council urged the warring
parties Wednesday to stop fighting and start pulling back from
their front-line positions.
</P>
<P>
   Council members expressed their readiness to do everything
possible to speed up deployment of a 5,500-strong U.N. observer
mission charged with overseeing the disengagement. But U.N.
officials said that under the most optimistic scenario, it will
take another 2{ to 3{ months to deploy the troops.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Miyet, the undersecretary-general for peacekeeping, told
council members that the Congo government and its allies claim the
rebels and their backers, Rwanda and Uganda, are continuing to
violate last summer's original cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Security Council welcomed last Saturday's
agreement reached in Kampala, Uganda, by the warring parties to
stop fighting and pull back 10 miles from their front-line
positions by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. deputy ambassador Nancy Soderberg called the Kampala
meetings ''promising and encouraging'' and said they offered the
first hopeful sign in Congo in some time.
</P>
<P>
   Council members also discussed their upcoming visit to Congo and
neighboring countries which Canada's U.N. Ambassador Robert Fowler,
the current council president, said is aimed at reinforcing ''the
excellent news'' of the new cease-fire. No date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels took up arms in eastern Congo in Aug. 1998 to oust
Congolese President Laurent Kabila from power. Citing concerns
about security along their borders with Congo, Rwanda and Uganda
backed the rebels, while Kabila enlisted the support of Angola,
Zimbabwe and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   The war has destabilized central Africa and last summer's
cease-fire has been violated by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   In late February, the Security Council authorized a 5,537-strong
U.N. mission -- including 500 military observers and four battalions
of security troops -- to verify that all parties observe the Congo
cease-fire. The council has also been pressing the warring parties
to stop fighting.
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday's adoption of a new plan to disengage the forces,
Miyet told the council that rapid deployment of the U.N. mission
''has acquired additional urgency,'' according to his prepared
remarks for the closed council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged U.N. members Monday to
provide specialized troops so the force can deploy quickly. Miyet
on Wednesday told the council the U.N. troops cannot deploy ''in
conditions of adequate security'' without these units whose need
''is greater than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   These units are needed to prepare and maintain remote airstrips,
provide air traffic control, search and rescue operations, river
patrols, engineering projects, fuel and cargo handling, and medical
duties, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Miyet said he had invited a number of potential
troop-contributing countries to a meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, U.N. officials said just 103 unarmed U.N.
military liaison officers are deployed in nine locations in Congo.
The United Nations only has commitments for two of the four
battalions -- from Pakistan and Senegal -- and Miyet said more
aircraft are needed to deploy troops and equipment throughout the
country because Congo has virtually no roads.
</P>
<P>
   With some 550,000 people displaced by the war, the council
reiterated its concern at the humanitarian situation. It also
appealed to donors to respond to the $73 million U.N. appeal for
Congo which so far has received only $1.2 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
