<HEADLINE> Urich Suing Castle Rock TV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Robert Urich is suing Castle Rock Television
for nearly $1.5 million, claiming his TV series ''Lazarus Man'' was
canceled and he wasn't paid because he had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Urich and his production company entered into an agreement with
Castle Rock in 1995 for Urich to act in the ''Lazarus Man'' pilot,
according to the suit filed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, he was to be paid $70,000 per episode for the
first season and $73,000 an episode the second season.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, Urich informed Castle Rock that he had cancer and
would have to undergo treatment, but the suit said at no time was
Urich unable to perform under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Castle Rock terminated the agreement a month later, the suit
said.
</P>
<P>
   Urich's breach of contract suit, filed in Superior Court, seeks
$1.47 million, the amount he would have received for the second
season of ''Lazarus Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle Rock said in a statement that the company did not
understand the basis for the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We worked very closely with him and only with great reluctance
concluded that we were unable to continue to produce the series
without its star,'' Castle Rock said.
</P>
<P>
   Urich underwent chemotherapy, radiation treatments and two
operations in the mid-1990s to successfully fight synovial cell
sarcoma, a rare cancer that attacks the joints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
