<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford, Texas DMV Battle For Web Site  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE MABIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN (AP) -- Opening statements began Wednesday in a dispute
that could change the way cars are sold over the Internet in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is asking an administrative law judge to allow
the automaker to reopen a used-car Web site shut down by the state
for violating franchise laws, arguing that officials are curtailing
e-commerce opportunities in the nation's second largest market.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Division of Motor Vehicles officials say, however, that
the law that clearly prohibits the direct selling of automobiles
online by Ford or anyone else without a license.
</P>
<P>
   ''When this Internet purpose is to sell used cars directly to
the public, it's a violation of state law,'' said Phillip Layer, an
attorney representing the state. ''It's very clear and simple,'' he
said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Only dealers licensed by the state can sell cars here; brokering
-- arranging a transaction for a fee -- is illegal, officials said.
Licensed dealers can sell cars online.
</P>
<P>
   Ford attorney Kenneth Valka countered that Ford followed Texas
laws that he said are ''difficult, non-defined and in fact, in this
particular case, non-applicable.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Ford is not selling cars over the Internet, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The true fact is that Ford is advertising its pre-owned
vehicles, not selling its pre-owned vehicles,'' Valka said. ''You
will not find one contract to buy a car between Ford and a
customer. Every contract is between the dealer and the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ford fight began in November 1999, when the division sent
Houston Ford and Lincoln Mercury dealers a letter informing them
that they could be fined up to $10,000 a day per violation for
participating in Ford's Pre-Owned Showroom program, which allows
consumers to search for certified used vehicles via a Web site.
Prices are preset by dealers and cannot be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says the actual sale is made by a dealer after customers
choose a vehicle, pay a deposit online and are referred to a local
dealership.
</P>
<P>
   The state contends that Ford -- not a licensed dealer -- is
selling cars directly, thus violating the franchise law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want the site to get up and running again,'' Mecke
said, adding that the company would like to expand the site
statewide. The program has been successful in parts of California,
Georgia, Alabama, New York and New Jersey, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from Ford and some Internet companies say it's a
case of Texas interfering with the growth of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems as if the (Texas Division of Motor Vehicles) is so
preoccupied with constraining auto manufacturers that they've
missed the point that this it is good for the consumers, it's good
for the dealer, it's great for Ford Motor Co.,'' said John H.
Mecke, director of legislative franchise affairs for Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The state also stymied General Motors Corp.'s plans to sell cars
in Texas over the Internet by denying the automotive giant a
dealer's license.
</P>
<P>
   Several dot-coms, which do not have licenses, also have been
prevented from selling online in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Kent, the lead enforcement officer for the Texas Division
of Motor Vehicles testified Wednesday that officials are only doing
their jobs of enforcing the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that it's on the Internet, as far as we're concerned,
is irrelevant. It's the activity that we are not condoning,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kent was the only witness to testify during the 9{ hour hearing,
which was scheduled to resume Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that 750,000 vehicles worth about $19 billion
will be bought online this year, doubling online sales although
representing a small portion of the $350 billion nationwide new-car
business.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen other states have similar laws, but many Internet
dealers have expressed frustration over being locked out of the
Texas market, the nation's second-largest estimated at upward of
$30 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have said the anti-broker law keeps
price-inflating middlemen out of the car business.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers say the laws are fair because they've invested millions
of dollars in their facilities and inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing is the first of as many as five hearings
that may be heard by the Texas DMV before a decision is made -- a
process that could take up to six months, said Gaby Garcia, a
spokeswoman from the Texas Department of Transportation, which
oversees the Texas DMV.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ford.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.dot.state.tx.us/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
