<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recorder From Marine Osprey Found  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARANA, Ariz. (AP) -- Investigators recovered the flight data
recorder from the charred wreckage of an Osprey military aircraft
that crashed during a training exercise, killing 19 Marines,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder, discovered Tuesday, will be taken to the
manufacturer, Smith Industries in Grand Rapids, Mich., where
officials from the Naval Safety Center will translate and analyze
the data. The Pentagon said it wasn't sure how long the process
will take.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they're optimistic that because of the presence of an
aircraft flight data recorder, we may actually be further ahead
than we would be in a military accident,'' said Maj. Patrick G.
Gibbons, a Marine Corps spokesman in Washington. ''Most military
aircraft do not carry such a device.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. David Andersen, a Pentagon spokesman at the crash site near
a rural, Arizona airport, said the recorder should contain
information on what was on the pilot's gauges and instrument panel,
such as speed and oil pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen said nothing has been ruled out a possible cause of
Saturday's crash.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery team Wednesday retrieved the last body left in the
wreckage. The other 18 were recovered Tuesday. All of the bodies
were to be flown to Dover Air Force Base in Delaware for
identification before they are turned over to the families.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage was being loaded onto pallets to be shipped on
three flatbed trucks by Friday to the Marine Corps Air Station in
Yuma, where the flight originated. The wreckage will undergo
further detailed inspection there.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
