<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Thursday as overnight drops
on Wall Street dragged down Japanese high-technology issues. The
U.S. dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 226.95 points,
or 1.09 percent, to 20,606.26 in the first 30 minutes of trading.
On Wednesday, the average closed up 310.69 points, or 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.84 yen, up 0.36 yen from late Wednesday in
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 105.80 yen
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices started lower following another
sharp fall in U.S. high-technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Among early losers were high-technology blue chips, including
Sony, TDK, NEC and Fujitsu.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Nasdaq composite index closed at 3,769.63 on
Wednesday, down 286.27 points, its second worst point drop and its
first close below 4,000 since Jan. 31. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 161.95 points to 11,125.13 at Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 25.01 points, or 1.47 percent, to 1,681.33.
The TOPIX closed up 5.25 points, or 0.31 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar edged higher against the yen in
early Tokyo trading as some investors bought back dollars sold
Wednesday after Bank of Japan Governor Masaru Hayami suggested the
central bank's near 'zero' interest rate policy may be changed. He
did not specify when that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates tend to make a nation's currency more
attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, dealers said they were expecting narrow range-trading
ahead of a weekend meeting of finance officials from major
industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Finance ministers and central bankers from the G-7 -- Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, Canada, the United States and Japan -- will
gather in Washington to discuss global economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 101.51 yen, up from
100.97 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.8350 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7800 percent. Its
price fell 0.45 point to 100.55.
(km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
