<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, April 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No Word on Outcome of Elian Meeting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A meeting between Attorney General Janet Reno and
the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez has ended tonight, but there is no word on
whether a handover agreement has been reached. Reno met with the boy's
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez, at the Miami
Beach home of Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, the nun who was host of a January
meeting between Elian and his grandmothers from Cuba. It was unclear whether
Reno met with the 6-year-old.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Senate Votes To Remove Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- South Carolina state senators today endorsed a bill to
remove the Confederate flag from atop the Statehouse dome. Opponents say the
banner is racist but supporters insist it's a symbol of Southern heritage. The
bill would remove the banner from the dome and place a similar battle flag
behind an existing monument honoring Confederate soldiers on Statehouse grounds.
The flag would fly on the north side of the Statehouse from a pole no taller
than 20 feet. That element was added to satisfy black lawmakers and other flag
opponents who did not want the flag in a prominent position to passers-by.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Stage Set for Run-Off Vote in Peru
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori fell just shy of the majority
needed to avoid a runoff for an unprecedented third term, election officials
said today, setting the stage for a showdown with international economist
Alejandro Toledo. Officials said that after counting 97.68 percent of Sunday's
ballots, Fujimori had 49.84 percent compared to 40.31 percent for Toledo. Jose
Portillo, head of the office in charge of the count, said the most Fujimori
could be expected win at this point was 49.89 percent of the vote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Breast-Implant Suit Arguments Heard
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- A Dow Corning Corp. attorney asked a federal judge today to
set aside a bankruptcy court's opinion the company says modifies and jeopardizes
a $3.2 billion settlement over silicone breast implants. George Tarpley asked
U.S. District Judge Denise Page Hood to vacate federal Bankruptcy Judge Arthur
Spector's December opinion that women opposed to the settlement may sue Dow
Corning's parent companies. Tarpley called Spector's opinion ''an error of law''
that, if allowed to stand, could cripple the settlement that took years to reach
and has been approved by 94 percent of the 112,774 women who last year voted on
it.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N., Cambodia To Resolve Deadlock
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cambodian and U.N. diplomats plan to meet soon in an effort to
end a deadlock over the prosecution of former Khmer Rouge leaders on genocide
charges, the United Nations announced today. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
