<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, Russia to Swap WWII Art  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany and Russia will exchange art looted by
Nazi and Soviet troops during World War II, including pieces from a
Russian czarist palace's legendary Amber Room, officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the swap, scheduled for later this month, is only a
small step forward in resolving disputes over ''trophy art'' that
weigh on relations between the two former enemies even after the
end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Germany still wants Russia to return more than 1 million books,
paintings, coins and other items such as church windows that have
languished in museum basements for more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has generally viewed the captured art as compensation for
the Nazis' wartime devastation. The Amber Room, named after its
wall panels of golden-brown amber, has been high on the list of art
Russia wants back.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in Moscow on April 28, German officials are to
return a mosaic and a chest of drawers that once were in the Amber
Room.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the city of Bremen -- where the mosaic was
discovered -- will get back 101 graphics and watercolors, including
art by Albrecht Duerer, Manet, Goya and Toulouse-Lautrec. The
works, valued in the millions, disappeared from a Bremen museum in
1945.
</P>
<P>
   The Amber Room mosaic was found to be in the possession of a
Bremen man in 1997. After a court ordered him to hand it over to
the city, a local businessman concerned about Germany's image
reportedly paid the man's heirs $100,000 not to sue to reclaim the
art.
</P>
<P>
   The chest of drawers was turned over to the German government by
a woman in Leipzig who recognized it in a 1996 TV report. She said
she bought it in the 1950s from a state antique agency in what was
then communist East Germany -- a Soviet ally.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300-square foot Amber Room was a gift from Prussian King
Frederick William to Peter the Great in the early 18th century. It
was installed in a palace the czar built for his wife, Catherine I,
outside St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Retreating Nazi troops looted the palace in World War II and the
Amber Room was moved to a castle in Koenigsberg, now the Russian
city of Kaliningrad. It disappeared from there in 1945 and most of
the amber panels have never resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Both Nazi and Soviet troops systematically stripped valuables
and shipped them home during World War II. The looted art has been
a regular irritant in German-Russian relations over the last
decade, at times leading to top-level diplomacy by former leaders
Helmut Kohl and Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most controversial items is the Trojan gold that the
Red Army carried from Berlin to Moscow at the end of the war. The
German government has demanded the return of the gold, which Moscow
long denied having, but then put on display in a museum in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The treasure was excavated by German archaeologist Heinrich
Schliemann in 1873, who believed that it once belonged to the king
of the ancient city of Troy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
