S.C. Senate Votes To Remove Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- South Carolina state senators today endorsed a bill to
remove the Confederate flag from atop the Statehouse dome. Opponents say the
banner is racist but supporters insist it's a symbol of Southern heritage. The
bill would remove the banner from the dome and place a similar battle flag
behind an existing monument honoring Confederate soldiers on Statehouse grounds.
The flag would fly on the north side of the Statehouse from a pole no taller
than 20 feet. That element was added to satisfy black lawmakers and other flag
opponents who did not want the flag in a prominent position to passers-by.
</P>
