<HEADLINE> War Criminal Gets Russia Citizenship  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin on Wednesday granted
Russian citizenship to Vasily Kononov, a Latvian convicted this
year of war crimes as a World War II Soviet partisan, the
presidential press service announced.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's move was not likely to have direct legal effect on the
case but underlined Russia's protest over the conviction. The
Kremlin has called the conviction discrimination against an ethnic
Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Kononov, 77, is serving a six-year sentence for ordering the
execution of nine civilians, some of whom were burned alive, when
he was a Soviet partisan fighting the Nazis who occupied Latvia in
1941-44.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, officials protested Latvia's refusal to allow
Russian doctors to examine Kononov, saying the Baltic country's
hard line in the case ''proves the complete disregard of Latvian
powers to acknowledge universal humanitarian principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Latvia have been at odds since the 1991 collapse of
the Soviet Union over Latvia's treatment of its large ethnic
Russian community and over Latvia's prosecution of fighters on the
Soviet side.
</P>
</TEXT>
