<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Blasts U.S. on Tuna Imports  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican authorities said Wednesday a U.S.
federal court ruling on ''dolphin-safe'' labels that effectively
extends the U.S. ban on Mexican tuna was unfair and uninformed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great loss for Mexico,'' said Dalia de la Pena Wing,
spokeswoman for the Secretariat of Environment, Natural Resources
and Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson on Tuesday blocked the
Clinton administration's attempts to loosen standards for
''dolphin-safe'' tuna, a label fishermen need to sell their fish in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The change would have given the designation to the method of
catching tuna Mexican fishermen use, even though they often trap
dolphins in the same nets used to snare tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico argues its industry does not harm the dolphins because
they are immediately released from the nets.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling ''disregards all the scientific evidence that the
U.S. government presented with the backing and participation of
many serious environmental groups,'' a statement from the
environment secretariat said. It was ''not only unfair, but clearly
uninformed.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed by environmental activists arguing that
the labeling change weakened U.S. laws protecting dolphins.
Henderson ruled the U.S. Commerce Department improperly concluded
the change would have no significant adverse impact on dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department issued a news release Wednesday
expressing disappointment in the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a consensus among many environmental groups ... that
our actions are the right thing to do to protect dolphins during
tuna fishing operations,'' Secretary of Commerce William M. Daley
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only incentive that the international fishing fleet has is
access to our markets. If they can't sell their tuna here, they'll
sell it to countries that do not require the same labeling
standards. And the environmental groups that support us also
understand this concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace's Mexico chapter said the ban has promoted the
expansion of other more devastating practices, such as the killing
of thousands of small marine species used for bait in catching
''dolphin safe'' tuna.
</P>
<P>
   The group's statement urged authorities ''not to pass off
protectionist measures in the name of conservation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has been battling for nine years to re-enter the U.S.
market after being banned because of concerns about the dolphins.
Officials estimate the embargo has cost the country $50 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ban, Mexico exported more than 80,000 tons of tuna a
year to the United States. It exports less than 20,000 tons to
Japan and Europe, while the remaining 125,000 tons of tuna fished
annually from Mexican waters is sold domestically.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities last year agreed to lift the embargo, but no
Mexican tuna has been allowed into the United States because none
qualified for the ''dolphin safe'' label.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2313 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0249 </DOCNO>
