<HEADLINE> James Vorenberg Dies at 72  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA VOZZELLA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- James Vorenberg, a former Harvard Law School dean
and associate special prosecutor during Watergate, died Wednesday.
He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg served as law school dean from 1981 to 1989 and taught
criminal law and legal ethics at Harvard at the time of his death.
He suffered a heart attack Monday and was admitted to Massachusetts
General Hospital, where he died Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg served as Watergate Special Prosecutor Archibald Cox's
principal assistant from 1973 to 1975. He often said his biggest
claim to fame came when reporters at a news conference asked Cox a
question he did not want to answer. ''Talk to my lawyer,'' Cox
said, pointing to Vorenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg served as director of the Justice Department's office
of criminal justice under Attorney General Robert Kennedy. His
responsibilities included encouraging the FBI to improve its
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''The notion that a Harvard professor was going to affect J.
Edgar Hoover in any way struck me as pretty optimistic,'' Vorenberg
told the Harvard alumni magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg co-authored a cookbook called ''Dean Cuisine, Or, the
Liberated Man's Guide to Fine Cooking,'' with Jack Greenberg, then
vice dean of Columbia Law School. The book received a positive
review from his friend and fellow Cambridge resident Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   Born Jan. 10, 1928, Vorenberg earned his undergraduate and
graduate degrees from Harvard. He served as a law clerk to Supreme
Court Justice Felix Frankfurter from 1953 to 1954. He joined the
Harvard faculty in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg leaves a wife and several children. Funeral
arrangements were pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2317 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
