<HEADLINE> Stars 2, Oilers 1  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Stars are trying to defend their
Stanley Cup with the same boring style that won it. The only
difference is they now have a few new faces playing it.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Lyashenko, a 20-year-old rookie forward who earned his
keep by playing the defense-first system coach Ken Hitchcock
demands, scored the tiebreaking goal with 8:29 left to give Dallas
a 2-1 victory over Edmonton in the playoff opener Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 is Thursday night at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers tied it seven minutes into the final period when
Roman Titov stole a clearing pass from Darryl Sydor and fired it
past Stars goalie Ed Belfour. It was the first playoff goal against
Belfour in 123:30, a streak that began with the Cup-clinching
triple-overtime victory against Buffalo last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keane gave Dallas a 1-0 lead late in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour had it easy this time as his defense limited the Oilers
to 14 shots. Edmonton went 15:50 into the second period without
taking a shot and had just three in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   The one-goal Dallas victory has been a trend when these teams
meet -- and they meet often.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, facing the Oilers in a fourth straight postseason,
have beaten Edmonton in eight straight playoff games. Dallas has
won 10 in a row at Reunion Arena. Since the Oilers eliminated the
Stars from the 1997 playoffs, Dallas holds an 18-2-1 advantage. The
Stars' last eight victories have been by one goal.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers goalie Tommy Salo stopped 30 shots, usually smothering or
catching them to prevent the Stars from taking second chances.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas blew several scoring opportunities by missing on
centering passes or sending it into open ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars finally broke through with 7:28 left in the second
when Keane slid the puck between the legs of Jason Smith, who had
just turned it over near Edmonton's blue line, and flipped it over
Salo's left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner poked in a rebound of a shot by Brenden
Morrow later in the period, but it was waved off because Scott
Thornton was caught holding during Morrow's shot.
</P>
<P>
   Lyashenko, who had six goals in 58 regular-season games, was in
the right place at the right time for his first postseason goal.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton's Igor Ulanov was trying to clear a great stick save by
Salo, but instead put the puck right on the Russian rookie's stick.
He flicked it towards the goal and Salo, who was still sprawled on
the ice, never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The goal by Titov was his first for the Oilers since being
acquired at the trading deadline from Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2317 </TRAILER>
