<HEADLINE> Ky. Teen Survives 100-Foot Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- A teen-age runaway fell 100-feet down a
cliff, broke both arms, shattered a hip and then lay in the
underbrush for four days.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, 17-year-old Harold Chandler Jr. managed to
crawl 50 feet on his elbows to the edge of the Cumberland River,
where a fisherman finally heard his cries for help.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Kentucky Hospital, with his mother at his
side, Chandler said Tuesday that he couldn't recall which had been
worse -- the pain or the fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said 'Lord, if you let me make it through, I'll never run
away again.'''
</P>
<P>
   The spot where Chandler fell on March 26 was near the bank of
the Cumberland River in Pulaski County. A few hours earlier, he'd
run away from the Kentucky Baptist Home for Children, a home for
students with discipline problems.
</P>
<P>
   He was sent there four months ago after being expelled from
Lexington Day Treatment Center, which handles students who have had
problems in other special education programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
