<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom To Sell Debt Securities  </HEADLINE>
By MATT MOORE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- MCI WorldCom hopes to sell $15 billion in
debt securities, the proceeds of which would go toward corporate
expenses and upgrading its national and international networks.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed a request Wednesday for advance approval from
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Drake Johnstone, an analyst with Richmond, Va.-based Davenport &AMP;
Co., said MCI's shelf filing gives it the flexibility to decide how
much it sells and when.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the next few years MCI WorldCom will have to spend a lot
of money both deploying more networks to support its growth in the
Internet and also to expand its international network,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the filing, MCI would use the proceeds of the sale
for more acquisitions, paying down existing debt, and other
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   MCI is in the process of upgrading its existing networks and
plans to establish a national fixed wireless network. The moves
come as the company prepares to offer residential users access to
cable and high speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone said MCI, which currently focuses on corporate
clients, could use some of the revenue from the sale to beef up its
national infrastructure and increase its revenue stream by making
its network available to residential consumers during evening
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to capture more spending from the residential side
because that additional traffic tends to be in the evening,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of MCI's traffic is business-related and is done during
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton-based MCI WorldCom is the second-largest
telecommunications company in the United States. It is acquiring
Kansas City-based Sprint Corp. in a deal worth $115 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders with both companies are scheduled to vote on the
merger April 28. The deal also requires approval by U.S. and
European regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MCI WorldCom fell $1 to close at $41.37{ at 4 p.m.
Wednesday on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: MCI WorldCom: http://www.wcom.com
</P>
</TEXT>
