<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Peru Runoff Vote  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department welcomed Peru's
announcement Wednesday that a presidential runoff will be
necessary, calling it a first step toward restoring credibility to
the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   The department commented shortly after Peru announced that
President Alberto Fujimori had failed to win an absolute majority,
thus requiring a runoff election with leading contender Alejandro
Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   A department spokeswoman, asking not to be identified, said the
outcome corresponded to the findings of five separate independent
monitoring groups and polling firms.
</P>
<P>
   She urged that the Peruvian government and electoral officials
''take every possible measure'' to ensure a free and fair process
in the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, department spokesman James P. Rubin had said
the United States would have ''serious, serious questions'' if the
final vote count showed Fujimori with more than 50 percent support,
contradicting the findings of the independent analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin spoke before the final returns were announced.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do expect there to be a second round,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is convincing proof of fraud, ''the government of Peru
will face a substantial challenge in restoring its credibility, not
only with the people of Peru but with the international community
and the United States government,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was premature to speculate on what measures the
United States would take if it were convinced the election was
fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department: http://www.state.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
