<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJ. Emmett Clair:
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALOS HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) -- J. Emmett Clair, a meatpacker whose
early patronage of Green Bay football helped establish the NFL
team's name, died Sunday of pneumonia. He was 102.
</P>
<P>
   Clair went to Green Bay in 1919 to join his brother in running
the Acme Packing Co. That was when he was approached by Curly
Lambeau's father to sponsor a local team.
</P>
<P>
   Clair agreed, and Acme obtained a franchise in the American
Professional Football Association. But that only lasted for the two
years the elder Clair remained in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   When the Clair brothers left Green Bay, Lambeau took over the
team and obtained a franchise in the NFL. But he kept the Packers
name.
James Marston Fitch:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- James Marston Fitch, an architect whose writings
and teachings helped further the cause of preservationists, died
Monday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch said respect for older buildings made environmental and
economic sense. He was recognized for popularizing the preservation
of historical buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch was the director of historic preservation at Beyer Blinder
Belle, the Manhattan architectural firm that recently completed a
renovation of Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after World War II, Fitch was an editor at
Architectural Record, Architectural Forum and House Beautiful in
New York. His books include ''Architecture and the Esthetics of
Plenty'' (1961) and ''Historic Preservation: Curatorial Management
of the Built World'' (1982).
Robert W. Komer:
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Robert W. Komer, a leader of the Johnson
administration's attempts to win hearts and minds in Vietnam who
earned the nickname ''Blowtorch Bob'' for his fiery defense of
American involvement in the region, died Sunday after suffering a
stroke. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Komer had been an aide to Gen. William C. Westmoreland, who
commanded U.S. forces in Vietnam from 1964 to 1968.
</P>
<P>
   President Johnson put Komer in charge of the program known as
pacification, the use of information and propaganda to gain
political and social control of South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Komer produced a stream of statistics to support his view that
the war could be won.
</P>
<P>
   Though Komer was convinced at the time that the United States
could win in Vietnam, he said many years later that the war was ''a
strategic disaster which cost us 57,000 lives and a half trillion
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1968, Johnson named Komer ambassador to Turkey. He
was replaced in January 1969 when Richard Nixon became president.
Diane Marie Munso:
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Diane Marie Munso, a Department of
Corrections manager who helped oversee California's $5 billion
prison building program, died April 6 of colon cancer. She was 50.
</P>
<P>
   Munso, chief of the prison system's construction support branch,
was honored in 1991 by then-Gov. George Deukmejian for outstanding
dedication and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Munso was a member of the Holy Spirit School board, was a parent
service coordinator at St. Francis High School and team mother for
the High Voltage volleyball club.
</P>
<P>
   Munso began her state government career as an entry-level clerk
at the Department of Motor Vehicles during her first year at
California State University, Sacramento.
Pete Springer:
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- State Sen. Pete Springer, a champion of
education and a critic of prison privatization who represented the
25th District for 12 years, died Wednesday of an apparent heart
attack. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved a resolution honoring Springer for his years
of public service.
</P>
<P>
   Springer was chairman of the Senate Government Operations
Committee, treasurer of the Senate Democratic Caucus and a member
of select oversight committees on education and children and youth.
</P>
<P>
   Among Springer's education fights, the former teacher and
principal opposed a bill last year that would have allowed only
school officials, not police, to conduct strip-searches when they
suspected a student was carrying a weapon.
James Vorenberg:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- James Vorenberg, a former Harvard Law School dean
and associate special prosecutor during Watergate, died Wednesday
of a heart attack. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his self-deprecating wit and his cooking skills,
Vorenberg co-authored a cookbook called ''Dean Cuisine, Or, the
Liberated Man's Guide to Fine Cooking,'' with Jack Greenberg, then
vice dean of Columbia Law School. The book received a positive
review from his friend and fellow Cambridge resident Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg served as law school dean from 1981 to 1989 and,
despite a long battle with Parkinson's disease, taught criminal law
and legal ethics at Harvard at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg served as Watergate Special Prosecutor Archibald Cox's
principal assistant from 1973 to 1975. He often said his biggest
claim to fame came when reporters at a news conference asked Cox a
question he did not want to answer. ''Talk to my lawyer,'' Cox
said, pointing to Vorenberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
