<HEADLINE> Aid Groups: Protect Civilians  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- International aid groups are urging the
Security Council to prioritize the protection of civilians in wars,
with one group suggesting council members waive veto power when
considering the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors Without Borders on Wednesday echoed a recent
recommendation from a U.N. University Study that the five permanent
members lose their veto power if the threat of veto impedes council
action to prevent a massive humanitarian catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's president, Dr. James Orbinski, noted that
veto power prevented U.N. action in Rwanda in 1994 and is currently
hindering U.N. action to protect civilians in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Security Council must recognize and insist that the
humanitarian must remain independent of the political,'' Orbinski
said.
</P>
<P>
   The five permanent Security Council members -- the United States,
Britain, France, Russia and China -- can veto any Security Council
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The calls came in an unusual closed meeting of the 15-member
council with aid groups such as Doctors Without Borders, Oxfam and
CARE International, who briefed ambassadors on their experiences
protecting innocents during war.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Smith-Lomas, emergencies director for Oxfam Great Britain,
said the aid groups welcomed the opportunity to address the
council.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we must remember to focus on the fact that what we need to
see is a change in protection and the change in people's lives on
the ground,'' he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council is scheduled to hold an open debate on the
topic of protecting civilians next Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
