<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates 6, Expos 4  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- There aren't many better hitters in a pinch
than John Vander Wal -- not now, not ever.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Wal hit his second homer in three pinch-hit at-bats this
season, a three-run drive that rallied the Pittsburgh Pirates past
the Montreal Expos 6-4 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Wal's sixth-inning shot off reliever Miguel Batista
overcame a 4-3 deficit and was his 15th career pinch-homer, and his
second in nine days. He had a two-run homer in the opener against
Houston on April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Wal, acquired from San Diego for Al Martin to upgrade
what was one of the NL's worst benches last season, moved into
sixth place in career pinch-homers and ninth place with 110 career
pinch-hits.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Expos manager Felipe Alou waved a stat sheet showing
Vander Wal hit a remarkable .522 last season with an 0-1 count --
normally, a situation where the pitcher is in control.
</P>
<P>
   ''What was the count when he hit the home run?'' Alou said.
''0-and-1. And there wasn't a whole lot we could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as he did in the opener, Vander Wal came off the bench to
homer in temperatures that had dipped into the 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Or, actually, he came out of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it's cold like this, I watch one inning, then go back and
take some hacks against the pitching machine,'' Vander Wal said.
''There's no way I can stay loose sitting in the dugout in
35-degree weather. I did the same thing when I played in Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou wasn't surprised to see Pirates manager Gene Lamont use his
best pinch-hitter relatively early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the right way to do it,'' Alou said. ''You never know
if you're going to get another man on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Batista (0-1), a former Rule 5 pick who spent a few weeks with
the Pirates in 1992, replaced starter Carl Pavano to start the
sixth and quickly struck out Wil Cordero and Warren Morris. He then
got ahead in the count 0-and-2 before walking Aramis Ramirez, who
was 1-for-15, and Chad Hermansen singled.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Wal then lifted an opposite-field drive over the
left-center field wall, helping end the Pirates' three-game losing
streak and the Expos' three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, in danger of falling into last place in the NL
Central, had lost five of seven and the Expos had won five of six
following an 0-2 start.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano pitched much better than he did in allowing 15 earned
runs in four innings in two starts against Pittsburgh last season.
But he couldn't hold a 3-1 lead as left fielder Rondell White's
error led to a two-run fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Cabrera's two-run double in fifth off Francisco Cordova
had put Montreal ahead. But Pavano walked Jason Kendall with one
out in the bottom half and Pat Meares' single glanced off White's
glove and bounded nearly to the wall, scoring Kendall and sending
Meares to third.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Giles, who had a run-scoring double in the second,
followed with a sacrifice fly. Giles' long drive in the second
ricocheted off the yellow stripe atop the right field wall and
probably missed by an inch of being a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova breezed through the first three innings on a chilly
night, giving him 10 hitless innings in his first 11 as a starter
this season. He pitched 7 1-3 no-hit innings against Houston on
Thursday before yielding two hits.
</P>
<P>
   But Cordova hurt himself by failing to handle Jose Vidro's
bouncer in the fourth for an error that led to Vladimir Guerrero's
run-scoring grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Silva (1-0) got the final two outs in the sixth for the
victory. Jason Christiansen followed with 1 2-3 scoreless innings,
and Mike Williams got the final four outs for the Pirates' first
save this season. Williams had a 14.48 ERA in the final six weeks
of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to get him back to where he was before the All-Star
break last season,'' Lamont said. ''We'll give some other guys a
chance to save games, but he's earned the right to get the
opportunity now.''
</P>
<P>
Notes: The gametime temperature was 46, and it kept dropping. The
temperature has been in the 40s for four of the Pirates' five home
games. ... Cabrera is 3-for-4 against Cordova. ... Pavano's career
ERA against Pittsburgh prior to Wednesday was 33.75. ... Guerrero
has not struck out in 56 at-bats since Sept. 25. ... The Pirates
had lost three of their first four at home. ... ... Kendall was in
a 4-for-21 slump before getting two hits. Lamont said he didn't
rest Kendall because the catcher gets too anxious and nervous when
he sits during a slump.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-12-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000412.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Meeting With Elian Kin Ends  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX VEIGA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno took an
extraordinary step to resolve the Elian Gonzalez case Wednesday,
flying to Miami and personally urging his relatives to end the
wrenching 4{-month custody struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Reno met for 2{ hours with the boy's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez
and cousin Marisleysis at the Miami Beach home of Sister Jeanne
O'Laughlin, the nun who was host of a January meeting between Elian
and his grandmothers from Cuba. Elian attended the meeting, moving
from lap to lap at the table.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting ended without a concrete agreement to hand him over,
O'Laughlin said. She said the family and Reno were cordial.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very respectful and they were very honest,''
O'Laughlin said. ''The pain of this family and their understanding
of the pain of Juan Miguel was very evident. They have expressed
over and over again their ... desire to be a loving family, whole
again.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no deadline issued and no letter delivered detailing
handover plans, though O'Laughlin said there was talk of a meeting
Thursday in Washington involving the Miami relatives. She said
attorneys for the two sides would speak late Wednesday or early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One option Reno had planned to propose was for Elian and some of
his Miami relatives to come back to Washington, perhaps even on her
plane, to arrange a meeting with the boy's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, and the eventual transfer of custody, according to a
government official, who requested anonymity. Reno left the meeting
without commenting, and immigration officials refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''She wants to do anything possible to resolve this,'' Justice
Department spokesman Myron Marlin said before the meeting. ''She
realizes it's a tall order but believes she may be the one who can
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris
Meissner also attended the meeting. Elian left the room only when
the subject matter with Reno was too sensitive. ''He was precious
with her,'' O'Laughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his relatives had left their politically charged
Little Havana neighborhood for O'Laughlin's gated home earlier in
the day. She said Elian would stay there Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The visit at least temporarily postponed the letter the
government had planned to send the Miami relatives Wednesday
telling them where and when to relinquish custody of Elian.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official, requesting anonymity, said before
the meeting that if Reno and the family could agree on transfer
plans, the letter wouldn't be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Under a government plan, Elian would be transferred either to
his father or another great-uncle, who would take the boy to meet
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Reno had also planned to meet with community leaders in her
hometown, where she served as state attorney for 15 years and where
Cuban exiles now wield signs denouncing her and depicting her with
horns.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, clinging to an inner tube, was rescued by two fishermen
on Thanksgiving after his mother and 10 other Cubans drowned when
their boat sank.
</P>
<P>
   His Miami relatives have been caring for him ever since and have
been fighting in court for him to have an asylum hearing. But the
Clinton administration has ordered Elian back to his father in
Cuba, saying only he can speak for the boy on immigration matters.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge affirmed that decision, but the family has
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, who met with Reno after coming to America last
week, remained in Bethesda, Md. He indicated Wednesday -- the day
after a meeting in Washington with the Miami relatives was
scheduled and abruptly canceled -- that he was through negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is going to simply ask now that the attorney general issue
a court order and that the boy be returned immediately to him,''
said the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, who met with him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, his wife and their infant son were
guests of honor at a reception at the Cuban diplomatic mission in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Havana, Ricardo Alarcon, the senior Cuban official who has
advised the father, criticized the Miami relatives for delaying the
transfer, saying they were showing ''a total lack of respect for
American society,'' and ''making fun of the U.S. government.''
</P>
<P>
   When O'Laughlin first got involved, she said she had no opinion
about whether the boy should be returned. But after the
grandmothers' visit, she said Elian should stay in the United
States -- drawing bitter criticism from the Cuban government and the
grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   If Elian's relatives were hoping for a quieter setting in Miami
Beach, they only partially succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   While Reno met with the family, dozens of police and federal
agents kept watch over about 200 demonstrators. Several waved a
Cuban flag bigger than a king-sized bedsheet.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Elian arrived at the house, a crowd chanted ''Elian!
Elian!'' in anticipation. The demonstrators were forced to keep a
greater distance than on Lazaro Gonzalez's narrow street. Police
kept them across a four-lane road, behind a median and a barricade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Reno, coward, Miami has had enough!'' some shouted. Reno left
in a motorcade that included 12 police motorcycles and a dozen
cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   At Lazaro Gonzalez's house, protesters were starting to
acknowledge that Elian may be heading back to Cuba. But the
attorney general's visit to Miami gave some a ray of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now she's not the Cuban-Americans' best friend, but that
could change between today and tomorrow,'' said Rolando Millet, 39.
He held a sign: ''America get ready for a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   AP Writer Michael J. Sniffen contributed to this report from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
