<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Mass. Students Boycott Tests  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE IVEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- While some students sharpened their No.
2 pencils, others sharpened their rhetoric Wednesday and boycotted
a statewide achievement test they consider unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's 17 hours that justify whether or not you can get a high
school diploma from the state for your four years of high school,''
said Sarah Bowman, one of 23 Brookline High School students who
refused to take the test.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third year the Massachusetts Comprehensive
Assessment System exam has been administered. The composition
portion was given to all fourth-, eighth- and 10th-graders
Wednesday. Math, science and social studies will be tested in May.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's scores showed more than half of all students either
flunked the MCAS or need improvement. Schools that consistently do
poorly could face state takeover, and in 2003, the state will
require students to pass the exam in order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters said the test is unfair to poor test-takers,
poorly funded schools, and special education students and should
not be the sole requirement to graduate. The boycotters faced
repercussions ranging from suspension to agreeing to write about
the test.
</P>
<P>
   State education officials estimated that less than 1 percent of
the 220,000 students scheduled to take the test Wednesday
participated in the boycott.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were very few cases of students boycotting the test,''
Education Commissioner David Driscoll said in a statement. ''Those
cases in my view are minor, and schools were orderly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
