<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By MELANIE CARROLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- One man is dead and another was injured
following a shootout Wednesday with an off-duty police officer who
was moonlighting as a security guard at a downtown Brooklyn
clothing store, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen or more shots were fired, but it was not known how many
were fired by the officer or who had fired first. At least one of
the two suspects had a weapon, said Assistant Chief Joseph
Esposito, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at 5:48 p.m. at the Jimmy Jazz clothing
store at Hanover Place and Fulton Street, Esposito said. The
store's alarm sounded when the two suspects entered the store,
causing the officer to respond, thinking it may have been a
possible shoplifting incident, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, who was not immediately identified, confronted the
suspects, words were exchanged, and a fight ensued. At least one of
the suspects produced a weapon and gunfire was exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The officer apparently shot one suspect in the chest. The
suspect -- identified as Malcolm Burno, 17, of Brooklyn -- was
pronounced dead at Brooklyn Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The other suspect, who was not immediately identified, was shot
in the leg and fled into a dark-colored car, apparently after
picking up the dead suspect's gun. He was later apprehended at
Bellevue Hospital, where he had checked himself in, Esposito said.
</P>
<P>
   A store employee, standing in back of the store, was shot in the
leg and taken to St. Vincent's Hospital in Manhattan, where he was
in stable condition. It was not immediately clear who shot him. The
police officer, who was given permission from department officials
to work at the store, sustained several facial injuries, Esposito
said. The 29-year-old officer is assigned to the 71st Precinct in
Flatbush, Brooklyn. He does not have any prior police shootings and
has a clean record.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking police source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said police were investigating whether the suspects were
part of a gang that sets off alarms upon entering stores. The scam
works like this, the source said: when the alarm goes off, store
employees see that the suspects have no merchandise. After
shoplifting, the suspects leave the store, setting off the alarm
again, but the store employees, believing the alarm is going off
erroneously, let the suspects leave.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a man opened fire outside the Jimmy Jazz store,
wounding eight people.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's incident was the latest shooting involving police
officers. The shootings have sparked a public outcry in the city
and led to intense scrutiny of police practices. The U.S. Civil
Rights Commission is considering whether to recommend an
independent federal monitor to oversee the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, four white undercover officers shot unarmed West
African immigrant Amadou Diallo on his Bronx doorstep, prompting a
month of daily protests outside police headquarters in which more
than 1,200 people were arrested, including elected officials and
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   The acquittal of those officers in February by an Albany jury
angered many who said it sent the wrong message to police. Shortly
after that verdict, another unarmed black man, Patrick Dorismond,
was fatally shot in a botched drug sting in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The officer and both suspects in Wednesday's shooting are black.
</P>
<P>
   Many criticized Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's statements in the wake
of the Dorismond shooting. He did not express sympathy to
Dorismond's family and he and Police Commissioner Howard Safir
released the dead man's criminal record -- including a sealed
juvenile record -- as they defended the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Those actions appeared to have an impact on Giuliani's public
support, giving his U.S. Senate opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, a
boost in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Anger bubbled over into violence between civilians and officers
outside Dorismond's funeral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
